badia ghati'a al-jabiri stood disconsolately outside what was left of his downtown hotel after it was hit by a soviet-made katyusha rocket fired by iranian revolutionary guards a few miles to the east
i'll need a fortune to get it repaired,'' he lamented as he viewed the facade tuesday. the front wall had collapsed into the street. ``but thank god nobody was hurt.''
al-jabiri's ibn kholdoun hotel was empty because most people have fled to safer areas out of reach of the relentless iranian bombardment
basra, once iraq's second-largest city, once again is taking a hammering in the renewed ``war of the city'' between iran and iraq. it has borne the brunt of the iranian bombardment of border cities
al-jabiri is like many basrans who are defying the iranian barrages and staying in their city after 7{ years of war
shells and missiles hit the city day and night. the iranians are dug in a scant six miles east of the city that straddles the shatt al-arab waterway
it is formed by the confluence of the euphrates and tigris rivers that forms the southern border between iraq and iran
official statistics released this month in baghdad showed that basra was hit by iranian artillery and missiles 179 times last year. most of the 776 civilians listed as killed in iraqi cities last year died in basra, the report said
al-jabiri lives with his wife, 10 children and his mother in the andalus district. he said they have no intention of leaving
where would we go?'' he said. ``i was born in this city, my kids have grown up here and know no other place. if we're going to die, then let us die here.''
in the latest round of missile, air and artillery attacks that began sunday after a short-lived cease-fire, officials said eight civilians have been killed in basra and 20 others wounded. the low casualty rate was because most of the basrans who are toughing it out live in shelters or basements
but the city's governor, anwar omar al-hadithi told reporters basra that nearly 50 civilians have been killed and 250 wounded since feb. 29
in that period, he said, 164 houses, 49 shops and 150 vehicles have been destroyed and 200 residences badly damaged
the iranians have fired nearly 3,000 shells and 183 short-range rockets into basra in that time, he said
despite the destruction, life goes on normally in several part of the city, with shops, government offices and the university open
the barrage has hit mosques, schools and hospitals in the ancient city, founded by caliph omer bin al-khatab in 637 a.d. and reputedly the starting point for the legendary voyages of sinbad the sailor
some basrans, especially those in the hardest-hit central section of town, have sought shelter in nearby towns or in the city's western outskirts
the authorities make no attempt to stop those who want to leave but supply temporary pre-fabricated homes for anyone who wants one on basra's western edge
if they want to leave they can go anywhere they like,'' al-hadithi said at his heavily sandbagged headquarters. ``if they want to stay they can stay.''
al-hadithi estimated that 40 percent of the pre-war population of more than 1.5 million has left the city in recent years, leaving about 870,000 people
many basrans were caught by the latest round of shelling. they had just returned to their homes believing that the cease-fire would hold, but it lasted only two days
the renewed bombardment put many basrans on the run again
we thought that the shelling had stopped so we went back home,'' said jassim jabar najim, 67. ``i even reopened my shop and arranged to start business again when a shell hit near the shop and i was hit in the hip by sharpnel.''
najim, interviewed from his bed in basra's general hospital, said he has repaired his house four times, ``but this time i'm going to leave it until the war is over.''
as he spoke, shells exploded in the eastern part of the city
israel is arresting arab activists like pharmacist assad saftawi, some of whom may have done nothing illegal, in its effort to end three months of violence in the occupied territories
saftawi, 53, also is headmaster of a an elementary school run by the united nations in the bureij refugee camp. he joined the fundamentalist moslem brotherhood as a youth in egypt and later spent four years in an israeli jail for working with the palestine liberation organization
alaa, his 25-year-old son, said five israeli soldiers took saftawi from the stone house on a dirt street of gaza city's sabra district sunday, adding him to a growing list of palestinians being held without trial for up to six months
authorities use administrative detention as part of its effort to break the rebellion, which palestinians call ``the uprising,'' that began dec. 8 in the west bank and gaza strip
the army reported 212 detentions up to feb. 26. the arab-run human rights group law in the service of man put the number at 232 through march 13, compared with 193 for all of 1987
it is used as an attempt to take out any potential leadership the community might have,'' said fatah azzem, a member of the group based in the west bank town of ramallah. ``it is a method of punishment for people who are active and not necessarily illegally active.''
the army confirmed saftawi was in administrative detention, but a spokesman would not say what he had done or what threat he was thought to pose
saftawi, a squarely built man who favors the long arab robe called the djellaba, is an ardent nationalist who was severely critical of occupation in an interview a few days before his arrest
as another son served glasses of tea and tiny blue cups of strong, sweet coffee, saftawi spoke with pride of his second son imad, a member of a fundamentalist organization. he has six sons and three daughters
imad, 24, became a local hero in gaza after escaping from jail and making his way abroad last year. saftawi credits his his son and imad's friends with setting the stage for the rebellion
by their actions and their success they gave confidence to the palestinian people to depend on themselves, to be self-sufficient,'' saftawi said during the interview in his diwan, or arab-style reception room
he contrasted the confidence of youth to the passivity of those who were adults when israel captured the territories from jordan and egypt in the 1967 middle east war
we were deceived, believing that the arabs or islam or the united nations would do something for us,'' he said, ``but this group made people believe we could depend on ourselves. they planted the seed of something new.''
the pharmacist and teacher was candid in criticizing the plo, which he said encouraged palestinians to await deliverance from the outside
there is no doubt that the plo's original leadership belongs to the older generation and was captive to old ideas, especially the idea that we as palestinian people were unable to do anything,'' he said
his comments had an element of self-criticism because saftawi, by his own account, has been associated with the plo for more than three decades
in the early 1950s in cairo, he was in the moslem brotherhood, a fundamentalist group founded by hassan al banna in 1929. ``i belonged to the only group at the time that was willng to make sacrifices,'' saftawi said
egyptian authorities cracked down on the brotherhood in 1955 so saftawi and fellow students like yasser arafat and salah khalaf, now the top two plo leaders, formed a new faction
their group, the nucleus arafat's future fatah guerrillas, made raids into israel but saftawi said he did not participate in them
saftawi was arrested in 1973, six years after israel took gaza from egypt, and convicted of handling plo funds. he spent four years in jail
imad was 9 at the time and took on responsibility for feeding the family by working at odd jobs, saftawi said
he became the breadwinner for the whole family and took care of my parents,'' the father said. ``if i count the hours i saw my son while i was in jail it was not more than 10.''
saftawi said imad went to the islamic university in gaza city and joined the moslem brotherhood, then formed his own group. switzerland</head>
defense secretary frank c. carlucci was monitoring events in central america while in the swiss capital for meetings with his soviet counterpart, aides say
carlucci discussed nicaragua in general terms with soviet defense minister dmitri yazov on wednesday, said a pentagon spokesman, but it was not clear how deeply they delved into that issue
dan howard, the pentagon spokesman, told reporters that ``regional issues were discussed .... angola, afghanistan, nicaragua, korea.'' but he declined to disclose the substance of the talks
carlucci and yazov met for 10 minutes with only their translators present at the beginning of an afternoon session at the soviet embassy, but the topic of that conversation remained secret
aides to carlucci worked through the night wednesday and early today, remaining in close contact with the pentagon and white house. they declined, however, to divulge the secretary's exact role in the decision to send 3,200 u.s. troops to honduras for what the white house called ``an emergency deployment readiness exercise''
investigators are looking for a prime-time prowler who slips into homes to take cash and jewelry while the residents are watching television
at least 55 such burglaries have occurred since december in the denver area, police say
it's a little bizarre,'' sgt. pat whitman of nearby cherry hills village said wednesday. ``most burglars would rather find an empty house than a resident inside.''
denver sgt. bill wiederspan says he's no psychiatrist, but he has theories
either it's psychological and he does it for the thrills. or, he's imitating burglars on tv shows and he's been watching too much tv,'' he said
in as many as six houses a night, a prowler has entered, usually through unlocked doors or windows, and fled with a few selected items such as rifles, jewelry boxes, wallets or purses
the first possible confrontation with the prime-time prowler occurred monday night when a cherry hills resident came out of the shower to find a stranger in his home
what are you doing here?'' the resident asked
don't worry. i'm just leaving,'' said the tall, slender young stranger, backing away and fleeing out a back door. a watch later was discovered missing, authorities said
the intruder, whose visits last only a few minutes, is so neat that many victims don't realize for some time that anyone has been in the house. in a few instances, the homeowner has heard something and the prowler has fled empty-handed
but authorities fear violence is not far away
i think it's just a matter of time,'' wiederspan said
reported incursions by nicaraguan troops into honduras in pursuit of contra rebels have marked the recent history of the six-year nicaraguan civil war, but the present u.s. reaction is the strongest yet
the white house said wednesday it was sending 3,200 american infantry and airborne troops to honduras today as ``an emergency deployment readiness exercise.'' the white house says the action was prompted by what it called the invasion of neighboring honduras by 1,500 to 2,000 nicaraguan forces
the u.s. troops were to be kept 125 miles from the area of reported hostilities, spokesman marlin fitzwater said
the last such incident was late in november 1986. honduras said a sandinista force of 2,500 soldiers crossed the border in a bid to stall the contras from mounting a dry-season offensive
honduras, which claimed the sandinistas had moved at least nine miles deep into the country, responded by having u.s. helicopters airlift about 3,000 honduran troops to the area
there was some small-scale combat between the sandinistas and hondurans. and the hondurans bombed and strafed suspected sandinista positions with french-built super mystere and old, u.s.-made a-37 jet fighters
nicaragua denied that its troops crossed over, and no casualty figures were released
in late march 1986, u.s. officials said about 1,500 nicaraguan troops were operating nine miles to 15 miles inside honduras
the sandinista government initially denied the charge, but president daniel ortega acknowledged border crossings which he claimed were ``totally defensive operations.''
the week before that incursion, the house had voted 222-210 against president reagan's request for $100 million in aid to the contras. the senate approved the money four days after the administration announced the incursion, and an aid package was passed in august
at the time of the incursion, reagan approved $20 million in emergency assistance to the hondurans, and u.s. helicopters ferried about 600 honduran soldiers to the area from the palmerola air base where the troops were being flown today
honduran military sources said 200 sandinistas were killed, 16 captured and others injured during the incursion, which lasted less than a week. forty contras were reportedly killed
other u.s. officials later scaled back their estimate of the number of sandinista troops involved in the border crossing to about 800. suggests</head>
aids may force the growing populations of some developing countries into decline decades after the first aids virus infection, according to computer projections published today
but another study says that at the worst, aids could cut the growth rate of a typical central african country in half
it's a disaster from any point of view,'' said john bongaarts of the population council in new york, who did the second study
today's projections appear in the british journal nature
they say that with low to moderate infection rates like those of kenya, uganda or zaire, population declines would not begin until 20 to 70 years after the aids virus invades a developing country, even one with low growth rates
the researchers stressed that their projections are crude and said too little is known about aids to make more realistic ones
it is clear that aids will have an impact on swelling population growth rates, but by how much is too sensitive to things we don't know about with sufficient certititude,'' said robert may of princeton university, who did the study with roy anderson and a.r. mclean of imperial college in london
any (firm) long-term projection about whether aids will or will not bring about zero or even negative rates of growth in africa cannot be made.''
in a telephone interview, may said the projections do not pertain to the united states or any other developed country
acquired immune deficiency syndrome in africa is thought to spread mainly through heterosexual contact, while most cases in the united states stem from homosexual contact or needle sharing by intravenous drug abusers
the researchers said they found potential for eventual population decline under a range of plausible assumptions for such factors as the fraction of infected people who will die from aids, the fraction of infected women's babies who are born infected and the length of time the virus lies dormant before causing aids
projections are severely limited by lack of precise knowledge on such points, may said
the federal centers for disease control estimates that an infected woman runs a 30 percent to 60 percent chance of giving birth to an infected baby, and that 20 percent to 30 percent of people infected with the virus develop aids within five years. the cdc has no figure on the percentage of infected people who eventually die from aids, a spokesman said
one series of projections in nature assumed an initial 4 percent growth rate like that of kenya, where the population doubles about every 16 years and residents have a normal life expectancy of 52 years
assuming an eight-year dormant period for the virus, one projection forecast eventual population decline if half or 30 percent of babies born to infected mothers are infected at birth
a second projection took the same basic assumptions, set the infected-newborn rate at 50 percent, and found eventual population decline if every infected person dies of aids
bongaarts said his projections come out differently because he divided the hypothetical population into groups of high, medium and low risk for aids
he also said that ``very implausible estimates'' of the prevalence of aids virus infection would be needed to project zero population growth or population decline
his projections, in the worst case, find aids cutting the 3 percent growth rate typical of central african nations in half. more likely is a reduction to 2 percent, he said
but even that implies a doubling of the death rate, leading to an overwhelmed health care system and disrupted social structure, he said
scientists reported today they have found the approximate location of a defective gene causing an inherited tendency toward kidney cancer, and that the gene also may help cause kidney cancer in general
genes lie along threadlike structures called chromosomes. the gene in the study is in a general area already associated with genetic abnormality in kidney cancer, the researchers said
if the gene plays a role in kidney cancer, which strikes some 18,000 americans a year, studying it may lead to better diagnosis and treatment, another expert said
the gene is now linked to von hippel-lindau disease, for which only a few hundred cases are known in the united states, according to the national organization for rare disorders
usually striking in young adulthood, the disease can cause tumors in the eye, brain and spinal cord that can damage eyesight and nerve function. about 40 percent of people with the disease develop kidney cancer, usually in both kidneys, and their prognosis is poor, researchers say
genes are chemical sequences that lie along chromosomes in every cell of the body
the u.s., canadian, british and dutch scientists, whose study is reported in today's issue of the british journal nature, used a ``marker,'' which is a chemical sequence at a known location on a chromosome and can be inherited along with a gene if it is close enough
in a study of 203 members of nine families, including 71 who had von hippel-lindau disease, the marker was inherited along with the defective gene 90 percent of the time, said james gusella of massachusetts general hospital and harvard medical school
other studies have found that stretches of the chromosome numbered 3 are missing in some kidney cancers. the new work shows that the defective gene causing von hippel-lindau disease resides in the same general portion of the chromosome as the deletions, researchers said
so the defective gene or a nearby one may play a role in at least some sporadic kidney cancers, gusella said
he explained that in its normal form, the gene may protect against kidney cancer. every cell gets two copies of a gene, so if one copy is defective _ as in von hippel-lindau disease _ the cell has only one normal copy left. if that copy is damaged or deleted during a person's lifetime, the cell could turn cancerous, gusella said
under that theory, people without von hippel-lindau disease could get kidney cancer if both normal copies are damaged or deleted during their lifetimes
the next step for researchers will be to find the gene and isolate it for study
w. marston linehan of the national cancer institute, who has studied chromosome deletions in kidney cancer, called the finding very significant work that may help in learning about development of kidney cancer
such new understanding might lead to better diagnosis and treatment, he said
col. leonidas macias, the alleged leader of a failed coup, in recent months had been a staunch defender of the nation's military strongman, gen. manuel antonio noriega
when president eric arturo delvalle tried unsuccessfully to remove noriega as chief of the 15,000-member defense forces on feb. 25, it was macias who heatedly told reporters that delvalle himself would go before noriega
within hours, delvalle was deposed by the legislative assembly in a noriega-orchestrated move
during the past year macias, about 50, has been chief of police, a job that put him in charge of about 5,000 officers and administrative employees
they include the riot police, who have forcibly put down street demonstrations against the government since last june
but after light arms fire broke out in the defense forces headquarters on wednesday, the military said that macias, three majors, a captain and some civilians were arrested after ``an attempt by several officers to take over the headquarters of our institution was foiled.''
panama's civil unrest began after accusations last summer that noriega was involved in crimes ranging from political assassination to drug trafficking
noriega was indicted on federal drug charges in florida last month
some of those arrested in the anti-noriega demonstrations have accused macias of allowing others to beat them while in custody. one of those detained told the opposition-aligned human rights association that macias took part in at least one beating. macias denied the accusations
macias had conducted a public relations campaign with reporters to counter the anti-noriega drive, holding several news conferences to report on events in the defense forces. he was the only high-ranking officer to do so
in recent months, macias called three news conferences, one christmas lunch and invited journalists to his home, always saying in a jovial manner that nothing was happening
during a protest strike that began feb. 29, macias took journalists around the city on a bus saying: ``look, there's nothing happening here. everything is fine. look at me, i'm unarmed. what policeman like myself can move around the streets of his city without being armed?''
but he could be harsh with the opposition
on feb. 29, he took chamber of commerce president aurelio barria, who had been arrested a few hours earlier, before reporters. ``clown!'' he yelled at barria. ``look at him, he's fine. you can go home!''
barria was detained for trying to enter the chamber of commerce building, which had been closed by the government four days earlier
although macias was considered one of the colonels most loyal to noriega, there had been rumors before wednesday that while they kept up the appearance of good relations, there were problems between the two men
the federal election commission has certified almost $3.5 million in new federal matching funds for 11 presidential candidates, including nearly $900,000 for pat robertson whose republican campaign is winding down
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis continued to lead the democratic money race, qualifying for more than $600,000 in new matching funds and raising his matching total to more than twice that of his competitors for his party's nomination
dukakis' closest democratic rivals jesse jackson and tennesee sen. albert gore jr. qualify for a little more than $300,000 and $336,000 respectively
vice president george bush, who has a big lead in the republican contest, got in line for a new quarter of a million dollars in federal funds, keeping his edge in the category
kansas sen. bob dole is eligible for almost $390,000
in all, the new funds certified on wednesday raise the total certified thus far for 14 candidates to $45.44 million
presidential candidates qualify for matching funds by raising at least $5,000 in individual contributions of $250 or less in at least 20 states. after qualifying, every individual contribution of $250 or less is matched dollar-for-dollar by federal funds. the money comes from the voluntary $1 checkoff on federal tax returns
carl and karen hawkinson will be taking a trip to new orleans together this summer as delegates to the republican national convention _ but that's where the togetherness ends
the couple were elected tuesday as gop delegates, but he supports kansas sen. bob dole and she backs vice president george bush
we didn't really expect to both be elected but that's the way it turned out,'' hawkinson said
even though bush is the front-runner, mrs. hawkinson said winning her delegate slot was a surprise because dole was considered the favorite in their congressional district
her husband's win was not as as unpredictable, she said
carl has held office since 1976 _ people are used to voting for him,'' she said. ``but i had never been on a ballot before.''
the two said campaigning for rival candidates made their home life a little hectic, but they avoided the kind of spats that have colored the bush-dole battle for the nomination
gov. mario cuomo has signed legislation to switch the date of the new york state primary to keep it from falling on the jewish holiday of rosh hashana
the primary, not to be confused with new york's april 19 presidential primary, will be held thursday, sept. 15. it was originally scheduled two days earlier
three other states had switched their primaries already to prevent the conflict. connecticut and rhode island will hold their primaries sept. 14, while massachusetts will join new york with a primary sept. 15
six states _ arizona, minnesota, new hampshire, utah, vermont and wisconsin _ will hold primaries on rosh hashana, sept. 13
in new york, jews usually represent 20 percent or more of the vote in democratic primary contests
the state primaries which were swithced on wednesday determine nominations for governor, state legislative seats, congress and local offices
lt. col. oliver north says he will fight the criminal allegations against him ``for as long as necessary'' despite heavy personal and financial costs
i did not commit any crime,'' north said wednesday a few hours after a federal grand jury indicted him and three others on conspiracy charges stemming from the iran-contra affair. ``i intend to fight allegations of wrongdoing for as long as necessary.''
appearing ashen-faced and grim, north said he was aware of the high personal and financial costs of fighting the charges, but ``i can assure you, i will never give up, we will win.''
north thanked the american people ``who have shown so much love and concern these past 16 months by their millions of telegrams and letters and prayers and support.''
the marine officer said that he was caught in the cross-fire of a bitter dispute between congress and the president over central america, and that ``it is a shame the new battleground for such a fight will be in a courtroom.''
beside north was his lawyer, brendan sullivan, who also represented north at last summer's hearings before joint committees of the senate and house
sullivan, whose spirited defense of his client was one of the highlights of the hearings, said that seeking wednesday's indictment ``was one of the worst prosecutorial decisions in the history of our country.''
it is a decision of an unaccountable prosecutor who came to washington determined to allege that some crime, any crime had been committed,'' sullivan said
sullivan added that lawrence e. walsh, the independent counsel ``presents an indictment after 15 months (of investigation) based on mistaken facts, novel and sometimes ridiculous legal theories.''
everyone must seriously wonder about a decision to indict a man like oliver north, a highly decorated marine corps officer, based on his tireless effort in the interests of his country,'' sullivan said
for his part, north said it was a sad irony that the decision to indict should occur on the fourth anniversary of the abduction in lebanon of william buckley and the third anniversary of the kidnapping of terry anderson, the associated press' chief middle east correspondent
a firm of ex-commandos credited with snatching a 7-year-old girl off a school bus in jordan for her american mother is known among law enforcement agencies for its anti-terrorist training, officers say
fayetteville police chief ron hansen said corporate training unlimited approached him last year and offered to train some of his officers in such areas as building searches, response techniques and hostage negotiations
it was excellent training,'' hansen said wednesday. ``i checked them out and found out they were very reputable and knowledgeable in their areas (of expertise).''
they are extremely competent and detailed in what they do,'' said hansen, whose 12-man emergency response team was trained by ctu specialists at no cost
ctu's brochure touts the company as an ``international security consulting and training firm specializing in both anti- and counter-terrorist tactics and techniques.''
our staff is comprised entirely of delta force and special operations qualified personnel, each with many years experience in this field,'' it reads. ``these personnel have passed a rigorous screening and selective process, participating in years of specialized training and have proven themselves under fire.''
oscar adkins, a ctu employee, is teaching a 40-hour course on specialized weapons and tactics at wilson county technical college in wilson, n.c., according to school spokeswoman mary lou smith,
representatives from the agency have also taught other courses in the past,'' she said. ``they came highly recommended from other law enforcement agencies.''
although ctu officials have denied involvement in the jordan mission, the company reportedly was paid up to $200,000 by cathy phelps mahone to recover her daughter, lauren bayan, from jerash, north of amman, in late january
ms. mahone, who is said to be in hiding outside dallas, claims her ex-husband, jordanian-born mohammed ali bayan, failed to return her daughter after a visit last october. a dallas judge had given ms. mahone custody after the couple's 1980 divorce, but bayan reportedly claims custody under jordanian law
the rescue operation was planned and executed jan. 28 by ctu, the philadelphia inquirer reported last weekend, quoting anonymous sources
ctu president donald feeney has denied involvement. a secretary at the company's office told the associated press on wednesday that company officials would have no comment on the story
state department spokesman charles redman said earlier this week an american embassy officer in amman has been recalled to washington to answer questions about his knowledge of the matter
redman said the united states has apologized to jordan for any role the embassy officer may have played in the mission. the officer, who was unidentified, had some prior knowledge of the plan but apparently was misled by ctu, redman said
in an interview last october, guy chapman, a former member of the army's secretive counter-terrorist unit delta force, said he and three other former delta members created the company in january 1986
a lot of companies profess to be knowledgeable, but when you come right down to it, no company has the experience we have,'' he said
in its brochure, ctu claims it offers courses to police agencies or corporate security organizations in hostage rescue, shooting enhancement, protective security, anti-terrorism and defensive driving. the company also provides audio-visual training material and professional guard services
chapman, who says he participated in the abortive iran hostage rescue mission in 1979, said ctu has worked with federal and local agencies protecting the u.s. strategic petroleum reserves in louisiana and texas
chapman also said ctu has trained special police forces in peru and ecuador, and worked with the south american offices of several major u.s. companies, including colgate-palmolive and johnson and johnson
carla mikell, a spokeswoman at colgate-palmolive, said wednesday that company officials would have no comment on the story. johnson and johnson spokesman jeff leebaw said his company does not discuss its security measures
