an explosion rocked a testing laboratory today, sparking a fire that forced the evacuation of industrial plants a half-mile away. authorities said three people were killed and one injured
among the hazardous materials used at gollob analytical services are radioactive hydrogen and krypton, and the solvents xylene and benzine, said department of environmental protection spokesman jim staples. light industrial buildings within a half-mile downwind were evacuated as a precaution, and employees heading to work at neighboring buildings were sent home
volunteer firefighters, working upwind of the one-story lab, thought they had extinguished the blaze by 6:30 a.m., nearly 4{ hours after it began, but it flared up again a half-hour later, officials said
the identities of the victims were not known, said police chief ralph m. del duca. a 30-year-old man was in critical condition in surgery today at university hospital in newark, said nursing supervisor mary kwasek
police at first reported two dead in the fire, but officials said later at a news conference that three bodies had been recovered
i have no information as to why they were in there. the company does not have a night time operation. but it is not unusual for employees to work on special projects overnight,'' said philip solomon, union county emergency managment coordinator
state inspectors will check a nearby brook that runs into the passaic river for contamination, and a township crew built a sandbag dam around the plant to contain runoff water from the firefighting, staples said. the air around the plant also will be checked for chemicals and radiation, he said. up 7th graf pvs: `carlucci described...'</note>
defense secretary frank c. carlucci said he and his soviet counterpart briefly debated the reported nicaraguan incursion into honduras today before concluding three days of talks on an upbeat note
carlucci said he protested the incursion to soviet defense minister dmitri yazov, who ``made some attempt to defend the sandinista action.''
i would not characterize it as a vigorous defense,'' carlucci told a news conference before leaving bern for washington
carlucci said he consulted with the white house overnight and endorsed the decision to send an emergency u.s. force to honduras on exercises
the sandinistas said they had chased contra rebels to the honduran border, but the nicaraguan defense ministry denied sandinista troops entered honduras
the soviet union provides nicaragua with military and economic aid. at a news conference, yazov did not address the issue of nicaragua specifically
we spoke out in favor of greater predictability and stability in the soviet-u.s. military balance,'' he said. ``we tried to better understand the logic of and rationale for u.s. actions in the military field.''
carlucci described his talks with yazov, which were closed to reporters, as ``cordial and businesslike'' and said he had been invited to moscow to continue the discussions at an unspecified date
he said he had not obtained the apology he requested for the fatal shooting by a soviet soldier of u.s. army maj. arthur nicholson in east germany three years ago. yazov said the incident occurred before he became defense minister last may, said carlucci
he said he would undertake to investigate it'' through the soviet foreign ministry, which has been handling the issue carlucci said
to avoid such ``dangerous activities,'' carlucci said, ``gen. yazov and i agreed that more would be done in this area.''
both agreed that ``there is no need for shooting,'' said carlucci. ``gen. yazov was firm on that.''
carlucci said the chairman of the u.s. joint chiefs of staff, adm. william crowe, and the soviet chief of staff, marshal sergei akhomeyev, would meet soon, probably in washington, to work out guidelines to prevent friction between u.s. and soviet ground, air and sea, forces
yazov repeated kremlin assurances that soviet troops would be withdrawn from afghanistan, but was unable to set a timetable, pending the outcome of stalled peace talks in geneva, said carlucci
the two sides also discussed space-based missile defense, negotiations to reduce strategic nuclear arsenals, and regional conflicts, including angola, cambodia and korea, he said
the soviets proposed an experiment of a new method of determining the presence of nuclear-tipped, sea-launched cruise missiles aboard vessels, a technique mentioned last december by kremlin leader mikhail s. gorbachev but never explained to the west
carlucci expressed doubt about the technique, but said the united states was willing to review the propsed experiment, details of which were not available
the soviets want to impose a limit on such weapons as part of the strategic arms reduction treaty now under negotiation. return, other details. changes byline. no pickup.</note>
four israeli soldiers went on trial today on charges of brutality against palestinians in the first such cases to reach court since violence erupted in the occupied territories more than three months ago
two soldiers pleaded guilty to reduced charges in the burying alive of four palestinians in the occupied west bank, and two others pleaded innocent in the televised beating of two palestinians
also today, israeli warplanes raided plo bases in the chouf mountains south of beirut, and the army said all targets were destroyed. one guerrilla was reported killed and two people were injured
israeli newspapers said secretary of state george p. shultz might return to the middle east in late march or early april to continue his mission to reach an accord between israel and the arabs for starting peace talks
senior military officials said israel imposed new restrictions against palestinians, ruling for the first time that any arab wishing to bring $1,000 or more into israeli-held territories from jordan must receive permission
the measure was intended to curb palestine liberation organization-provided funding for the current unrest. the money has helped shopkeepers on strike and aided arab families whose homes were destroyed by the israeli army
in addition, dairy and produce deliveries were not permitted to enter the cities of nablus, tulkarm and jericho, arab reports said. the army said it was checking the report
in a military court in jaffa, pvts. yair nissimi and dror segen-cohen were accused of assault and abuse for helping bury alive four palestinians with a bulldozer after a feb. 5 demonstration in the west bank village of kfar salem
a third soldier, sgt. mjr. charlie danino, was being tried separately on the same charges, as well as unbecoming conduct
nissimi and segen-cohen accepted a reduced charge of shameful conduct under a plea bargain placed before a panel of three military judges. they were to be sentenced to two months and 2{ months in jail, respectively
i'm sorry about everything that happened,'' nissimi told the court. ``i know i made a mistake.''
attorneys for the two soldiers charged in the beating incident filmed by cbs television _ pvts. sagi harpaz and yehuda angel _ said the soldiers entered pleas of not guilty and the trial was recessed
attorney uri slonim, representing harpaz, said his client would argue he had carried out his mission of dispersing a demonstration ``in a way that seemed correct under the circumstances'' and had only used the ``amount of force needed to carry out his mission.''
about 250 reserve soldiers, meanwhile, submitted a petition to government leaders today supporting the israeli army in its attempt to quell the unrest in the territories
the dailies yediot ahronot, maariv, haaretz and jerusalem post all reported that shultz, having received an equivocal answer about the u.s. peace plan from visiting israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir, is expected to return to the region either late this month or early next month
haaretz also reported that despite shamir's opposition to an international conference, shultz, who meets next week with soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze in washington, would propose the two leaders jointly appeal to the united nations to convene such a session
the attack on lebanon came a day after a volley of katyusha rockets was fired from south lebanon into a community in north israel. an israeli army spokesman said the rockets shattered windows and damaged citrus trees, but caused no injuries
in clashes wednesday, four arabs were shot and killed by troops, bringing the palestinian death toll to 100 since the uprising began dec. 8, according to the united nations
also wednesday, the occupied lands were paralyzed by a general strike, ordered by the plo-affiliated underground leadership of the uprising in a clandestine leaflet. most stores were shuttered, public transportation halted and most of the 110,000 arabs who work in israel stayed home
congressional republicans who investigated the iran-contra affair today criticized the indictments of two former white house officials and two other men, but democrats said the charges buttress last year's findings
i personally think that the indictment counts are pathetic,'' said sen. orrin hatch, r-utah, on abc-tv's ``good morning america.''
you have in this particular case 30 full-time lawyers, 50 investigators, millions of dollars being spent by the government, an overwhelming onslaught of legalities here, '' said hatch, one of the reagan administration's strongest supporters during last summer's hearings
rep. richard cheney, r-wyo., said on the nbc-tv ``today'' program, ``i don't think that men like poindexter ... and north deserve to end up being prosecuted on criminal grounds that deal with their service in government. ... i'm not sure the indictments are warranted but i'm sure at this point probably the only way to resolve it is to go forward with the trials.''
rep. lee hamilton, d-ind., chairman of the house iran-contra committee, who also appeared on abc, said the charges are similar to the conclusions reached by the legislative panels, although the committees didn't apportion criminal blame
when we set out, there were a number of laws that we thought had been broken. ... the indictments track these findings in our report very carefully,'' said hamilton
these are very serious offenses, said another democrat from the senate panel, sen. george mitchell of maine, on nbc
i think it should be noted that the prosecutor (lawrence walsh) is a lifelong republican, a former deputy attorney general in a republican administration, appointed to the court by a republican president so there are no political implications in the prosecution,'' said mitchell
rep. henry hyde, r-ill., an administration supporter on the iran-contra panel, said earlier, ``this is only the beginning of what will be a very long legal process that will question the sufficiency of the indictments and the constitutionality of the laws.''
he said ``the indictments are premised on some assumptions that may or may not be true, like title to the money. the prosecutors believe the money from the sale of weapons to iran belonged to the u.s. treasury and therefore it was misappropriated for the contras, but i think a very good argument can be made that the proceeds of the sale don't belong to the treasury.''
sen. daniel inouye, d-hawaii, chairman of the senate committee, said, ``i personally remain convinced that they (the four men) exhibited insufficient sensitivity to the rule of law, and to the fact that under our system of government the congress must make the laws.''
but he added that ``we must await the verdict of a jury of their peers as to whether this insensitivity was criminal in nature.''
sen. james mcclure, r-idaho, another administration defender during the hearings, noted that the white house was charging that nicaraguan troops had entered neighboring honduras to battle the contras
it's ironic that on a day when indictments were handed down in washington against the very people who tried desperately to keep the freedom fighters alive, sandinista troops were in honduras trying to wipe out the freedom fighters once and for all,'' mcclure said
rep. richard gephardt, d-mo., a candidate for the democratic presidential nomination, said, ``whatever the outcome of these prosecutions, i think the special prosecutor has given as fresh evidence that the reagan administration generally has put the constitution of the united states through the shredder.''
this will be an important issue in the campaign,'' gephardt said, particularly the role of vice president george bush, who is the front-runner for the republican presidential nomination. touring enterprise. no pickup.</note>
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev was introduced today to the communist east's ``doorway to europe,'' an industrial region in northern yugoslavia that has realized his dream of joining the world trading community
gorbachev received a less enthusiastic welcome here than he did in belgrade, where he spent the first three days of his five-day tour of yugoslavia
more than 1,000 people gathered in ljubljana's revolution square, but the soviet leader and his wife, raisa, were greeted with only polite applause. cheering, shouting crowds welcomed the gorbachevs to belgrade
belgrade is the center of yugoslavia's serbian republic, which traditionally has had closes ties to moscow
at an electronics plant in slovenia, yugoslavia's northernmost republic and one of the most prosperous regions in the communist world, premier dusan sinigoj told gorbachev his semi-autonomous republic is bound to the west both culturally and economically and now concentrates on developing new technologies for export
slovenia represents a doorway to (western) europe,'' selling more than half the goods it produces abroad, he told the soviet leader. slovenia has only 8 percent of yugoslavia's population but produces 25 percent of the nation's exports
the soviet union is slovenia's second-largest trading partner, behind west germany
unders gorbachev's program of ``perestroika'' or restructuring, the soviet union is trying to encourage joint ventures with western firms, hoping to produce more goods for export and improve trade with hard-currency countries
gorbachev responded in good nature to criticism about his restructuring plan
franc sifkovic, general director of the iskra avtomatika plant that gorbachev was visiting, complained that decentralization undur perestroika had complicated the firm's dealings with the soviet union. now, he said, iskra must deal with individual managers instead of with a single government ministry, as in the past
then restructure yourself,'' the soviet leader said with a smile
during a tour of one branch of iskra, the largest electronics and appliance enterprise in yugoslavia, gorbachev was shown equipment made for export to the soviet union and was introducud to the research and development division of the plant
keeping up with western technology and developing improved, state-of-the-art equipment is central to iskra's business strategy and is what gorbachev hopes for soviet enterprises
if gorbachev was impressed with the advanced products and methods, he gave little indication publicly. his remarks were confined to expressions of friendship and a desire for improved soviet-yugoslav relations
yugoslavia has a $1.4 billion trade surplus with the soviet union but has beun unwilling to accept soviet manufactured goods in compensation for the debt. officials here say soviet products, notorious for poor quality, won't sell in yugoslavia
although the average wage in slovenia is about 500,000 dinars, or $365 a month _ nearly twice that of yugoslavia as a whole _ gorbachev's motorcade passed a shantytown near the iskra plan that illustrated the nation's economic crisis
yugoslavia's runaway inflation is pegged at 170 percent a year, and 15 percent of the country's workforce is jobless
western influence is apparent in slovenia shops, which sell a variety of west european products from flashlight batteries to automobiles. slovenia borders both austria and italy, and yugoslavs _ unlike soviets and most other east europeans _ may travel freely abroad
slovenians living along the border often do their shopping in austrian and italian stores, and many work in austria
the republic industrialized rapidly after world war ii and benefitted by being able to obtamn raw materials cheaply in yugoslavia and export manufactured goods to world markets
more than 300,000 people turned out under cloudy skies today for dublin's st. patrick's day parade in a celebration intensified this year by the 1,000th birthday of the irish capital
street vendors did a brisk trade selling sprigs of shamrock, and a hamburger chain sold ``shamrock-flavored'' shakes in the traditional irish color _ green
across the border in the british province of northern ireland, the festivities were overshadowed by wednesday's deadly attack on an irish republican army funeral in belfast. three people were killed and 68 wounded
but in ireland, theaters, pubs and hotels have been throbbing with traditional irish music, drama and folk dancing this week, which has been designated st. patrick's week
patrick, who tradition says brought christianity to the pagan irish in the 5th century, is the patron saint of ireland
about 6,000 people took part in the dublin parade, which winds along a three-mile route from st. stephen's green to o'connell street, the main thoroughfare
police estimated that more than 300,000 people, including about 10,000 tourists, mainly americans, turned out to watch the procession of dancers, marching bands and historical-theme floats pass by
prime minister charles haughey took his place on a reviewing stand outside the general post office in o'connell street and called the colorful carnival ``one of the best ever.''
government offices, schools, banks and most businesses were closed in the south for the national holiday, but many industries, offices and department stores remained open in northern ireland. churches were thronged for morning mass and pubs were packed with imbibers
organizers said the dublin parade was being televised by more than 80 tv stations in the united states and canada
patrick, the son of a deacon and apparently born in wales, was consecrated a catholic priest in a.d. 432 and sent to ireland, where he was largely credited with organizing the christian communities
in belfast, mourners wearing shamrocks and green armbands attended the funeral of a slain ira guerrilla a day after a man opened fire and hurled grenades in milltown cemetery during the burial of three ira guerrillas shot by british commandos in gibraltar march 6
on wednesday, haughey appealed to ulster's roman catholic minority to ``to respond with calm'' to the attack at the ira funeral
