the ap lake</head>
a citizens group upset over congressional action to rename a lake after sen. strom thurmond presented the south carolina republican with petitions signed by 42,000 people thursday urging that the original name be restored
but thurmond refused to become involved in the controversy after meeting privately for 35 minutes with representatives of the group and with south carolina legislators supporting the name change to honor thurmond
thurmond declined to answer questions as he left the meeting at his capitol office, referring them to his press secretary, christopher simpson
he told them he feels the matter is settled and since he did not instigate it or push for it, he feels it would be inappropriate for him to get involved now,'' simpson said
the dispute over the name of the army corps of engineers-built clarks hill lake, which straddles the south carolina-georgia border, began in december which congress, acting quickly and with no public hearings, enacted legislation changing the name of the lake, dam and road to strom thurmond
roy giles, a lincolnton, ga., restaurant owner and one of the leaders of the citizens group, said the petitions propose a compromise that would restore the name of the lake to clarks hill but would retain the new strom thurmond name for the dam and road
rep. doug barnard, d-ga., has introduced legislation paterned after the compromise, which giles said would permit thurmond to ``have his monument and the people will have their lake back.''
south carolina state sen. john drummond of greenwood said the legislators told the citizens group that it would be an embarrassment for thurmond to ``ask the whole congress and the president to reverse what they've done.''
drummond said he told the group the two states need to work together ``to save that lake, not the name'' because the low water level in the lake is threatening its recreational potential
giles said the name change will result in financial losses for businesses that have built their reputations using the clarks hill name. and he vowed that the group will continue its fight, even without thurmond's help. figures</head>
the chamber of commerce has apologized to the rev. joseph lowery for including stories profiling civil rights activists on a list of potentially negative stories journalists might write during the democratic national convention
chamber president jerry bartels had received complaints on lowery's behalf after reports that chamber officials regarded the president of the southern christian leadership conference as a public relations liability
a chamber official said wednesday the group made a mistake in putting the subject of profiles of civil rights activists on a list of potentially negative news stories about atlanta
barry king, the chamber's vice president for communication, said lists of ``positive'' and ``negative'' potential media topics were drafted to help the chamber prepare to respond to reporters' questions during the convention this july
the lists appeared in the chamber's newsletter last month. the atlanta journal and the atlanta constitution subsequently reported that chamber officials considered lowery among the ``negative'' news figures
negative subjects on the chamber's list include ku klux klan activity, nude dance clubs and textbook banning. on the positive list were southern hospitality, the book and movie ``gone with the wind,'' and atlanta's fortune 500 companies
following the news reports, bartels wrote lowery, saying the chamber considers him a positive force in atlanta. no other letters were sent, king said, because there were no other questions about the chamber's views on a specific civil rights figure
however, lowery said tuesday that he didn't consider the letter an apology. ``what he never did explain was how profiles of civil rights leaders get in a negative category,'' he said
we never mentioned the names of anybody on any of these lists,'' king said. he said he regretted that ``positive'' and ``negative'' labels were used
many of the stories, he said, could turn out to be flattering or derogatory depending on how they were written. a story about civil rights might be negative, he said, because the ``overall record of achievement could be questioned.''
if reporters ask about civil rights leaders, he said, ``we would simply put them in touch with the civil rights leaders.'' dropped word. picks up 4th graf pvs, the rules ... with minor editing to trim; 6 grafs sub for grafs 19-21 pvs, updating with new shooting, corrects israeli victim's name. picks up 22nd graf pvs, the army ....</note>
israel began its first major trials on thursday of soldiers charged with brutality in the arab rebellion, and palestinians wounded an israeli with gunfire for the first time since the violence began dec. 8
israeli warplanes raided palestinian guerrilla bases in the mountains south of beirut, and newspapers said secretary of state george p. shultz may return to the middle east early next month to promote the u.s. peace plan. the raid came a day after rockets landed in northern israel, causing light damage
authorities increased restrictions in the occupied territories, which already include travel bans and a cut-off of telephone service to the outside. a military official said palestinians must get approval to bring $1,000 or more from neighboring jordan, where most hold citizenship and have family
the rules are intended to hamper the palestine liberation organization in organizing and financing the protests
trials beginning thursday involved the burial alive of four arabs by an army bulldozer feb. 5 in kfar salem, a west bank village, and the beating feb. 24 of two palestinians near nablus, which was photographed by a cbs news crew
neighbors soon rescued the buried palestinians. the beating was televised around the world and aroused international protest
several weeks after trouble began in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, the army introduced a policy of beating rioters as an alternative to firing live ammunition. at least 100 palestinians have been killed in more than three months of violence, and hundreds wounded
yair nissimi and dror segen-cohen, both army privates, pleaded guilty in the burial case to reduced charges of shameful behavior. the plea bargain would give nissimi 2{ months in jail and segen-cohel two months, and both would be placed on probation
a three-judge panel is to rule march 29 on whether to accept the arrangement
sgt. maj. charlie danino pleaded innocent to assault and unbecoming conduct, and is expected to argue that he was not at the scene
mustafa hamdan, one of those buried, said of the plea bargain: ``they buried four people alive. if an arab did that they would have given him 200 years.''
defense lawyer josef danai said in court the burial was ``an instance of letting off steam, revenge and deterrence'' by soldiers in difficult circumstances
they spilled a little earth on them,'' he said. ``the tractor driver said an ant could have gotten out of it.''
sgt. amichai vaturi, who was at the scene but is not charged, testified that the arabs were covered with about two feet of wet earth but their heads and shoulders were exposed
hamdan said the heads of three men were covered
in the beating case, sagi harpaz and yehuda angel, army privates, pleaded innocent to assault and the case was recessed
two other soldiers were sentenced tuesday to 10 and 21 days in jail for minor roles in the beating
in the gaza strip, a 25-year-old khan yunis resident, subhi abu sharar, was shot in the chest and seriously wounded, said ilana ziv, spokeswoman for barzilai hospital in ashkelon
arab reports said israeli soldiers shot him during a demonstration
also in gaza, two arabs shot 44-year-old israeli contractor adi tzabari four times in the legs near jabalia refugee camp, ms. ziv said
tzabari told israel army radio ``i threw a hammer'' at one arab with a pistol, ``then another one appeared with a kalashnikov (assault rifle) and opened fire.''
the army confirmed the shooting. it was the first time an israeli, civilian or soldier, has been reported hit by arab gunfire since the beginning of what palestinians now call ``the uprising.''
an arab truck driver in the same area tried to run down an israeli soldier earlier thursday but the soldier escaped without injury, the army said
arab reports from jabaliya said the army fired tear gas and rubber bullets at 800 schoolgirls who stoned soldiers, raised palestinian flags and burned tires
officials of a u.n. clinic said 25 girls were treated for minor injuries. palestine press service, an arab-run news agency, said soldiers in the west bank arrested 150 palestinians overnight in nablus, jenin, qabitiyeh, ramallah and hebron
arab reporters said the army blocked dairy and produce deliveries to nablus, tulkarm and jericho
the army said these reports were being checked
paul simon, his democratic presidential candidacy rejuvenated by his homestate primary win, campaigned wednesday on the prospect of a brokered convention and said he was ``as acceptable as a second choice as anyone.''
simon toured wisconsin and michigan, both with important contests in the coming weeks, and expressed hope he'll be the mutual ``second choice'' who might emerge with the presidential nomination once the front-runners have fallen short of victory
we're not going to have a first-ballot winner in atlanta,'' he said
i will have a significant block of delegates. ... i think paul simon is as acceptable as a second choice as anyone,'' he said. ``i think i stand in a very good position.''
simon did not predict victory for himself in michigan's march 26 caucuses or wisconsin's april 5 primary, but he said he would pick up enough convention delegates to stay in the race
i've come to michigan not expecting to carry michigan, but i'd like to pick up as many delegates as i can,'' simon told a news conference near the state capitol
in milwaukee earlier in the day, he said, ``i can't tell you precisely where i think we'll come in, but i think we have a good shot of winning here and i am going to make every effort to win.''
simon won a lopsided illinois primary victory tuesday, followed by another favorite son, jesse jackson, in second, and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis relegated to a lackluster third
dukakis and jackson top the race for delegates with more than 400 apiece, sen. albert gore jr. is in second, while simon and rep. richard gephardt stand far back in the count
a domestic jetliner with up to 136 people aboard crashed during a storm in the northern colombia mountains thursday and burst into flames, with no immediate sign of survivors, officials said
the boeing 727 had just left cucuta, about 250 miles northeast of bogota, and crashed at nearby zulia, police at the town said, quoting witnesses
there was no immediate confirmation from the civil aeronautics agency, which reported the avianca flight missing soon after takeoff
zulia police said three witnesses reported that the plane clipped some trees, then slammed into the earth and burned, and they saw no survivors
according to the government air transport agency, it left cucuta near the venezuelan border at 1:16 p.m. for barranquilla, a caribbean port 250 miles northwest
how many people were on the flight was not clear. the agency said 136, including five crew members, but avianca said there were 78 passengers and six crew
the control tower at cucuta lost contact with the plane 15 minutes after takeoff as the aircraft traveled through the mountainous region in stormy weather, the aeronatics agency said, adding that it did not report mechanical problems
colombia's last major air crash occurred july 27, 1985, when an air force transport plane went down in the amazon jungle, killing 74 people. it was transporting passengers because of an airline strike
president francesco cossiga on wednesday asked ciriaco de mita, leader of the dominant christian democrats, to try to form italy's 48th government since world war ii
de mita, 60, indicated he would seek to put together a coalition of the same five parties that have governed off and on since 1981: christian democrats, socialists, republicans, social democrats and liberals
cossiga named de mita premier-designate after three days of consultations with political leaders following premier giovanni goria's resignation. goria, a christian democrat, stepped down friday after 7{ turbulent months in office
de mita told reporters at quirinal palace after meeting cossiga that he would open negotiations friday with the other parties
he said the christian democrats want solidarity ``among the same five parties of the coalition.''
the key to de mita's chances will be support of the socialists, the no. 2 party in the coalition. socialist leader bettino craxi said wednesday he did not object to de mita's candidacy but that his support would depend on the program outlined
among divisive issues facing de mita is italy's nuclear policy. a government decision last week to resume construction of a nuclear power plant near rome angered the socialists and helped force goria to resign
also in dispute is the fate of the secret vote in parliament. the socialists want the secret vote abolished
the bald-pated de mita was elected in 1982 as secretary of the christian democrats, a post many consider the most powerful political position in italy
de mita, son of a tailor, was born in nusco, a small hill town near naples. he entered politics in the 1950s after earning a law degree. he was elected to parliament in 1963 and has held his seat since then, serving as a minister in several governments in the 1970s
political commentators and cartoonists often poke fun at de mita's thick southern accent. he and his wife anna maria have four children
warplanes believed to be from honduras attacked a sandinista military headquarters in northern nicaragua near the honduran border, the nicaraguan presidential spokesman said thursday
manuel espinoza enriquez said there were no injuries and no damage in the attack. sandinista troops fired on the f-5 warplanes, forcing them to turn back to honduras, he said
he said the planes fired at least five rockets at the headquarters, but did not say if any hit it
president daniel, 1st graf pvs leslie dach, sted gearan</note>
the presidential candidates who made it through the costly super tuesday and illinois contests are now lining up fund-raising events to see them through the rest of the primary season
some of the most cash-draining states are yet to come _ new york, pennsylvania, california and ohio
vice president george bush has no money worries, and gop rival pat robertson has already shelled out nearly all he can legally spend. but the democrats continue hunting for cash for their generally lighter treasuries, and republican sen. bob dole is also seeking contributions
sen. paul simon of illinois and rep. richard gephardt of missouri both are scrimping along, looking to draw enough contributions to keep their campaigns afloat beyond caucuses on march 26 in michigan and primaries march 29 in connecticut and april 5 in wisconsin
the democratic money leader, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, has ``an active april fund-raising schedule,'' and remains in good financial shape, a spokesman said
democrat jesse jackson, whose fund-raising has trailed that of opponents, has been picking up money through an aggressive mail program, and will appeal for money in california this weekend
aides to sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee did not return calls thursday to discuss his financial picture
bush's schedule includes a handful of dinners and receptions through april, and then he can close up his fund-raising shop. that is because he will have brought in as much as he can spend on his primary campaign under election law rules, said campaign treasurer fred bush, who is no relation to the candidate
the limit is $27 million, and the campaign figures on another $2 million or so for legal and accounting costs, which are exempt from the limit
money has been pouring into the bush coffers as he heads to all-but-certain nomination this summer
the vice president's push down the fund-raising home stretch included a $1,000-a-person dinner thursday night in washington, for which 170 people were signed up and another two dozen had to be turned away, said the campaign treasurer
in addition to the events, bush will mail one more appeal to his 70,000 or so donors who have not yet ``maxed out'' with the $1,000 maximum contribution they are allowed to give
bush currently has more than $4 million in cash on hand, spokeswoman ede holiday said thursday. although he has nearly raised the limit, he can continue campaigning because he has not spent it all
in a different situation is gop rival robertson, the former tv evangelist, who must drastically scale back his campaign operation to avoid exceeding the spending limit
robertson has said he will rely heavily on volunteer efforts to see him through the rest of the campaign
dale tate, a spokeswoman for sen. dole of kansas said that after dole's poor showing on super tuesday and in illinois, receipts had not ``fallen off precipitously.''
in fact, she said, people have been calling unsolicited to pledge money and urge him not to drop out
these are republicans saying we think there should be a race,'' she said
on friday, callers pledged $140,000, on monday $95,000 and on tuesday $60,000, she said. still, she added, ``we're not bathing in dollars,'' and no decisions on tv advertising have been made for the campaign's next targeted state, wisconsin
dukakis spokesman mark gearan said the campaign raised $100,000 wednesday night in new york and is focusing on raising money for the new york and pennsylvania primaries. dukakis' strong showing in the 20-state super tuesday contests on march 8 has kept money flowing to him, he said
dukakis has about $1.5 million in the bank, not counting the more than $600,000 he got this week in federal matching funds, said spokesman leslie dach
for simon and gephardt, both of whom did poorly in the super tuesday races, the situation was not so bright, although both said they were not in debt
both also said they had record fund-raising months in february _ gephardt collecting $1.2 million and simon more than $900,000. a simon spokesman conceded, ``march will not be a record for us as february was.''
it's a day-to-day thing,'' said gephardt's spokesman mark johnson. ``we're using aggressive fund-raising'' techniques, mostly involving phone calls to contributors. ``you're at a point now where cash flow is very important, and you need a quick turnaround,'' he said
gephardt is is targeting michigan for a heavy advertising campaign, but johnson said he has no idea whether any loans will be taken out
simon spokesman david carle said that after paying off remaining bank debt thursday the campaign had around $300,000 in cash on hand. simon has scaled back his operation, laying off about 15 people at the campaign headquarters, on the heels of more than 250 layoffs after the iowa, new hampshire and super tuesday contests, carle said
simon collected about $60,000 at a chicago event monday night, and expected to bring in another $25,000 thursday night in new york
a mailing to simon's 50,000 contributors will go out next week, and unsolicited donations came in following simon's victory in his home state of illinois, carle said. he declined to give specific figures
simon will strongly contest wisconsin, with a large tv campaign, but will not buy ads in michigan, he said. response from webster spokesman, details on basis for probe</note>
fbi director william h. webster may have been ``misinformed'' in 1985 when he defended continuing a terrorism investigation into a group opposing reagan administration policy in central america, a congressman said thursday
the fbi's investigation of the committee in support of the people of el salvador was closed just two months later for lack of evidence
at a congressional hearing thursday, rep. f. james sensenbrenner referred to webster's testimony of april 17, 1985, in which the then-fbi director, now head of the cia, justified continuing the cispes investigation
but the inquiry ended in june 1985 following a review by the justice department which concluded that cispes was involved in political activities involving first amendment rights and not international terrorism
sensenbrenner, r-wis., said the shutdown such a short time after webster supported the investigation raised the question of ``whether there was this review going on when webster made the statement.''
the congressman said he was certain that a decision ``was not made quickly or rashly'' to close the terrorism investigation, which had been going on since 1983, preceded by an earlier domestic criminal investigation begun in 1981
i don't know if webster was misinformed or what,'' sensenbrenner said after raising the issue with current fbi director william sessions at a hearing before the house judiciary subcommittee on civil and constitutional rights
sessions confirmed his own statements of last month about the investigation being closed in june 1985, but said any elaboration would have to wait until an internal fbi review of the bureau's handling of the cispes inquiry is completed
in his april 1985 testimony before the same subcommittee, webster said ``we are not keeping track of the membership of cispes as such. there are, as in many organizations, a wide range of individuals engaged in that organization, including some in whom we have a legitimate independent foreign counterintelligence interest.''
webster's comments came in response to complaints from rep. john conyers, d-mich., that a member of cispes who had traveled to nicaragua had been interviewed by the fbi for ``intelligence gathering'' purposes
after thursday's hearing, cia spokesman william baker, who also served with webster at the fbi, noted that justice department reviews of such probes take place annually and that go-aheads for the cispes investigation had been given twice previously based on ``a valid predication'' that there was a conspiracy to commit terrorist acts
the investigation was based on circumstantial evidence, which the fbi was unable to document, that cispes members were sending money to the farabundo marti liberation front, the main insurgent group trying to overthrow the government of el salvador
in january, the center for constitutional rights released fbi documents obtained under the freedom of information act showing that the fbi had investigated cispes extensively
the investigation included photographing protesters at peace rallies and recording their license-plate numbers, investigating nuns, union members and college students and checking up on church forums, according to the documents
last month, sessions denied that the bureau had mounted a massive surveillance campaign, but did acknowledge that the investigation ``was not properly directed'' in all instances
py picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``we logically ...</note>
warplanes believed to be from honduras attacked a sandinista military headquarters in northern nicaragua near the honduran border, the presidential spokesman said thursday
manuel espinoza enriquez said the attack on bocay caused no injuries or damage. sandinista troops fired on the planes, forcing them to turn back to honduras, he said
he said the planes fired at least five rockets at the headquarters but did not say if any struck their target
the attack came a day after honduras charged that nicaraguan troops had entered its territory while pursuing u.s.-backed contra rebels
president daniel ortega said thursday that nicaragua was ready to ``combat and liquidate'' american troops sent to honduras after the reported incursion. he said his soldiers won't withdraw from the border region
ortega also called for a meeting of the u.n. security council to deal with what he called ``one more escalation of the war against nicaragua.''
we logically are going to maintain our offensive ... we are not going to withdraw our troops now that we have recovered our territory,'' he said
we are ready to combat and liquidate the famous forces of the 82nd airborne division,'' he said
earlier, a foreign ministry spokesman said nicaragua already had begun withdrawing troops from the border region after driving about 2,000 contra rebels back into honduras
the operations have succesfully been concluded, and we don't plan to stay along the border region. in fact, this deescalation has already begun,'' the spokesman, alejandro bendana, said on nbc's ``today'' show
ortega spoke to reporters before meeting with 14 opposition parties ``to explain to them the national and international situation.''
the 3,200 u.s. troops that began arriving in honduras on thursday include two battalions from the 82nd airborne at fort bragg, n.c
ortega called the u.s. troop movement ``a dangerous act'' and accused the united states of pressuring honduras into asking for the american presence
the c-141 planes carrying the u.s. troops were arriving every 30 minutes at palmerola air force base, the main center of u.s. military operations in honduras. the base is about 125 miles west of the border, where heavy fighting was reported wednesday
bendana denied u.s. and honduran allegations that sandinista troops entered honduras, and he invited the united nations and organization of american states to visit the area to ``establish what the facts are and end these accusations.''
ortega himself wouldn't say if sandinista troops crossed the border
here the question is not if (nicaraguan) army troops penetrated honduran tserritory or not, but that we have dozens of camps of mercenary forces in honduran territory, in view of and tolerated by the honduran government,'' he said
but honduran military officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said about 4,000 honduran soldiers were surrounding about 2,000 nicaraguan soldiers thursday. the sources said the entire honduran military was on alert
ortega told reporters the nicaraguan ``invasion only exists in the warped imagination of the north american leaders'' and said the sending of american troops ``violates international law and the regional peace efforts,'' he added
we demand that the united states withdraw its troops from honduras immediately and, with this, contribute to the meeting that is going to be held in sapoa march 21 having positive results,'' he said
government and contra representatives are scheduled to begin three days of peace talks monday in sapoa, a town in southern nicaragua near the border with costa rica
ortega said the united states would use the current situation to give the contras logistical and military aid not approved by congress
at the united nations, the nicaraguan mission confirmed that the government plans to ask for a meeting of the 15-member security council, the highest u.n. body
u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuella called for restraint in the conflicts but had not decided whether to send in an observer team
five current or former school bus drivers were among seven people arrested in an investigation into drug dealing and marijuana use, officials said wednesday
more arrests are expected
the problem was so great, we decided not to end this operation,'' said officer wayne hoskins of the department's drug enforcement unit. ``to me, this is one of the biggest things we've done. these guys were driving busloads of kids around. that bothers me as a citizen, not just a cop. my kids have rode those buses.''
hoskins said officer harold robinson posed as a bus driver to gather evidence. robinson made a drug buy within a week of being hired jan. 8, police said
he let it be known he was looking and it went down that quick,'' hoskins said. ``it's really unbelieveable how bad it was. we're talking about a lot of people involved in drugs down there.''
linda ethridge, president of the waco independent school district board, said the police investigation was prompted by a school district request
she said the wisd conducts background checks on those hired as bus drivers, but that sometimes those reviews fall short. there are about 150 drivers in the district
board members have in the past discussed whether to start drug-testing of drivers and will likely take up the matter in the future, she said
jafus cavil, vice president of the school board, said he doubted if the board could establish a drug-testing policy because ``i think there are some legal problems to it.''
federal agents arrested the current and former drivers monday and tuesday. the three current drivers were fired
hoskins said police monitored the drivers suspected of using drugs to ensure they were capable of driving
the undercover officer found both marijuana and cocaine sold and used at the bus barn before morning routes, hoskins said. after 3rd graf bgng ``she likened.''</note>
a group of anti-apartheid activists called on the south african government wednesday to commute the death sentences of six blacks who were involved in a 1984 demonstration during which a black deputy mayor was killed
molly yard, president of the national organization for women and a member of the free south africa committee, said the government of prime minister p.w. botha was using the death penalty in an effort to intimidate the country's black protest movement
she likened such tactics to those of nazi germany, contending that the pretoria government is ``on the road to totally obliterating all blacks except those who accept slavery.''
secretary of state george p. shultz telephoned south african foreign minister roelof (pik) botha to protest the plans to execute the six, department spokesman charles e. redman said
a protest also was delivered to the south african government by u.s. diplomats in pretoria
as the president said yesterday, we do hope that the south african government will heed this call for clemency,'' redman said
speaking at a news conference, yard urged congress to approve stronger sanctions and require total withdrawal of american business interests from south africa
now was joined at the session by representatives from transafrica, the washington lawyers committee for civil rights and the national conference of black lawyers, as well as aides to presidental candidate sen. paul simon, d-ill., and rep. mervyn dymally, d-calif., chairman of the congressional black caucus
the groups praised the reagan administration for joining the british and west german governments in asking for clemency in a telegram to botha
at the same time, they urged president reagan to end diplomatic relations with south africa and ask the western allies to join in a trade embargo
we've seen what this government can do against poland and panama,'' yard said ``why not south africa?''
the south african prisoners, known as the sharpeville six, were convicted in the sept. 3, 1984 killing of black township councilor jacob dlamini in sharpeville, about 40 miles south of johannesburg
evidence at their trial indicated that the six were not among those who hacked and burned dlamini to death. they were convicted under the doctrine of ``common purpose,'' which holds that they were responsible for the killing by being part of the mob that gathered outside of dlamini's home with intent to kill him
michael prosper, of the lawyers committee, told the news conference that dlamini, who refused to leave his home when south african police tried to take him to safety, had incited violence by firing several shots into the crowd
the plea for clemency also is supported by amnesty international, the united auto workers, the national coalition against the death penalty, the national council of churches and other national religious groups
the soviet union has bought an additional 200,000 metric tons of u.s. corn for delivery this year under a long-term supply agreement between the two countries, the agriculture department said wednesday
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. the 200,000 tons of corn would be about 7.9 million bushels
corn prices recently have been averaging about $1.83 per bushel at the farm level, meaning that the sale could have a farm value of around $14.5 million
the corn is part of the grain the soviet union is committed to buy during the fifth and final year of the agreement, which calls for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of u.s. grain. the pact expires sept. 30
according to the agreement, the annual purchases are supposed to include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. the soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain equivalent
with the latest purchases, the soviets now have bought 3.47 million tons of corn, plus more than 6.9 million tons of wheat; 813,300 tons of soybeans, and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal
christian lacroix scored a solid success in his first ready-to-wear show wednesday, keeping hemlines short and flirty
his show capped the first day of a big week for buyers and press who come to view what paris has to say about next winter's clothes. the consensus is that many influential designers plan to keep their skirts short. others will set hemlines zooming down
paris wonder-boy lacroix was most successful in his daytime clothes. his late-day dresses were inspired by moroccan folklore and the dance hall, a departure from the ``arlesienne'' look of previous collections
he had hinted he would show very simple clothes, but couldn't resist some occasional fantasy, and his offerings were anything but dull
the show started with a bang: hot-colored coats in all shapes from swirly trapeze to fitted, often with big fichu collars. the little suits in houndstooth checks or plaids with fitted jackets or tiny boleros were geared more to daily life then some of the costumey lines in his couture collections
simplicity, however, took away none of the pizazz of these outfits, which are priced ultra-moderately compared to his ``luxe'' or couture lines. made for him by genny of italy, the ready-to-wear ensembles are expected to sell for about $420 to $1,060
top sellers in this collection may be the fabulous silk jacquard full-skirted coat-dresses in coral, yellow and blue
lacroix was ebullient, with a fun-and-games approach in hats such as an animal-spotted stovepipe or tipped pyramids, to go with little satin beribboned ballerina shoes
he went in for some of his favorite full taffeta babydoll dresses with bows or pyramid shapes. his fluid black jersey waistless or fitted dresses with asymmetrical hemlines, topped by dresses with big white organza collars might appeal as well _ to those with conservative tastes
the fancier numbers included some ribbed sweaters with embroidered net tops over flying bright skirts. there were merry widow dresses too, complete with music-hall tights that had lace and garter effects under the full, bouncy skirts
in a circus vein, he branched out into some loud and crazy patchwork dresses with woolen balls and ribbons
the dressier silk or velvet outfits with moroccan jewelry and lace embroidery did not come off as well in this collection as the beautifully finished simpler clothes. but the audience loved it all anyway, and gave him a big hand for his peppy approach
in contrast to lacroix's exuberance, lolita lempicka's collection featuring mannish suits was down-to-earth to the point of boredom
in greys and black pinstripes with ties, the outfits had long pleated or short lean skirts, some of the jackets fitted, other spencer-style for office chic. more mannish looks featured trousers, making a comeback
streamlined long and loose princess coat dresses were winning in sober silvery grey, black or brown light wools
the satin and lace evening looks made an attempt at gaiety with their bubbling scalloped skirts, but they didn't quite hit the mark. and lace sleeves on man-tailored jackets over knit knickers were not quite successful in their androgynous aim for a masculine-feminine line
doby broda went in for sweaters on more sweaters _ a pullover v-neck topped by a cardigan with a shoulder shrug, sometimes over cuffed long or pedal-pusher pants. her skirt lengths in low-key outfits of mauve, beige or violet were either well above the knee or nearly to the ankle
kimijima's ``venetian carnival'' show was all in good fun, especially the evening wear with huge peplumed bright taffeta skirts, some harlequin-motif underskirts, and embroidered fitted tops
chantal thomass _ known as ``queen of lingerie'' _ toned down some of her risque touches in a bright, appealing show featuring lots of pink angora and black stockings with vine-like motifs up the front
her wrapped tops over very short lean or bubbled skirts were offset by some ankle-length numbers, often in soft pastel knits. equally appealing here might be the long and full cuffed pants and the coats _ either full trapeze style or in sober charcoal and white stripes fitted like short redingotes
in the first such cooperative effort with the people's republic of china, federal agents arrested three men in san francisco in connection with a 7-pound heroin shipment from china to the united states tucked away inside dead goldfish, the drug enforcement administration said wednesday
the goldfish were laden with southeast asian heroin which was sewn inside condoms, said dea spokesman cornelius dougherty. boxes of fish containing the heroin and bound for a business called the goldfish aquarium in san francisco were spotted by authorities in china on march 9
dea and u.s. customs service agents were alerted and authorities seized the heroin in china
most of the heroin was later resewn inside some of the fish, which were placed in the bottom of each of 20 boxes containing 50 to 60 live goldfish and shipped to the united states aboard an aircraft. a shanghai police official and a dea agent from hong kong accompanied the shipment to san francisco
the boxes were deposited in a cargo area and attached with transponders emitting a signal so that dea and customs agents could keep the boxes under electronic surveillance
two men picked up the boxes in san francisco and delivered them to the aquarium, where they were opened by three people then arrested by agents who had trailed them to the location. the three were arrested last friday. in addition, four people were arrested in china in connection with the shipment
the dea said it was the first time the united states and mainland china had worked together on a controlled delivery of heroin from china to the united states
tally bookmaking sheets also were recovered at the aquarium building, suggesting it was an illegal sports betting establishment, dougherty said
the house budget committee approved a $1.1 trillion federal budget for the 1989 fiscal year thursday that obeys congress' budget summit accord with president reagan, but scrambles some of his domestic spending priorities
the spending plan would leave a deficit of $134.1 billion, according to the budget panel, enough to avoid automatic spending cuts under the gramm-rudman budget-balancing law
the budget resolution, expected to be sent to the full house next week, was pieced together over the last several days during closed-door meetings among committee republicans and democrats. the panel approved the document, on a voice vote with no objections, during a five-minute public session
we've had a bipartisan process, with full participation by republican members,'' said committee chairman william h. gray iii
the bipartisan camaraderie was in stark contrast to last year, when republicans walked away from the budget resolution process and bickering lasted for months
but the budget pact reached last november between reagan and lawmakers locked in new taxes and spending levels for fiscal 1988 and 1989 for defense, foreign affairs and overall domestic spending
lawmakers are proving eager to avoid reopening those questions and sparking potentially bitter fights in an election year. thus, the main fight remaining has been over how to distribute the $169.2 billion the summit allows for the domestic programs that congress directly oversees and are not financed under automatic formulas
the key was the budget summit, which gave us the key ceilings for the spending categories which are usually most controversial,'' said rep. willis d. gradison jr. of ohio, senior committee republican at the meeting
in the 1989 budget he presented congress feb. 18, reagan proposed a 20 percent increase in spending on space and science programs to $13.1 billion. the budget panel, looking to restore proposed cuts to several other domestic programs, pared that increase to $12.2 billion
the committee felt that was a realistic figure for nasa to carry out its mission,'' gray said
where reagan proposed deep cuts in programs such as mass transit assistance and eliminating other programs such as federal aid to amtrak, the passenger railroad, the budget committee would retain current levels of spending or reduce it by 1 percent or 2 percent
for programs for low-income people such as job training and child health care, the budget panel's proposal would allow enough of a spending increase to keep up with inflation, expected to reach 4 percent this year
the committee's budget also rejects $1.2 billion in savings in medicare that reagan had proposed, spends $1.5 billion for aids research _ slightly more than the president proposed _ and retains previously planned levels of spending for education, fighting drugs and providing aid to the homeless
the panel also proposed a 3 percent pay raise for federal workers and civilian employees of the military. gray said lawmakers will have to decide later this year whether members of congress would qualify for the salary increases
the committee's budget leaves intact the summit agreement spending levels of $294 billion for military programs for the 1989 fiscal year, and $14 billion in new taxes. most of the levies are on corporations
the senate plans to write its budget resolution next month. the resolution does not need the president's signature, and it serves as a blueprint for actual spending legislation to be enacted later
the lawmakers chose the path of least political resistance in selecting the crucial economic assumptions that determine how healthy the government's balance sheet will appear
thus, to weigh the budget deficit, the lawmakers adopted the economic assumptions used by the president's office of management and budget. the committee chose not to use economic figures calculated by the congressional budget office, which has said red ink is actually $35 billion greater than omb estimates
under gramm-rudman, the deficit target for next year is $136 billion. the law states that spending would be automatically cut to that level if the deficit exceeds the target by $10 billion
the 1989 fiscal year begins oct. 1
the presidential candidates who made it through the costly super tuesday and illinois contests are now lining up fund-raising events to see them through the rest of the primary season
