in fact, she said, people have been calling unsolicited to pledge money and urge him not to drop out
these are republicans saying we think there should be a race,'' she said
on friday, callers pledged $140,000, on monday $95,000 and on tuesday $60,000, she said. still, she added, ``we're not bathing in dollars,'' and no decisions on tv advertising have been made for the campaign's next targeted state, wisconsin
dukakis spokesman mark gearan said the campaign raised $100,000 wednesday night in new york and is focusing on raising money for the new york and pennsylvania primaries. dukakis' strong showing in the 20-state super tuesday contests on march 8 has kept money flowing to him, he said
dukakis has about $1.5 million in the bank, not counting the more than $600,000 he got this week in federal matching funds, said spokesman leslie dach
for simon and gephardt, both of whom did poorly in the super tuesday races, the situation was not so bright, although both said they were not in debt
both also said they had record fund-raising months in february _ gephardt collecting $1.2 million and simon more than $900,000. a simon spokesman conceded, ``march will not be a record for us as february was.''
it's a day-to-day thing,'' said gephardt's spokesman mark johnson. ``we're using aggressive fund-raising'' techniques, mostly involving phone calls to contributors. ``you're at a point now where cash flow is very important, and you need a quick turnaround,'' he said
gephardt is is targeting michigan for a heavy advertising campaign, but johnson said he has no idea whether any loans will be taken out
simon spokesman david carle said that after paying off remaining bank debt thursday the campaign had around $300,000 in cash on hand. simon has scaled back his operation, laying off about 15 people at the campaign headquarters, on the heels of more than 250 layoffs after the iowa, new hampshire and super tuesday contests, carle said
simon collected about $60,000 at a chicago event monday night, and expected to bring in another $25,000 thursday night in new york
a mailing to simon's 50,000 contributors will go out next week, and unsolicited donations came in following simon's victory in his home state of illinois, carle said. he declined to give specific figures
simon will strongly contest wisconsin, with a large tv campaign, but will not buy ads in michigan, he said
susan butcher, winner for the third year in row of the 1,150-mile iditarod sled dog race, is a transplanted easterner who pursues the arctic sport with a passion
her victory was less than four minutes old wednesday night, but the intense, 34-year-old from manley hot springs already was thinking about next year's race _ and about breaking the magic 10-day mark
i think it can be done, and i'd like to be the one to do it,'' said butcher, who crossed the finish line in 11 days, 11 hours and 41 minutes, a record for the race's longer northern route from anchorage to nome
the record she broke was her own, set in 1986. last year, her winning time of 11 days, 2 hours set a record for the shorter southern route
butcher has run the race 11 times, finishing second twice and in the money _ or among the top 20 _ all but once, in 1985, when she scratched after a cow moose charged her 17-dog team, killing one animal and injuring five others
butcher is an outgoing, strongly built woman who works out daily along with teams from her 150-dog kennel. she once took four dogs to the summit of mount mckinley, at 20,320 feet, the highest peak in north america
dave monson, her lawyer husband, shares her passion for dog racing and several weeks ago won the equally challenging yukon quest international sled dog race from fairbanks to whitehorse in the yukon territory
butcher grew up in cambridge, mass., moving to colorado when she was 16 along with two siberian huskies she had bought as pets. there she worked as a veterinary technician
she moved to alaska in 1975 because she was looking for a wilderness lifestyle
butcher married monson two years ago and they live 140 miles from fairbanks in a 16-by-19-foot cabin with no running water and a gas-driven generator for electricity. she draws water for her 150 dogs from a nearby creek
of her $50,000 iditarod first-place prize in 1986, ``every cent went back into the kennels,'' she said
i train them 12 months of the year,'' butcher said in a recent interview. ``in summer i run dogs in harness pulling a four-wheel cart. once the snow starts falling, i run eight to 10 to a team from 10 to 50 miles a day.''
they're worth $1,000 to $6,000 apiece, so they're precious, besides the emotional involvement,'' she said
they love competition. they're professional athletes, and i'm more like a coach. coaching to victory is the job of a musher. the formula for winning is one-third musher, one-third dogs and one-third luck.'' to segen-cohen, not segen-cohel. picks up 9th graf pvs, a three-judge ...</note>
israel began its first major trials on thursday of soldiers charged with brutality in the arab rebellion, and palestinians wounded an israeli with gunfire for the first time since the violence began dec. 8
israeli warplanes raided palestinian guerrilla bases in the mountains south of beirut, and newspapers said secretary of state george p. shultz may return to the middle east early next month to promote the u.s. peace plan. the raid came a day after rockets landed in northern israel, causing light damage
authorities increased restrictions in the occupied territories, which already include travel bans and a cut-off of telephone service to the outside. a military official said palestinians must get approval to bring $1,000 or more from neighboring jordan, where most hold citizenship and have family
the rules are intended to hamper the palestine liberation organization in organizing and financing the protests
trials beginning thursday involved the burial alive of four arabs by an army bulldozer feb. 5 in kfar salem, a west bank village, and the beating feb. 24 of two palestinians near nablus, which was photographed by a cbs news crew
neighbors soon rescued the buried palestinians. the beating was televised around the world and aroused international protest
several weeks after trouble began in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, the army introduced a policy of beating rioters as an alternative to firing live ammunition. at least 100 palestinians have been killed in more than three months of violence, and hundreds wounded
yair nissimi and dror segen-cohen, both army privates, pleaded guilty in the burial case to reduced charges of shameful behavior. the plea bargain would give nissimi 2{ months in jail and segen-cohen two months, and both would be placed on probation
a three-judge panel is to rule march 29 on whether to accept the arrangement
sgt. maj. charlie danino pleaded innocent to assault and unbecoming conduct, and is expected to argue that he was not at the scene
mustafa hamdan, one of those buried, said of the plea bargain: ``they buried four people alive. if an arab did that they would have given him 200 years.''
defense lawyer josef danai said in court the burial was ``an instance of letting off steam, revenge and deterrence'' by soldiers in difficult circumstances
they spilled a little earth on them,'' he said. ``the tractor driver said an ant could have gotten out of it.''
sgt. amichai vaturi, who was at the scene but is not charged, testified that the arabs were covered with about two feet of wet earth but their heads and shoulders were exposed
hamdan said the heads of three men were covered
in the beating case, sagi harpaz and yehuda angel, army privates, pleaded innocent to assault and the case was recessed
two other soldiers were sentenced tuesday to 10 and 21 days in jail for minor roles in the beating
in the gaza strip, a 25-year-old khan yunis resident, subhi abu sharar, was shot in the chest and seriously wounded, said ilana ziv, spokeswoman for barzilai hospital in ashkelon
arab reports said israeli soldiers shot him during a demonstration
also in gaza, two arabs shot 44-year-old israeli contractor adi tzabari four times in the legs near jabalia refugee camp, ms. ziv said
tzabari told israel army radio ``i threw a hammer'' at one arab with a pistol, ``then another one appeared with a kalashnikov (assault rifle) and opened fire.''
the army confirmed the shooting. it was the first time an israeli, civilian or soldier, has been reported hit by arab gunfire since the beginning of what palestinians now call ``the uprising.''
an arab truck driver in the same area tried to run down an israeli soldier earlier thursday but the soldier escaped without injury, the army said
arab reports from jabaliya said the army fired tear gas and rubber bullets at 800 schoolgirls who stoned soldiers, raised palestinian flags and burned tires
officials of a u.n. clinic said 25 girls were treated for minor injuries. palestine press service, an arab-run news agency, said soldiers in the west bank arrested 150 palestinians overnight in nablus, jenin, qabitiyeh, ramallah and hebron
arab reporters said the army blocked dairy and produce deliveries to nablus, tulkarm and jericho
the army said these reports were being checked. raided</head> graf pvs, two battalions ... with minor editing to trim; insert 2 grafs after 20th graf pvs, a spokesman ... updating with air raid. picks up 21st graf pvs, heavy fighting ...</note>
planeloads of u.s. soldiers streamed into this air base thursday in a show of strength ordered by president reagan to counter what he called an invasion by nicaraguan forces
in northern nicaragua, warplanes raided a sandinista military headquarters thursday, but no casualties or damage resulted, nicaragua said. a reagan administration source, speaking on condition of anonymity, confirmed in washington that honduras launched the raid, but called it ``totally a honduran operation.''
two battalions from the renowned 82nd airborne division of fort bragg, n.c., and two battalions from the 7th light infantry division of fort ord, calif., were combined into a task force of 3,000 troops
a honduran official said his government had given the sandinistas 24 hours to get out of the country, which they entered in pursuit of contra rebels
president daniel ortega of nicaragua responded that his army was ``ready to combat and liquidate the famous forces of the 82nd airborne division.''
maj. gen. carl w. stiner, commander of the 82nd airborne, said he knew of no plan to have u.s. troops enter into the battle between the sandinistas and the u.s.-backed -contras
we have not been told to do so,'' he said before leaving fort bragg. he said the force was capable of that, if needed
the american troops were to engage in joint exercises with the hondurans
stiner also said there was no plan to use the troops if more trouble broke out in nearby panama
the american forces began arriving at palmerola at 10:15 a.m. as part of what the pentagon called operation ``golden pheasant.''
the 26 c-141 transport planes landed in the intense heat at 30-minute intervals at this air base, headquarters of u.s. military operations in honduras, 40 miles northwest of tegucigalpa
the deployment was about 125 miles west of the area where reagan administration officials say the nicaraguan sandinista army has chased rebel contra forces over the border into honduras
col. manuel suarez benavides, honduran armed forces spokesman, said the deadline for the sandinistas to leave was final
he said 2,000 nicaraguan soldiers had crossed the border and penetrated about six miles in pursuit of contra rebels. a military intelligence source said earlier the nicaraguans were surrounded by about 4,000 honduran troopers
suarez benavides would not comment on pentagon reports of new nicaraguan attacks inside honduras
the sandinista movements did not appear to be a full-fledged invasion, stiner said, adding that he saw the u.s. operation as a deterrent
ortega would not say whether his soldiers had crossed the border in pursuit of the u.s.-supported rebels
here the question is not if army troops penetrated honduran territory or not, but that we have dozens of camps of mercenary forces in honduran territory, in view of and tolerated by the honduran government,'' he said at a news conference in managua
he said nicaraguan soldiers would not withdraw from the border area. ortega called the u.s. troop deployment ``a dangerous act'' and ``another escalation of the war against nicaragua.'' he demanded a meeting of the u.n. security council
a spokesman for the nicaraguan foreign ministry said before the news conference that nicaragua had begun pulling its troops back from the frontier region after driving about 2,000 contra rebels back into honduras. the defense and foreign ministries denied that nicaraguan troops entered honduras
nicaraguan presidential spokesman manuel espinoza enriquez later said that air attackers fired at least five rockets thursday at the nicaraguan military headquarters at bocay, near the honduras border. sandinista gunfire forced the planes to turn back, he said
the u.s. official in washington said two honduran air force f-5s and four super-mystere attack jets carried out the assault, destroying a soviet-built helicopter on the ground
heavy fighting was reported wednesday in the olancho border province about 125 miles east of palmerola
included in the american forces are two battalions from the 82nd airborne and two from a new division organized for quick movement around the world. the 82nd airborne and 7th light infantry are based at opposite ends of the country
the final 800 u.s. troops are to arrive friday by parachute, weather permitting
in addition to the c-141 aircraft, a giant c-5a transport was loaded with helicopter gunships for the exercise
the honduran intelligence source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said: ``we will not allow the sandinistas to move farther into the interior of our territory. we want to avoid a large conflict, but if it isn't possible, we will have to face the invading troops.''
secretary of state george p. shultz said in washington the soldiers were not being sent in ``a shooting capacity'' but to ``get people's attention to what is happening in central america'' and say to the honduran government: ``we are your friends.''
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the complete deployment would take about 27 hours. the defense department said the soldiers had their normal weapons along with nine helicopters and two light tanks
it was the the most dramatic show of u.s. force since the contras began fighting in nicaragua six years ago, and came in response to a request for help from president jose azcona hoyo of honduras
since 1981, honduras has been a key u.s. ally in central america and a major element in reagan administration policy of fighting nicaragua's leftist government
about 1,100 american soldiers normally are stationed at several military installations in honduras. in addition, other national guard and army troops rotate through for joint exercises, road-building and other projects
a house committee chairman called wednesday for the resignation of a high-ranking education department official who was quoted in a published report as saying students at black colleges include ``a high level of thieves.''
rep. augustus hawkins, d-calif., chairman of the house education and labor committee, said the remarks by deputy undersecretary bruce carnes make him ``incapable of objectively carrying out his duties. he is not qualified for this or any position in federal government.''
in a story tuesday about a crackdown on student loan defaults, the wall street journal quoted carnes as saying: ``the sector that will be hit hardest by this will be black colleges. it's possible that their student bodies contain a high level of thieves.''
but carnes said in a statement that ``i have no recollection of saying that or anything remotely like that. it's completely at variance with everything i have said before on this topic, and with what i believe.''
gary putka, the reporter who wrote the story, said he has carnes' comment in his written notes and stands by the quote. ``he hasn't denied it to us nor has he asked us for a correction or retraction,'' putka said
in a letter to the journal, dated tuesday, carnes said the newspaper article ``has grievously misrepresented my views concerning black colleges and their students. in fact it ascribes to me a view that is precisely the opposite of the one i hold and have repeatedly stated.''
education department spokesman loye miller said the letter did not demand a retraction because the newspaper would have refused to publish it that way
hawkins called on education secretary william bennett to remove carnes from his position if carnes did not resign. hawkins also said he had written to president reagan about the incident
miller said carnes has repeatedly said he does not believe stiffer penalties and enforcement in the area of student loan defaults will be a special problem for historically black colleges
miller also said he has heard carnes rebuff people who say such colleges need an exemption from the default crackdown because their students are less reliable about paying back loans
in his letter to the journal, carnes said students at historically black colleges ``are as capable as others of meeting their commitments.'' he said the department is holding workshops and seminars to help historically black colleges with high default rates manage their student loans. dukakis endorsements</note>
democratic presidential contenders debated long-distance with republican bob dole thursday over the dispatch of u.s. troops to central america, with richard gephardt charging the administration had ``abandoned the rule of law.''
dole called for u.s. military help for the nicaraguan contra rebels, who he said were being ``slaughtered by the hundreds.''
but jesse jackson, campaigning in michigan, said, ``we are being told we have to be saved from the sandinistas. there are no sandinistas in detroit.''
jackson also included vice president george bush, the gop presidential front-runner, in his verbal attack. commenting one day after former white house aide oliver north and three other men were indicted for their roles in the iran-contra money diversion, jackson said, ``in a real sense, the mailmen have taken the rap for the postmaster.''
north and the others are fall guys in the process. ... this investigation must conclude the fact that this is president reagan's policy and the fact that mr. bush knew about the scheme,'' he said
sen. paul simon said of the troop deployment, ``i'm skeptical like a lot of my colleagues. i don't know what i can trust from the administration.''
massachusetts gov. dukakis not only criticized the administration's central american moves but also laid into bush for refusing to break with reagan over a civil rights bill the president vetoed on wednesday
reagan has complained the bill would expand federal power, and he has offered a substitute. but dukakis said, ``there's a very basic principle involved here. that is that institutions which receive money from the government should not discriminate.''
bush spokesman pete teeley said the vice president has not publicly discussed his views of the issue, and he said, ``we're not going to respond to dukakis.''
dukakis, meanwhile, made the rounds on capitol hill on thursday, picking up the endorsements of several lawmakers _ sen. barbara mikulski of maryland, sen. patrick leahy of vermont and sen. donald riegle and rep. howard wolpe, both of michigan
pat robertson, still in the gop race but apparently making only a token effort the rest of the way, was hoping to bring in needed cash at a california fund-raiser
bush and dukakis had fund-raising events on their schedules, too, and so did illinois democratic primary winner simon, as the candidates took advantage of a primary season lull to catch their breath and pick up campaign money for the series of big-state primaries next month
dukakis praised democratic national chairman paul kirk and new york gov. mario cuomo for their recent comments against deciding the party's nominee at a brokered convention _ as simon has said is inevitable _ and in favor of settling the matter beforehand. dukakis paraded new endorsements from two senators whose states have already voted _ barbara mikulski of maryland and patrick leahy of maine _ and sought support from two others _ bill bradley of new jersey and donald riegle of michigan
the massachusetts governor also compared himself to former vice president walter mondale, who lost the general election in a landslide to reagan after a tough fight to win the nomination in 1984
this is a long process,'' dukakis said of his wins and losses in primaries so far. ``mondale in '84 lost a whole string of primaries and pulled it out, numerically, with new jersey. if there's one campaign that's doing it primary by primary, caucus by caucus, it's this campaign.''
gephardt was campaigning hard in michigan ahead of march 26 caucuses there. the missouri congressman, who fell far behind dukakis, sen. albert gore and simon on super tuesday, is traveling the state in a bus while his 80-year-old mother, loreen, has been making the rounds of radio talk shows in detroit
gore was on the campaign trail, too, but was having weather problems in kansas, where democratic caucuses will be held saturday
the tennessee senator, who bypassed the year's lead-off contests in iowa and new hampshire, got a taste thursday of the cold, snowy campaigning he missed in those states. he greeted workers arriving at a boeing plant in wichita, which had been hit by late-winter snow. and his next stop in pittsburg, kan., was canceled because the airport there had no de-icing equipment
gore, in a news conference later in topeka, was less critical than several of his democratic rivals of the reagan administration's sending of troops to honduras. but he did say, ``i think it was wrong to mislead the congress and fail to provide the information about what led up to the decision.''
he also said, ``i think the president erred in not virgorously pursuing'' a peace plan offered by the president of costa rica
dole, in a speech on the senate floor, declared that the nicaraguan contra rebels were being overrun and ``slaughtered by the hundreds,'' and he said reagan should immediately resubmit a request for military aid
does it make sense, even as thousands of communist troops cross the border of a free country in this hemisphere, for members of congress to make excuses for (nicaragua's) aggression, while accusing the president of the united states of fueling the fires of war in central america?'' dole asked
gephardt, however, in a statement released by his office in washington, strongly criticized reagan for sending troops to honduras
now we have this overreaction that puts american troops in harm's way,'' he said. ``this `exercise' serves no purpose but to draw us into a war that the american people oppose.''
gephardt said, ``in pursuit of its failed policy of support for the contras, the administration has lost its sense of direction, abandoned the rule of law and failed to protect american national interests in a troubled region.''
dukakis said to reporters in boston that the decision to send troops was ``very regrettable.''
the army announced wednesday it had decided to begin purchasing a specialized west german military reconnaissance vehicle rather than continue development of its own
the decision ultimately could be worth $790 million to west germany and demonstrates the u.s. commitment ``to nato standardization and cooperation,'' the army said
the decision involves a unique type of wheeled reconnaissance vehicle outfitted for use in a battle zone contaminated by either nuclear radioactivity or biological and chemical agents
the west german version of the vehicle is known as the ``abc-spuerpanzer fuchs'' and is made by thyssen henschel of kassel, west germany. the u.s. army calls the german vehicle the ``fox nbc reconnaissance vehicle.''
the fox wheeled vehicle has been in service with german forces since 1979,'' the army said. ``a version of it has been recently fielded as a reconnaissance vehicle with imbedded nuclear and chemical detection, warning and navigation equipment
the army will adopt (this) vehicle ..., terminating funding for the xm87 nbc reconnaissance vehicle program.''
maj. randy morger, a pentagon spokesman, said the army intended to purchase six of the fox vehicles in the near future for about $1 million each in order to perform final acceptance tests
ultimately, the service may spend about $790 million to acquire 576 of the vehicles. that pricetag would include adding some additional sensor, data processing and radio equipment to the vehicle, morger said. planes into nicaragua; picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``more than ...; inserts 1 graf after 9th graf pvs, ``honduras has ... to update with details.</note>
planes from honduras attacked a sandinista military headquarters in northern nicaragua at noon thursday, but president daniel ortega's office said they caused no casualties or damage
reporters on the scene confirmed the raid, which came the day after honduras accused the nicaraguans of sending thousands of soldiers across the border in pursuit of u.s.-supported contra rebels
a reagan administration source in washington said the honduran air force had carried out the attack. however, a honduran armed forces spokesman in tegucigalpa, the capital, denied the armed forces had crossed into nicaragua and said rockets were fired at sandinista forces in honduran territory
more than 3,000 american soldiers began arriving in honduras in a show of support thursday. ortega declared his army ready to ``combat and liquidate'' the americans and said his soldiers will not withdraw from the border region
nicaragua has committed an estimated 6,000 soldiers to an anti-rebel operation in an area running from the central region to the border, with most of them at the frontier
manuel espinoza enriquez, spokesman for ortega, said the attack on bocay, near the border, caused no injuries or damage. he said nicaraguan soldiers fired on the planes, forcing them to turn back
at least five rockets were fired at the headquarters, he said, but did not say whether any hit the target
the u.s. official in washington said two u.s.-built f-5s and four super-mystere attack jets of the honduran air force carried out the assault, destroying one of nicaragua's soviet-made helicopters on the ground
this was totally a honduran operation,'' the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity
honduras has one of central america's smallest armies and relies on air superiority for defense. it and mexico are the only nations in the region with jet fighters
manuel suarez, the honduran armed forces spokesman, said in a telephone interview that the air force dropped at least five bombs inside honduras along the border region near bocay. he said he had no further information
ortega called the dispatch of u.s. troops to honduras ``one more escalation of the war against nicaragua'' and demanded a meeting of the u.n. security council
