the interior department said wednesday a proposed 358-mile northeast natural gas pipeline is unacceptable because its route across the appalachian trail would create scenic and environmental problems
but the project developer vowed to work with federal park officials to find a new route across the hiking trail that would be acceptable
interior secretary donald p. hodel, in a letter to sen. lowell p. weicker jr. r-conn., said he rejected the iroquois proposal because the pipeline would cross the 2,000-mile appalachian trail at a point in new york near the connecticut border where it would have ``significant environmental and scenic impacts.''
gary b. davis, spokesman for the iroquois gas transmission system, said he was confident the company could find a route across the trail that would satisfy hodel
the plan now is to find a place along the new york-connecticut border where we can cross,'' davis said. ``we will have to sit down with the park service again and discuss our concern. ... something will have to be worked out.''
the pipeline, which would begin in ontario, would have to cross the appalachian trail at some point on any route to long island because the trail runs from maine to georgia. the pipeline would serve connecticut, new york and new jersey
the $384 million project is the first and most prominent northeast gas line proposal under consideration by the federal energy regulatory commission
but deputy assistant interior secretary susan recce said the u.s. park service, which is under the interior department, has jurisdiction over anything affecting the appalachian trail, which is part of the national park system
hodel's ruling was based on the recommendation of a park service survey in january
the pipeline would have crossed the appalachian trail at dover, n.y., in eastern dutchess county, n.y., near sherman, conn. davis said that site was chosen becaue at&amp;t telephone lines already cut across the trail there
meanwhile, the federal energy regulatory commission on wednesday took its first procedural step in reviewing the applications of 31 northeast projects. iroquois was the first application submitted, nearly two years ago
it's important because a procedure is now moving forward,'' davis said. ``after 22 months, finally ferc is starting to take some action on our application.''
the licensing consideration is going ahead under traditional ferc guidelines
iroquois had pushed to have the project considered under a ``fast-track'' procedure that would have avoided a series of lengthy hearings. but that attempt, opposed by weicker and other officials in connecticut, has been in effect been abandoned by the company, davis said
opponents argued that the fast-track procedure was designed for smaller projects. civil defense ending search thursday night. adds one graf with background on plane</note>
a domestic jetliner with 137 people aboard crashed during a storm in the northern colombia mountains thursday and burst into flames, with no immediate sign of survivors, officials said
the boeing 727 had just left cucuta, about 250 miles northeast of bogota, and crashed on a mountain near zulia, police at the town said, quoting witnesses. zulia is about 50 miles north of cucuta
the civil aeronautics agency, which reported the avianca flight missing soon after takeoff, said it could not confirm the crash. it said two search planes and three helicopters searched for the aircraft in the remote mountainous region where it was reported to have crashed
zulia police said three witnesses reported that the plane clipped some trees, then slammed into a mountain and burned, and they saw no survivors
passengers included a roman catholic auxiliary bishop and members of two colombian soccer teams
we heard a tremendous noise ... and ran toward the mountain where we saw the ruins of the plane,'' said victor pineda villamizar, a schoolteacher, in an interview with the radio network rcn
the teacher said local rescuers could not reach the crash site, which he said was at about 8,000 feet
in bogota, col. edgar lozano, a spokesman for the government air transport agency, said the search would continue at dawn friday. civil defense, police and red cross search teams suspended their efforts late thursday
according to the government agency, the plane left cucuta near the venezuelan border at 1:16 p.m. for barranquilla, a caribbean port 250 miles northwest, and then was to continue to the port city of cartagena
avianca and the government air transport agency reported the plane left with 131 passengers and six crew members. the agency and airline earlier had given different numbers
the agency said the control tower at cucuta lost radio contact with the plane four minutes after takeoff as the aircraft traveled in stormy weather. the agency said the plane did not report mechanical problems
it was on the route, but it was flying at a very low altitude,'' said a spokesman at the control tower, who spoke on condition of anonymity
the agency said the passenger list included a roman catholic auxiliary bishop, monsignor horacio olave velandia of tibu, and at least 31 soccer players from two teams who were flying to a tournament in cartagena
olave velandia, 44, was named an auxiliary bishop last month. the soccer teams were affiliated with the state petroleum company ecopetrol
colombia's last major air crash occurred july 27, 1985, when an air force transport plane went down in the amazon jungle, killing 74 people. it was carrying passengers because of an airline strike
the boeing 727 began flights in 1963 and is currently being flown by more than 170 carriers. the 727 was the best-selling jetliner in history until it was recently surpassed by the 737
upcoming in about 10 minutes, a 5th ld-writethru to am-colombia-plane, a0923, to update with civil defense confirming no survivors in crash
an explosion and fire touched off by a mislabeled or contaminated gas cylinder struck a chemical plant thursday, killing three men and seriously injuring one, officials said
the fire at the gollob analytical services plant burned out of control for more than 4{ hours. officer david bogert said he felt the early morning blast from the police station 1{ miles away
the blast occurred after an employee of a distributor arrived to remove the cylinder at gollob's request because tests showed it did not contain the nitrous oxide ordered, said state environmental commissioner richard t. dewling
the tank ``either was mislabeled or contaminated somehow,'' and gollob had asked it be removed immediately, dewling said
from there on we don't know what happened,'' he said. ``we don't know whether they were loading it onto a truck, moving it or what.'' he said it is not known whether the cylinder itself blew up or leaked gas that caused an explosion
the fire gutted the one-story, 10,000 square-foot cinderblock building and forced the evacuation of about 30 night-shift workers in nearby buildings, officials said
fire chief michael amodeo said the three men who died were found outside the plant and appeared to have been trying to escape
dewling would not identify the distributor of the gas, saying the matter was under investigation. gollob, which has been in business for 22 years, tests chemicals
a department manager and a technical director were killed in the blast and fire, officials said. the third person killed had not been identified
james diemer, 30, of leonia, was injured, and one leg was amputated below the knee at university hospital in newark, said a nursing supervisor
authorities said it was not immediately known whether he worked for gollob or the distributor
port-au-prince, haiti (ap) _ the government of president leslie manigat vowed wednesday to crack down on narcotics trafficking, but made no specific mention of the u.s. indictment of col. jean-claude paul on drug charges
a communique signed by martial celestin, the prime minister and minister of justice, and by foreign affairs minister gerard latortue, declared:
the government ... reiterates its determination to struggle against drug (trafficking) ... and confirms its desire to cooperate with foreign governments in the struggle against drug trafficking in which haiti could be used as a point of transit
in any precise case implicating an individual or institution . .. the government would appreciate receiving ... a complete file, solidly documented with evidence, which would be transferred to (judicial) authorities.''
a federal grand jury in miami on march 9 indicted paul, his brother and paul's former wife in connection with a 220-pound shipment of cocaine allegedly flown to the bahamas in a plane that left paul's ranch outside the capital port-au-prince. the cocaine was said to be florida-bound
paul, a battalion commander in port-au-prince, denied the charges, and haitian officials said they never were officially notified of the indictment
u.s. embassy spokesman jeffrey lite, however, said ambassador brunson mckinley personally notified manigat last thursday. lite said a complete judicial file will be delivered to the haitian government within two weeks
the indictment was seen as putting manigat in a touchy position. he came to power in a jan. 17 election that rival candidates said was rigged by the army
radio stations meanwhile reported wednesday that the chamber of deputies almost unanimously approved the cabinet proposed by manigat and celestin, with minor changes
manigat has been without an official cabinet since taking office feb. 7
parliament rejected a proposed cabinet last thursday, arguing that the state could not afford to maintain 14 ministries
agreement on a cabinet was reached tuesday evening
hundreds of british troops took off wednesday night on an 8,000-mile practice airlift to reinforce the remote falklands islands garrison in the south atlantic
the first of up to 10 transport planes carrying 900 troops departed at about 10 p.m. from brize norton royal air force base, 60 miles northwest of london, said a defense ministry spokesman, who was not identified in keeping with british custom
it was part of britain's controversial fire focus military exercise, which marks britain's first major drill in the falklands since it won a 1982 war with argentina over the islands. the 25-day exercise began march 7
phantom fighter jets and other planes will fly in from other british bases, royal air force spokesman michael hill said
argentina, backed by other latin american nations, has called the $690 million troop movement ``aggravating.'' britain insisted it is defensive
in the falklands, gen. neil carlier told reporters at mount pleasant airport ``it is much cheaper to mount an exercise like this than to hold a vast number of people down here at taxpayers' expense which might also, perhaps, send out the wrong signals.''
carlier called the nature of the exercise misunderstood and said the airlift was needed because ``we've just set up in a new base and not yet had the opportunity to prove the system for having reinforcements.''
the 2,000 troops stationed on the south atlantic archipelago were placed in a state of high readiness to prepare for the arrival of the reinforcements thursday and friday, he said
the reinforcements will include troops taking the role of the enemy. advance personnel, equipment and reporters arrived tuesday
britain built the airport after the 1982 war to accommodate wide-bodied jets which could be used to rush troops there in the event of a build-up of tension in the region
in 1982, argentine forces invaded the islands. lack of a suitable runway forced britain to form a naval task force that took weeks to reach the islands
britain recaptured the colony after a 74-day conflict which killed 712 argentines, 255 britons and three falkland islands civilians
argentina, 200 miles west of the islands, claims it inherited the falklands from spanish colonial days and that they were stolen by britain, which has ruled them as a colony since 1833
the 1,900 islanders, most of british descent, say they prefer british rule
this month, the organization of american states voted 25-0 to urge britain to reconsider the exercise. the united states and st. lucia, a former british colony, abstained
a federal energy official said wednesday the planned superconducting super collider is generating widespread interest abroad, but several lawmakers said the project is threatened by a lack of financing and firm commitments from interested foreign countries
james f. decker, the energy department's acting director for energy research, told a house subcommittee that the government hopes to get up to 40 percent of the estimated $4.3 billion cost from foreign and non-federal sources
decker said recent energy department missions to rome, paris, london, bonn, geneva, tokyo and ottawa found high interest in the project at every stop, with indications that financial support will be forthcoming
the discussions with japan and other countries were fairly significant and give us reason to believe there will be contributions,'' decker said at a hearing of the house subcommittee on international scientific cooperation
asked repeatedly about specific commitments, decker said it was premature to obtain them
all countries were interested in the scientific phase and some would contribute to the construction phase as well,'' decker said, predicting that contributions would be in goods and services rather than cash
potential contributor nations ``will be watching support in congress this year and your decision will guide theirs,'' decker said
that prompted rep. robert a. roe, d-n.j., to describe financing as a ``chicken and egg situation'' since congress is waiting to see how much outside money will be contributed
it's a ``catch-22 predicament in which the department says it can't get foreign money until domestic spending for ssc is approved, and we respond that we can't permit domestic spending until enough foreign money has been committed,'' said rep. sherwood boehlert, r-n.y
we've got to have some help from other countries,'' said roe, chairman of the full science, space and technology committee
the government is spending $25 million on super collider preparations this year and has requested $363 million for 1989
rep. ron packard, r-calif., said he has found in talks abroad that theoretical physicists were highly enthusiastic about the u.s. project and ready to lobby for financial support of it with the less-enthusiatic officials of their governments and research institutions
vietnam charged wednesday that chinese warships attacked three vietnamese freighters near disputed islands in the south china sea, then blocked rescue efforts
china blamed vietnam for the raid and said some chinese were wounded in the exchange of gunfire. foreign ministry spokeswoman li jihua refused to say how many people were hurt
vietnam has not reported any casualties
the official voice of vietnam radio said the freighters had been on fire since the attack monday near sinh ton island in the truong sa archipelago, which vietnam claims
the islands, also known as the spratly islands, are claimed by china, taiwan and the philippines
the vietnamese side sent lifeboats flying red cross flags to rescue those freighters, but they were obstructed by chinese warships,'' said the vietnamese broadcast, monitored in bangkok
the vietnamese side urged the chinese side to order its warships to move away from this area and not to prevent the vietnamese ships from coming to the rescue of the crews on these freighters. the vietnamese side wishes a favorable and early reply from the chinese side,'' it added
the radio said vietnam's foreign ministry made the charges in a meeting wednesday with li shuching, beijing's ambassador to hanoi
vietnam said the clash began when three chinese warships opened fire without provocation on two vietnamese freighters. the warships then fired on other vietnamese freighters that came to the rescue, the radio said
but ms. li of china's foreign ministry said vietnamese naval ships fired on chinese vessels and on teams doing a scientific survey on a reef
ms. li refused to disclose how many chinese were wounded, whether they were civilians or military personnel or other details
vietnam had charged that chinese naval vessels interferred with vietnamese cargo ships near the archipelago on jan. 31
there are believed to be oil deposits near the archipelago, about 300 miles south of china's hainan island
china was a major arms supplier to the vietnamese communists during the war against the french and the americans, but relations later deteriorated and the two countries fought a 17-day border war in 1979
china's most famous journalist, ousted from the communist party last year for his reports critical of the government, will spend a year in the united states on a fellowship, his wife said wednesday
liu binyan, a reporter and writer whose stories uncovered official corruption and inefficiency, was a winner of harvard university's prestigious nieman fellowship, his wife zhu hong said. she said he will leave friday
the former senior reporter for the official people's daily will teach at the university of california in los angeles for two months before going to harvard in the fall, she said
liu, 63, was expelled from the party in 1957 and again in january 1987, when he was accused of vilifying the party and attacking marxism. he was dismissed from his post at people's daily, mouthpiece of the communist party, in may 1987
however, he has remained vice chairman of the chinese writers' association
in a statement on liu's expulsion, the party charged that he ``confounded right and wrong and spread slanderous rumors.''
liu was one of three prominent intellectuals ousted from the party in the campaign against ``bourgeois liberalization,'' or the favoring of western ideas, that began after student demonstrations in support of democracy flared across china
astrophysicist fang lizhi, accused of inciting the student protests, and writer wang ruowang were also purged
liu, who taught himself english, had a standing offer from harvard since 1983 to take the nieman fellowship, which is given each year to a handful of american and foreign journalists, zhu said
publication of three of liu's books was suspended and a ban was put on the sale of a collection of his articles, called ``tell you a secret,'' after his ouster from the party
he has not been able to publish anything since
liu's writing, whether investigative reporting or fiction, has long irritated officials
during the ``hundred flowers'' movement in 1956, when intellectuals were encouraged to express themselves, liu wrote ``bridge worksite,'' in which he criticized a group of bureaucrats, and a novel, ``news behind the news,'' about the ideological struggles and politics at a newspaper
both works were branded ``poisonous weeds'' in the crackdown the next year, and liu was expelled from the party and sent to work as a janitor
he was barred from writing for more than 20 years
during the chaotic 1966-76 cultural revolution, liu was accused of being a soviet spy and a traitor, sent to a labor camp and forbidden to speak to his family for four years
he was quoted as saying it was the worst period in his life and only the thought that ``no one would know the truth'' prevented him from committing suicide
liu was rehabilitated in 1979 and joined the staff of the people's daily
that same year, he published his most famous work, ``between men and monsters,'' about a county party secretary who amassed a fortune by taking bribes and using her power to extort money from subordinates
a truck carrying a crane knocked out supports below a freeway overpass under construction wednesday, dislodging a 22,000-pound steel beam that killed the driver and pierced a car's roof, officials said
the driver of the car escaped injury, fire capt. ron cervantes
the truck driver, who was not immediately identified, was driving about 35 mph when the crane struck the beam's metal supports. the beam crushed the driver's compartment, cervantes said
wood and other construction debris from the overpass smashed on to the busy interstate 5 in the 1:30 p.m. accident 15 miles north of downtown san diego, closing the northbound route between san diego and los angeles
it was like lincoln logs, falling and collapsing all around the crane truck,'' said motorist ellen williams, who saw the accident from a freeway ramp
the truck driver had a state permit to use the freeway but apparently violated a prohibition against driving in areas with low clearance, cervantes said. the construction material had reduced clearance under the overpass, he said
construction crews working on the overpass were uninjured. prison</head>
cathy evelyn smith, the rock 'n' roll groupie who admitted giving comedian john belushi the heroin-cocaine ``speedballs'' that killed him in 1982, was freed from prison wednesday after serving 15 months
ms. smith, 40, a native of canada, faces immediate deportation, said joe flanders, a spokesman for the immigration and naturalization service
she was paroled from the california institution for women in frontera after serving the full term imposed, said hal tanner, chief deputy superintendent. she was a model prisoner, he said
ms. smith accompanied belushi, the manic comic who parlayed his popularity on the ``nbc saturday night'' tv show into starring roles in such movies as ``animal house'' and ``the blues brothers,'' on a drug binge that ended in a bungalow at the chateau marmont hotel on hollywood's sunset strip
belushi, 33, was found dead march 5, 1982, in the bungalow
ms. smith later admitted she and the comic injected ``speedballs,'' a potent combination of cocaine and heroin, but denied any responsibility for his death
she fled to canada but returned in 1986 to plead guilty to involuntary manslaughter and furnishing and administering a controlled substance. she originally was charged with second-degree murder and drug counts, but accepted a plea bargain
she will appear within a few days at a deportation hearing, flanders said
ms. smith has been a companion and backup singer for such entertainers as hoyt axton and gordon lightfoot and has been acquainted over the years with members of the rolling stones and the band
a united airlines 747 knocked the anti-collision beacon off a small, private plane at seattle-tacoma international airport as the jet taxiied for takeoff to hong kong, officials said wednesday
the jet sustained a 10-inch scratch tuesday but continued on its way after an hour and 45 minute delay for inspection. the private plane was unoccupied, said frank mcanulty, station manager for united airlines at the airport
no one was injured
the federal aviation administration and the airline are investigating. ^by oldemar ramirez</byline>
guatemala called wednesday for a meeting of central american foreign ministers to discuss crises in nicaragua and panama, but the planned session fell through, officials in costa rica said
a costa rican foreign ministry official, who spoke on condition he not be identified, did not say why the talks could not be arranged
he said guatemala's foreign ministry had called for the meeting of the five countries that signed a peace accord last august
the ministers were to discuss ways to mediate a solution to the panama crisis, in which opposition forces and the united states are pressing for the ouster of gen. manuel antonio noriega, head of the defense forces
the meeting also would have addressed nicaragua's military offensive against contra rebels on the country's border with honduras, the official said. honduran officials and the reagan administration said the sandinistas crossed into the neighboring country during the offensive
rodrigo madrigal nieto, costa rica's foreign minister, told the associated press earlier wednesday his government was particularly preoccupied with the increased fighting in nicaragua, which occurred just before the sandinista government and the contras were to hold three days of cease-fire talks
the talks are scheduled to take place in the southern nicaragua town of sapoa on monday
president oscar arias of costa rica won the nobel peace prize for sponsoring the peace plan, which called for talks between insurgents and governments in nicaragua, el salvador and guatemala
madrigal nieto also expressed concern about panama, where a group of officers tried unsuccessfully to overthrow noriega on wednesday. thousands of panamanians angry about his rule and the government's inability to pay their salaries poured into the streets
what happened today in panama shows there is a very delicate situation in central america that does not cooperate with the pacification efforts that have come about,'' the foreign minister said
the central american peace plan calls for cease-fires in el salvador, guatemala and nicaragua, an end to outside support for the area's insurgencies, and negotiations aimed at installing democratic governments, among other points
loma linda medical center said wednesday it has agreed to care for a second baby born with only a brain stem in hopes that her organs can be used for transplant
the newly arrived infant, a girl identified only as baby cassandra, was born tuesday at a small hospital in texas with a fatal condition known as anencephaly, in which most of the brain and skull are missing
at her parents' request, the infant was incubated and placed on a respirator,'' ms. mcclintock said in a statement
dr. joyce peabody, chief of neonatology at the medical center, said baby cassandra already is very close to meeting the clinical criteria for brain death. once that occurs, her organs will become available for transplant
an anencephalic infant already at the hospital, baby d, has not shown the required signs of brain death after six days on a respirator, lessening the chance that major organs can be taken from him, spokeswoman joyce mcclintock said
loma linda has developed the nation's first medical guidelines for preserving anencephalics' hearts and other vital organs for transplant to critically ill infants
under the guidelines, infants are placed on life-support systems for seven days. if doctors declare an infant brain-dead within that time, organ procurement agencies are alerted and a search for a suitable recipient begins
if the infant is not declared brain dead within seven days, it is taken off the respirator and allowed to die naturally. such a death causes the organs to deteriorate, rendering the heart and liver unsuitable for transplant
however, heart valves and corneas are usable and have been taken from other babies who died after being removed from respirators
the hospital's format was devised to address ethical questions surrounding the use of doomed anencephalics used as organ donors. ^by terence hunt</note>
president reagan said wednesday he will not revise or abandon an american plan for mideast peace talks even though israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir complained that it was ``not conducive to peace.''
ending two hours of talks with shamir in apparent deadlock, reagan warned that opponents of the u.s. proposal face certain consequences
they'll need to answer to themselves and their people as to why they've turned down a realistic and sensible plan to achieve negotiations,'' the president said, standing alongside an unsmiling shamir during a white house departure ceremony
reagan said shamir did not specifically say ``no'' to an international peace conference demanded by jordan's king hussein with u.s. support
however, shamir made clear that he rejected the idea. ``i have strong reservations concerning the proposed international conference, which in my view is not conducive to peace,'' he told reporters
shamir last october accepted a proposal by secretary of state george p. shultz to hold direct talks with jordan under u.s. and soviet auspices. ``i shall be ready to consider a similar proposal,'' he told reagan
however, hussein has rejected the idea, holding out for a full-scale international conference, and a senior u.s. official said: ``standing by itself, there would not be much point in presenting that again.''
the official, briefing reporters on condition of anonymity, said reagan and shamir dealt almost exclusively with differences over the international conference
he said they did not review israel's concerns about the u.s. proposal that it cede at least part of the west bank and gaza strip it has held since the 1967 six-day war in exchange for recognition by arab nations
shamir met for 20 minutes with a group of black congressmen who raised their concerns about israel's handling of the violence in the west bank and gaza strip and israel's ties with south africa
rep. mervyn dymally, d-calif., who heads the congressional black caucus, said he was ``dissatisfied'' with the short time alloted to the meeting, saying it precluded serious discussion
shamir will wrap up four days of talks thursday with another meeting with shultz. ``we are where we expected to be,'' the u.s. official said, since shamir did not come to washington with a decision by the israeli cabinet on the u.s. plan
shultz had hoped to convene the peace conference next month and to open negotiations may 1. he asked for a prompt reply from israel and the arabs. ``we are not setting our watches on any of them,'' the senior official said
but he stressed the need to make arrangements rapidly
at the departure ceremony in the east room, reagan promised to work to strengthen u.s.-israeli ties during his final months in office
without specifically mentioning the three months of palestinian rioting and the israeli crackdown in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, he said the talks focused on the search for peace in the middle east
we've seen a new sense of urgency on the part of many in the region, and a wide recognition of the reality that the status quo is unacceptable,'' the president said
he said ``the present situation is a challenge and an opportunity to move decisively to break the deadlock that has lasted far too long. i hope we will not lose this opportunity.''
reagan said the u.s. plan ``offers a realistic and achievable way to change the relationship between israel and the arabs. ... so let's be clear about several things: the united states will not slice this initiative apart and will not abandon it.''
explaining reagan's stand later, the senior u.s. official said, ``you start pulling it apart, it's not going to be workable.''
while rejecting the ntion of an international conference, shamir said, ``israel firmly believes that those who are prepared to live with each other in peace must learn to negotiate directly with each other.''
the u.s. official tried to put a positive face on the talks. he said ``there was essentially no slamming of the door'' by israel and that the tone of the talks was excellent
despite the apparent impasse, the president sought to reassure the hesitant israeli leader that the united states would not allow terms to be dictated at a peace conference and shared shamir's distrust of the palestine liberation organization
the official paraphrased reagan as saying that peace cannot be made under violence and terrorism
he said the plo is revealing its real intent: no to peace and yes to violence. we must find ways to give moderate palestinians and other arabs a stake in the process.''
vice president george bush, hosting a dinner for shamir wednesday night at the state department, assured him ``no wedge will be driven between the united states and israel.''
toasting shamir, the vice president said: ``we are like brothers; our two countries, friends and allies forever.''
shamir, in reply, said israel was proud of its record as the most consistent supporter of the united states in the united nations and of sharing military technology with washington. he said the u.s.-israeli relationship ``is stronger than ever.''
about 1,000 students and workers marched five miles through this capital wednesday to denounce approaching legislative elections and demand more money for the national university of el salvador
the march ended at the treasury ministry, where young men wielding nail-encrusted clubs, their faces covered by bandannas or ski masks, began jeering at troopers
the troopers fired tear gas, but the demonstrators set fire to a half-dozen vehicles before they dispersed
student groups at the university called the march to demand an increase in the school's budget. it was joined by labor unions and other organizations that sympathize with leftist guerrillas battling the u.s.-backed government
the demonstration became more of a condemnation of sunday's legislative and municipal elections than a demand for increased spending on education
marchers carried posters ridiculing candidates of the governing christian democrats and of the main opposition party, arena, a rightist group
voters will choose mayors and councils in 262 municipalities and fill 60 seats in the legislative assembly
leftist parties are boycotting the vote. the guerrillas and leftist union members say the elections are ``a farce,'' that no free and fair balloting can be held in the middle of a civil war
guerrillas from five leftist groups have been fighting since 1980 to overthrow the government. the war has killed about 65,000 people, displaced 500,000 and ravaged the economy. patients</head>
dying patients in florida nursing homes will not be forced to accept tube-feedings after july 1 under a rule change instituted by the state wednesday
it gives those choices back to those persons who are dying, and not the state saying we're going to force you to accept a tube-feeding,'' said connie cheren, director of the department of health and rehabilitative services' licensing office
currently the department permits life-support sytems to be turned off but does not allow feeding tubes to be withdrawn
that rule ``has basically been intrepreted that if the facililty does not do the forced feeding, it must discharge the resident,'' said ms. cheren
the new rule ``does not relieve a facility's responsibility to do all the palliative things like giving ice chips, holding hands and rubbing the back, easing somebody through the dying stages,'' said ms. cheren
it's better because sometimes forced feeding is more harmful to the person than helpful,'' she said. ``sometimes taking the food during the dying stages is more painful for the person because the body is shutting down at this time.''
church leaders in this country and abroad wednesday urged clemency for the sharpville six, scheduled for execution friday in south africa
church officials also expressed appreciation to president reagan for asking south africa to halt the execution on ``compassionate and humanitarian grounds.''
the six blacks, a woman and five men, all in their 20s or 30s, were convicted in the 1984 death of jacob dlamani, black council member of sharpville township, in a demonstration of about 2,000 people
the human rights office of the u.s. national council of churches, which includes most major protestant and eastern orthodox bodies, urged that the six be spared
their trial did not fulfill the norms of jurisprudence and their executions will not serve the cause of justice in south africa,'' the council said. ``in god's name, grant clemency to the sharpville six.''
in a telegram to the south african government, the executive council of the 1.7-million member united church of christ said:
since the judge in the case has admitted that none of the defendants in the case has contributed causally to the alleged crime, there is no basis for the proposed brutal punishment
we can only conclude that the planned executions are meant to serve a political purpose in continuing efforts of your government to deprive black south africans of their political and human rights.''
from geneva, switzerland, the rev. emilio castro, general secretary of the world council of churches, sent messages to ecumenical councils in a score of countries, urging them to ask their governments to intervene with south africa
castro said the impending execution for an ``alleged role in murder, which has not been proved in the case of any of the six accused, according to the appeals court judge, is disturbing to human conscience the world over.''
castro also urged continuing ``prayers of intercession for victims and families of the apartheid system. ... may god restore justice and peace to south africans.'' inadvertently.</note>
about 3,200 american infantry and airborne troops are flying to honduras today in the most dramatic show of u.s. force in the six-year nicaraguan war, causing the senate's top democrat to accuse president reagan of ``overreaction.''
the white house described the movement as ``an emergency deployment readiness exercise'' triggered by what it called the invasion of honduras by 1,500 to 2,000 nicaraguan forces pursuing contra rebels
the exercise involves two battalions of the 82nd airborne division from fort bragg, n.c., and two battalions from the 7th infantry division at fort ord, calif
members of congress are skeptical about whether the reported nicaraguan military incursion into neighboring honduras is as large or as threatening as the reagan administration claims
senate majority leader robert byrd called president reagan's decision to send 3,200 u.s. troops to honduras an ``overreaction,'' and a number of other legislators said they were still waiting for hard evidence from the white house to back up its claims
house majority whip tony coelho, d-calif, said: ``i think you have to ask the question of whether 1,200 nicaraguans going across the honduran border is a threat to u.s. national security,'' as secretary of state george p. shultz had argued in an earlier briefing for congressional leaders
military officials said honduran soldiers surrounded about 2,000 nicaraguan troops who crossed three miles into the country in pursuit of contra rebels, but had not engaged them in combat
the military intelligence sources told the associated press that the sandinista soldiers had been in the border province of olancho for 24 hours when honduran troops encircled them wednesday
the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the entire honduran military was on alert
president daniel ortega said sandinista troops had forced 2,000 contras into honduran territory, and he warned the nation that u.s. forces may invade nicaragua to save the rebels
the united states, disrespectful of international law and disrespectful of the principles of the american constitution, is threatening today (wednesday) to directly employ its military forces to save the mercenaries,'' ortega said, referring to the u.s.-supported contra rebels
ortega was reacting to an initial report by the white house that the united states was considering ``everything ... short of invasion'' after president jose azcona hoyo of honduras accused nicaragua of sending troops across the border into his country and asked president reagan for help
independent counsel lawrence e. walsh is leaving the door open for further criminal charges in the iran-contra affair following the indictment of lt. col. oliver north and three others on charges of ``deceitfully exploiting'' u.s. weapons sales to iran
the 23-count indictment charging that north, former national security adviser john poindexter and two weapons dealers engaged in a criminal conspiracy ``is simply an interim report'' of the grand jury's 14-month investigation, walsh told reporters
the grand jury is not finished,'' walsh said wednesday after the panel returned the 101-page indictment against north, poindexter and arms dealers albert hakim and retired air force maj. gen. richard v. secord
u.s. veterans are cheating the government out of tens of millions of dollars each year by lying about their incomes and collecting excessive benefits as a result, a congressional report says
the report by the general accounting office, the investigative wing of congress, compared veterans administration income forms filled out by pensioners with internal revenue service data
sen. frank murkowski, r-alaska, released the report wednesday and said congress should move to halt the abuses by giving the va access to same tax information so it can verify what veterans tell it about income from jobs and investments. murkowski is the senior republican on the veterans affairs committee
soldiers loyal to gen. manuel antonio noriega patrolled the streets of panama city today, one day after a failed coup attempt by rebel officers sparked rioting by thousands of panamanians
the rampage by citizens fed up with military rule and the nation's financial crisis was the largest disturbance since civilian opponents first began staging demonstrations calling for noriega's ouster last summer
wednesday's protests erupted spontaneously throughout the capital and in the country's second largest city, colon, 50 miles to the north
senators stood in respect as gov. evan mecham arrived for the first time at his impeachment trial to testify that he didn't cover up a death threat and did not sell appointments for campaign contributions
mecham told the arizona senate on wednesday that his trust in some aides was ``a trust misplaced'' and that he also had ``big trouble'' in relations with state attorney general bob corbin, a fellow republican
the 63-year-old first-term governor, who said his 1986 campaign theme was to ``rid the state of corruption,'' was expected to resume testimony today
sirens wailed and hundreds of boisterous fans jammed the street to cheer susan butcher as she coasted to an unprecedented third straight victory in the 1,150-mile iditarod trail sled dog race
bitterly cold winds raked nome as the flushed and perspiring 33-year-old alaskan cruised beneath the log-arch finish at 8:42 p.m. wednesday
it means a lot to me to win three years in a row,'' said a smiling butcher, the only musher to win three consecutive iditarods, as she hugged her frosty-faced lead dogs, granite and tolstoy
a newly divorced carol leifer sits in her apartment amid moving boxes, sifting through the remains of her marriage
it's one thing to be divorced, she muses, but what about people who have their marriages annulled? ``that means the marriage never existed. talk about denial.''
she shows her wedding pictures. ``what do you tell people when they see this? `oh, that was just some play i was in?'''
leifer, a standup comedian best-known for her frequent appearances on ``late night with david letterman,'' gets to act out and expand on elements of her standup act in her first cinemax comedy experiment, ``carol doesn't leifer anymore,'' an ode to the trauma of divorce, co-written by leifer and ``late night'' writer fred graver
the half-hour show, airing tonight as well as on march 20, 23, 28 and april 5, follows leifer as she packs up to begin anew
i would say the motivation was definitely from real life,'' said leifer, who is divorced in real life, ``because the gist of the show is, oh, you get divorced and single life is going to be great. you think you're going to be `that girl!' you quickly find out you're really going to be more like miss hathaway from `the beverly hillbillies.'''
as the piece opens, leifer hits the road with enthusiasm, but soon every song on the radio is about lost love and loneliness. (that's will lee, the guitarist in the ``late night'' band, singing ``i'm mr. lonely.'') then she stops at a gas station only to find her moving men standing behind the van reading her diary
once ensconced in her new place, she goes grocery shopping, cleaning out the frozen dinner section and stocking up on cans of instant whipped cream, which she squirts directly into her mouth in times of stress _ like after strangling her aerobics teacher or selecting just the right kind of condoms
when she does date, she decides she can't be too careful and leads a prospective beau on a detailed recounting of his entire sex life, complete with charts and pointer
friends throw her a surprise party, and she meets a possible mr. right. but he turns out to have a herd of kiddies and thinks gourmet dining is to be found at the international house of pancakes. he orders the veal, prompting her to think, ``if he goes for the syrup, i'm gone.''
in real life, leifer assures, ``i didn't really have that nightmare of a date. i never really had a date who took me to get his car inspected. i mean, it's never gotten that bad _ almost.''
leifer aspires to have a comedy series of her own, perhaps something along the lines of ``it's garry shandling's show.'' for now, she still works the standup circuit, recently going as far afield as the university of alaska _ ``the woman who picked me up at the airport said, `i don't know why we can't get entertainers here.' i thought, `oh, i don't know, maybe it's the 10-hour plane ride?'''
the former ``saturday night live'' writer grew up on long island, and it is middle-class suburbia more than feminism that informs her comedy
i don't really think of myself as `a woman doing comedy,''' leifer said. ``that's not foremost on my mind. there a lot of jokes in my act that a man could do. but there are also a lot of jokes about my experience, which happens to be as a woman
i know when i go to watch comedy, i've never liked the kind of women comedians who go out, and they kind of foster that separation in the audience. they go out and it's a lot of, `am i right, ladies, am i right?' _ it's like, please, someone shoot me if i ever say that. i just cringe
there are also a lot more women doing comedy,'' she said. ``but i think it's just a reflection of the times. i mean, there are also a lot more women in prison, too.''
elsewhere in television:
country music on pbs _ as part of its programming for pledge month, the public broadcasting service is serving up a star-packed special on saturday, ``country music crossroads,'' featuring such up-and-coming c&amp;w crossover artists as randy travis, reba mcentire, lyle lovett and nanci griffith. the show is from the producers of ``austin city limits.'' ..
country music on nbc _ if the pbs special isn't enough, c&amp;w fans can tune in monday night for the ``academy of country music awards'' on nbc, with co-hosts reba mcentire and hank williams jr. performers will include alabama, merle haggard, the judds, tanya tucker and dwight yoakam
