above a pawn shop in downtown toronto, patti labelle rips into a group of lackadaisical brooklyn high school students
in her first major dramatic role, the pop star is playing an inspirational teacher in a movie musical based on sing, the annual song-and-dance competition in brooklyn's schools
the legendary program at such schools as erasmus hall gave rise to such talents as barbra streisand and neil diamond. but with the urban decay of the past decade, only a dozen schools now take part
the struggle to preserve that old brooklyn spirit has inspired the film, ``sing,'' with a plot centered on education board plans to close a beloved high school where generations of immigrants got their start
with songs from the writer of ``footloose'' and ``fame'' and a tempestuous love story between a street-smart italian kid and a jewish princess, the tri-star pictures production now shooting in toronto is scheduled for release in february 1989
i'm hooked on it. i'm one of those people who think about community and pulling together and family,'' said labelle, the rhythm and blues artist who first hit the pop charts in the 1960s with the blue bells and later in the '70s with the trio labelle. she has appeared in two previous films, ``a soldier's story'' and the tv movie ``unnatural causes.''
in ``sing,'' she plays mrs. devere, an adviser who shakes her junior class students out of apathy
she's very uplifting to the kids,'' labelle said between takes of her chart-targeted big number, ``total concentration,'' in which she demonstrates how to put over a song
producer craig zadan and screenwriter-lyricist dean pitchford, who won an academy award for ``fame,'' said they created the part with labelle in mind and waited until she found time to do it
there's a real honesty there, nothing phony about her. in her own way she's lived through what this teacher has gone through,'' said pitchford
labelle has charmed the crew by introducing them to her own home cooking _ fried chicken and potato salad. but she's not sure about life as an actress
i'm not a cher. i don't know if i'd have enough patience to do another movie,'' she said, complaining about the number of retakes. ``it hurts enough some times that you want to cry. i like to perform live.''
however, director richard baskin, who co-produced streisand's landmark ``broadway album'' and is making his first feature film, said labelle looked great in the first rushes
co-stars include lorraine bracco who played tom berenger's wife in ``someone to watch over me,'' louise lasser of ``mary hartman, mary hartman'' fame and george dicenzo who was rob lowe's boss in ``about last night.'' the young lovers are peter dobson and jessica steen
for co-producer neil meron, a brooklyn and sing alumnus, the project is a labor of love
in the high school i went to, sing no longer exists,'' meron lamented. ``brooklyn is one of the oldest communities in america, and the way those communities found to express themselves was through music and dance.''
to research the film, the production team talked with veteran teachers in brooklyn and attended a sing performance at midwood high school where faculty member bella tillis launched the program in 1947
sing competitions involved reviews or skits created and staged by a committee from each class. the musical skits were judged on sing night when freshmen, sophomores, juniors and seniors got to strut their stuff. in the 1950s and '60s, when sing was at its peak, the competitions were fierce
lyricist pitchford also found inspiration in england, where he's been working with the royal shakespeare co. on the broadway-bound musical, ``carrie.''
after `fame' the last thing i wanted to do was another high school film set in new york about kids who sing and dance,'' he said
but england has tradition and history we can only approximate in america. the closest thing to that kind of longevity is in east coast settlements like brooklyn. sing became a metaphor for that tradition
i developed an enormous affection for sing and the neighborhoods of brooklyn and a real despair for the passing of this tradition.''
paul dooley wanted to act in silent movies
he missed that by a few years, but he's done ok in the talkies and is a member of director robert altman's repertory company. he's also done fine right in television, most recently starring as super private eye william j. burns in the nbc miniseries ``the murder of mary phagan.''
now he is starring in a new series on cbs, ``coming of age.'' he plays an airline pilot who is forced, kicking and screaming into retirement in arizona
the half-hour comedy also stars phyllis newman as his wife and alan young and glynis johns as an incredibly happy couple in the retirement village
it's funny. here i am playing a guy who's winding down. in real life i've got a rejuvenation, a new family and a new job,'' said dooley
the whole reason i wanted to do movies was to do silent pictures,'' he said. ``of course, the silents were long gone. but when i did `the ed sullivan show,' my dressing room was across from buster keaton's. a few months later we did a commercial together. we played keystone kops. he was so sweet. he never seemed to gain any sophistication
the thing i loved about laurel and hardy was that they were so sweet to each other. one reason i didn't want to do a series was that in so many i saw people insulted each other. in this my character is retired, which is why he's unhappy. he complains about the heat of arizona and the boredom of retirement. i find the character enjoyable. he has his frustrations, but he doesn't insult people. most of my conflict is with alan young. why is he so happy?''
dooley, 60, has three college-age children from his first marriage. he remarried and has a 2{-year-old daughter, savannah
dooley says he often plays younger because his hair hasn't thinned or turned gray. ``it gives me a longer career,'' he said
he grew up in west virginia with the hope of becoming a cartoonist. ``i drew a lot,'' he said, ``and i kept that ambition until about halfway through college. i was at the university of west virginia at morgantown. i was doing plays and finally switched my major to drama. i had $50 when i graduated and drove an old dodge to new york. i had to keep it in a friend's driveway in brooklyn because i couldn't afford to run it
don knotts and i had been in college together and he got me my first job in new york. he mentioned my name and i got a job on a children's tv show, `bobby benson and the bar-b ranch.' i played don's nephew for about six months.''
dooley, who had been a teen-age juggler and magician, next landed the role of coocoo the clown on a saturday morning show. ``i'd pull a string and a bird came out of my hat,'' he said. ``i brought my whole bag of tricks with me and i'd perform at birthday parties. it paid the rent.''
he became a member of second city's new york improvisational group and at about the same time began to do television guest star work and small parts in movies. he was in an off-broadway play written by jules feiffer when director robert altman saw him
he was looking for the father of the bride in `a wedding,''' he said. dennis christopher played his son in that movie and later in a non-altman film, ``breaking away.''
dooley didn't do the tv series ``breaking away'' because by that time he was off to malta to play wimpy in altman's ``popeye.'' he wore a fat suit, a fake moustache and had to cut off most of his hair
for the last 10 years he's done mostly movies, such as ``sixteen candles,'' ``health,'' ``kiss me goodbye,'' ``a perfect couple,'' ``endangered species'' and ``big trouble.'' he was also a regular on ``the dom deluise show.''
comedian paul rodriguez says he has never been happy with television, either as a performer or a viewer, but is willing to give it another shot
rodriguez and eddie velez co-star in the new cbs comedy ``trial and error'' as two young hispanic men who share an apartment but little else in life. they are as mismatched as oscar and felix in ``the odd couple'' or balki and larry in ``perfect strangers.''
the only unique thing about this is that i'm in it,'' said rodriguez, a standup comic. ``it's contrived, but it's an attempt to get more latinos into television. who cares? it's a job. maybe it will open some doors to other latino actors. i'm happy with everybody for going out ot the way to make the show more accessible to latinos. i'm dubbing it in spanish for simulcast over radio stations in 10 cities.''
rodriguez plays tony rivera, a funky entrepreneur who makes his living selling t-shirts to tourists. velez is john hernandez, a clean-cut, ambitious young attorney
john is typical of a lot of latinos whose ambition is to cross over and assimilate,'' rodriguez said. ``he thinks if you get a college education, work 9-to-5, people are going to forget your background and ask you to join the california club
my character's philosophy is that if you have enough money you can do anything you want. his whole thing is to get enough money to tell the world where to get off. of course, neither of us are right.''
he describes john as the kind of young man all latinos want their sons to grow up to be. ``and my character is the kind most of them actually grow up to be,'' he said
his first series was the short-lived ``a.k.a. pablo'' on abc in 1984
i was not anxious to get back into television,'' he said. ``my experience with `a.k.a. pablo' was not happy. i was at the comedy store when norman lear came into my life. the show was over-hyped. when it failed i was blamed by latinos for its image
this time i said i wanted to be more involved. i wanted to do some writing. i suggested we call the show `east l.a. law.'''
trial and error'' originated as an idea by tommy chong (of the comedy team cheech and chong) and howard brown about an up-and-coming young latino attorney who still lived at home. it was called ``the family martinez.''
cbs liked the idea of the lawyer, but wanted the show recast and changed to a buddy show. it then became ``amigos.''
when they called me i said i wouldn't be in a show called `amigos,''' said rodriguez. ``i felt i had already over-stereotyped myself.''
rodriguez was born in mexico and was raised in various parts of this country as the son of migrant farm workers
as a kid i had a love-hate relationship with television,'' he said. ``television showed me the things i would never have, cars i would never drive, places i would never see. my favorite show was `route 66.' two single men driving a corvette down the highway, wind blowing in their hair and always a blonde around the bend. then i'd look around my neighborhood. i didn't see any corvettes or blondes
that worries me because now that i'm in tv i'll be a part of the problem as some latino boy sees me with nice clothes and the right people.''
besides tv and his concert appearances, rodriguez has been in five movies, ``d.c. cab,'' ``quicksilver,'' ``born in east l.a.,'' ``miracles'' and ``whoopee boys.''
my favorite is `quicksilver,' because it gave me a chance to do some dramatic acting,'' he said
rodriguez said he is constantly asked if the show will advance the cause of latinos
come on,'' he said, ``this is just another sitcom. and i'm not that altruistic. we're happy to be working. if a byproduct is that we help other latinos, i'm all for it. but that's not my goal. my goal is to become financially secure so that my kids don't have to harvest someone else's vegetables. not that that's not an honorable job, but let somebody else do it. i'm not the latino moses. i'm just a standup comic. my job is to make people laugh.'' empire</head>
exiled television evangelist jim bakker is dreaming of attracting a new flock to a christian retreat in the california desert, even as ptl, the ministry he left behind one year ago saturday, struggles to survive
ptl, under the control of a u.s. bankruptcy court in columbia, continues to spend thousands of dollars a day more than it takes in
the ministry's television network is in the middle of a ``march to victory'' telethon with a goal of raising $4.2 million by april 1 to meet expenses, and ptl is considering the sale of hundreds of undeveloped acres at the heritage usa theme park to pay creditors
the woman bakker admitted having sex with and paying money to keep silent, jessica hahn, is living in the playboy mansion in los angeles. she is writing more of her story for playboy magazine, spokesman bill farley said
the man bakker originally accused of using blackmail to cause his march 19 downfall at ptl, the rev. jimmy swaggart, is dealing with his own admitted sexual transgression that knocked him from the pulpit
and the evangelist bakker accused of stealing ptl, the rev. jerry falwell, is back preaching at his old time gospel hour in virginia
falwell, who led ptl for six months, said it's been a dismal year. ``it was obviously the toughest year evangelicals have ever faced,'' he said. ``credibility was gravely injured by the ptl scandal.''
the national religious broadcasters association met in washington last month to set stricter standards of moral and financial accountability
it is going to take me years to say all that i have learned through this,'' bakker told the charlotte observer recently. ``and i'm going to be a different minister. i'm going to be less judgmental.''
bakker calls his proposed new promised land heritage springs and says it would be a 1,600-acre complex that would be similar to heritage usa outside fort mill, s.c. he says it would be located in the california desert, but no specific plans have been made
the boyish-looking minister, newly ordained by a little-known oklahoma church, was used to preaching in a high-tech studio, his sermons carried via satellite
the scene was very different last week when bakker delivered his first homily since heading west
for 30 minutes, he preached to elderly retirees at a trailer park beside the salton sea in a desolate stretch of desert south of palm springs, where he and his wife, tammy, live
tammy, who wept after introducing her husband to the congregation in a tiny wooden chapel that doubles as a bingo hall, said it has been a hard year for them
some people will ask, `what have you learned in this last year that you could share? the thing that i have learned the most is that when everything is gone and what you worked 25 years to build has crumbled to your feet, god doesn't change,'' mrs. bakker said
and what of the evangelical empire bakker began building in 1978?
the devout still travel to fort mill to vacation at the 500-acre heritage usa, with its hotel, water park and stables. the cable television network still uses bakker's upbeat formula of entertainment mixed with preaching, prayer lines and pledges
but there are new faces and a new message: integrity and modesty
david clark, a former christian broadcasting network executive who was appointed ptl trustee by bankruptcy judge rufus reynolds, continually assures viewers the new guard isn't out for greed and glory
the people here are living modestly and conservatively,'' he said on the show recently. ``there are no seven-figure salaries here and there are no celebrities. we're willing to be accountable to you.''
an internal revenue service report filed in bankruptcy court said the bakkers and their top aides received $14.6 million in excessive compensation from 1984 to 1987
a federal grand jury in charlotte, n.c., is investigating bakker for possible tax, wire and mail fraud
last week, bakker fired his own salvo. he had a lawsuit filed in york county against roy grutman, a new york attorney who used to represent the ministry. bakker is charging that grutman tricked him into resigning and turning the ministry over to falwell
the bakkers, who are seeking more than $10,000 in damages, claim they did not know grutman also represented falwell at the time he advised the bakkers to step down
the suit says grutman told the bakkers that swaggart was heading a conspiracy to take over ptl
grutman said the allegations were ``utterly meritless.''
i think this is a publicity stunt by bakker and his lawyers. i was never retained by mr. bakker. i was not his lawyer,'' grutman said
in the year since jim bakker disclosed his sexual encounter with jessica hahn, many former friends have turned against her. she's angry and hurt, and she's planning to retaliate _ in print
i'm not exactly the most loved person. there are a lot of angry people. my mother never gave me a middle name and i finally figured out why, because it's `controversy,''' said the 28-year-old former church secretary
much has happened to her in the year since her tryst with bakker became public, forcing him to resign the ptl ministry
she was paid $1 million by playboy to tell her story. she claimed bakker had forcibly taken away her virginity, though he said she appeared to be sexually experienced and was a willing participant
her appearance in the pages of america's leading men's magazine was just the start of her relationship with the playboy empire. she moved into founder hugh hefner's los angeles mansion; she denied she had become his lover
she recuperated at the mansion after having her breasts lifted and her teeth and nose fixed. she bought a red mercedes 560 sl convertible
and she was forced to contend with a series of allegations that she was not the innocent bible belle that she claimed
one married man said he had slept with her before 1980 while two others said they had had affairs with her. she said all three lied
then, a long island woman claimed in a penthouse story that miss hahn had worked as a call girl for her. finally, the son of barbara bencivenga pietropaolo, a neighbor, claimed he had been seduced by miss hahn when he was 14
people have made a career out of my name. it's unbelievable,'' miss hahn said. ``it's mean what people are doing. it's really bad. the madam story, c'mon. i never left my house. i'm the one girl who didn't even go out nightclubbing.''
but ms. pietropaolo, who a year ago helped shield miss hahn from reporters, brought her messages and drove her on errands, is angry
she makes herself like a madonna. but i still say she's like the anti-christ,'' she said
miss hahn has ``forgotten all her friends,'' ms. pietropaolo said. ``there were times she seemed so sweet and so nice.''
ms. pietropaolo said her 12-year-old daughter, tiffany, still misses miss hahn. ``tiffany was so close to her that she said, `if i ever make it big you'll be dripping in furs and diamonds.' she didn't even say goodbye.''
jessica hahn is working on her own kind of farewell _ another magazine story she says will explain why so many people who used to be her friends have attacked her. she spends her days writing at the los angeles mansion, where she has her own room and can stay indefinitely
she occasionally goes shopping, jogs and takes trips to new york, where photographers have caught her at publicity parties. recently, she said, she bumped into entertainer liza minnelli at a los angeles restaurant. she was pleased to learn that miss minnelli did not believe the attacks on jessica hahn
still, miss hahn said she thinks ``this other story needs to be told.''
i have to defend myself,'' she said. ``i'm going to have the last word, believe me.''
u.s. industrial production edged up 0.2 percent in february as reductions in output at auto factories and coal mines offset gains in other areas, the government reported
the federal reserve said wednesday that the february advance, which followed a 0.3 percent january gain, was the poorest showing since output declined by 0.2 percent in september
but private economists said the gains, even at a much slower pace, represented good news for the economy
the housing industry, after staggering for two months following the october stock market crash, enjoyed a sharp 8.9 percent increase in construction activity in february, the biggest gain in more than a year, the government said
the commerce department said the increase boosted construction to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.49 million units last month following declines of 15.8 percent in december and 1.9 percent in january
those setbacks raised concerns because housing is often the first industry to weaken at the onset of a new recession
directors of american standard inc. met to review several alternative proposals to a hostile, $2.1 billion buyout bid from black &amp; decker corp., including an offer topping black &amp; decker's proposal
earlier wednesday, a judge in delaware granted black &amp; decker's request to temporarily prohibit american standard from altering its retirement and severance pay plan as a defense against the takeover bid
black &amp; decker had argued the changes unfairly would add to the cost of acquiring american standard
embattled koppers co. said it was studying a cash payout to shareholders, asset sale or employee stock ownership to battle a takeover attempt by british investor brian beazer and a new york investment bank
but before koppers details the options under study, the company is expected to launch a publicity campaign criticizing investment banker shearson lehman hutton inc
also on wednesday, pittsburgh filed suit in federal court alleging that shearson, as underwriter of city bonds, violated its duty not to do anything to hurt the pittsburgh economy
despite the threat of a presidential veto, the house labor committee approved and sent to the floor legislation to raise the current federal minimum wage of $3.35 an hour to $5.05 over the next four years
the democratic-controlled house labor and education committee approved the measure wednesday after defeating several republican proposals, one of which would have established a ``new hire'' wage of $3.35 an hour
congressional action on the measure is expected to be completed by the end of april
job prospects for both production and service workers are the brightest they have been in three years but are declining slightly for technical, professional and office workers, according to a private survey
twenty-one percent of the 398 corporations polled in the survey published wednesday said they anticipate expanding their production and service work forces from april through june
but only 19 percent of the companies surveyed by the bureau of national affairs said they plan to increase their technical and professional staffs, down from 21 percent for the first quarter of this year
a federal judge upheld ohio's anti-takeover law, blocking an italian tire maker's attempt to strike it down as part of its takeover bid for firestone tire &amp; rubber co
u.s. district judge alice m. batchelder ruled wednesday that the ohio control share acquisition act does not violate federal law by discriminating against interstate commerce, or causing inconsistent state regulation
pirelli societe generale sa of italy made a tender offer of $58 a share last week for firestone
back interest payments on brazilian loans could add $250 million to citicorp's 1988 earnings, chairman and chief executive officer john s. reed said
i believe brazil is likely to reach an agreement with the banks, but it is difficult to be assured of it,'' reed said wednesday
citicorp, the nation's largest bank holding company with assets of $203.6 billion, is the leader of negotiations between banks and the brazilian government aimed at restructuring that country's debt
stung by bankruptcies among its most prosperous denizens, a record clip of bank failures and a massive criminal investigation of its savings and loan industry, texas' fabled financial brilliance has dimmed further now that the state's largest bank holding company is seeking a federal rescue
analysts said wednesday that the worst isn't over for texas' hobbled financial industry
dallas-based first republicbank corp., with $33.2 billion in deposits and 134 banking facilities across the state, acknowledged tuesday that its deteriorating loan portfolio and difficulty in raising deposits forced it to seek federal help
a west virginia physician filed consumer fraud complaints in all 50 states charging four major publishers with selling achievement tests that give a misleadingly rosy picture of student progress
the complaints were filed wednesday by john jacob cannell
cannell gained prominence last november as a test gadfly with a 26-page report accusing publishers of the iowa test, the metropolitan achievement test and similar tests of giving ``children, parents, school systems, legislatures, and the press misleading reports on achievement levels.''
residents of mid-sized cities in the west no longer will get detailed figures on monthly price changes in their communities
in new york and los angeles, monthly household surveys of employment and unemployment are being cut back sharply. tracking of trends among blacks, hispanics, teen-agers and women in the two cities will be less current
the government is changing the numbers it collects and crunches to measure whether times are good or bad
the stock market rose in a late rally wednesday. the dow jones average of 30 industrials closed 16.91 points higher at 2,064.32
the dollar rose slightly against most major currencies. gold prices edged lower in domestic trading after climbing overseas
bond prices tumbled on government reports indicating growth in the economy
most grain and soybean futures prices turned weaker. crude oil prices closed higher in a volatile session following reports of unrest in central america
reports of unrest in panama and nicaragua set off sharp fluctuations in crude oil prices, but near-term futures contracts managed a moderate gain by the close of trading
on the new york mercantile exchange, contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude, rose 32 cents to settle at $16.00 per barrel on wednesday
among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale gasoline for april delivery rose 0.86 cent to 45.24 cents per gallon and the april contract for wholesale heating oil gained 0.61 cent to close at 44.08 cents per gallon
the april price of crude jumped as high as $16.18 a barrel and sank as low as $15.75 during the session amid reports of an attempted coup in panama and of a nicaraguan attack on contra rebels in honduras
traders were concerned about a disruption in oil supplies because of the vulnerability of an oil pipeline that runs through panama from the atlantic to the pacific, said madison galbraith, senior energy specialist with merrill lynch energy futures
as the reports crossed news wires, prices spurted upward, galbraith said. prices later fell back as calm and sellers returned to the trading floor
galbraith attributed some of wednesday's price fluctuations to technical factors, including covering of short sales
in a short sale, a trader borrows a contract and sells it, hoping to replace it later with another contract bought at a lower price. a price rise can cause a flurry of buying as traders attempt to cover their positions. atlanta dateline, are asked to use the following story.</note>
the associated press erroneously reported tuesday that coca-cola co. is buying h.p. hood inc., a boston-based citrus and dairy company. the agreement is only for coca-cola to buy hood's citrus food operations in florida
shareholders are waiting for koppers co. to say how much they could get under the company recapitalization plan being considered as a defense against an unsolicited $45 per share takeover bid from a british investor and the investment firm shearson lehman hutton inc
that's what i'm waiting for,'' robert kanters of legg mason wood walker inc. of pittsburgh said wednesday. ``we really don't know how much better the deal is until we get the particulars.''
koppers on wednesday rejected as inadequate the $1.3 billion tender offer from bns inc., a group led by shearson and british investor brian beazer, and said it was studying a recapitalization as an alternative
the disclosures came as shearson faced increasing state and local government pressure over its unusual role in the takeover bid
koppers stock dipped 87{ cents to $53.62{ a share wednesday in heavy new york stock exchange trading
koppers said its recapitalization _ which analysts have speculated could pay cash and securities worth $55 to $60 a share _ would include a substantial cash dividend to holders of koppers' nearly 28 million common shares, plus stock in the recapitalized company
recapitalization _ essentially making a major adjustment in a company's relative levels of debt and equity _ has been used often in recent years as a takeover defense. a recapitalizing company generally must make huge borrowings to finance the special dividend to shareholders, making a takeover much more expensive
charles r. pullin, koppers' chairman, said the company also would explore the public sale of all or a part of its construction materials business _ one of its two business lines _ to help boost the special dividend. it also would consider the sale of its common stock to a new employee stock ownership plan
a koppers spokesman said the board of directors set no timetable for settling details of any recapitalization plan
beazer quickly criticized koppers' announcement, and claimed that if koppers explored a recapitalization the company was obligated to give confidential corporate information to bns
beazer said that based on recent court decisions in similar recapitalizations, kopper essentially would be bidding for itself. koppers therefore was obligated to give bns access to the same confidential corporate data koppers _ or any other bidder _ would get for formulating the plan
shearson, which holds a 46 percent share in bns, came under further fire from city and state lawmakers
shearson's equity participation is an aggressive variation of investment bankers' traditional role as adviser and financier in hostile takeovers
the city of pittsburgh filed a federal suit claiming that shearson _ an underwriter of city bonds _ by joining with beazer had violated its duty not to hurt the pittsburgh economy
under beazer's plan to sell koppers' chemical business, about 1,100 jobs could disappear in pittsburgh, city officials contend
separately, mayor richard caliguiri ordered department heads to exclude shearson from consideration as an underwriter of future financing, said spokesman david welty
in addition, pennsylvania treasurer g. davis greene jr. suspended his department's dealings with shearson. the state purchased $565 million in commercial notes and bonds from the firm in the past six months, according to greene
separately, pennsylvania's state employees retirement system approved a resolution expressing concern over the takeover attempt. the system holds 544,650 shares of american express, shearson's parent, and 17,900 shares of koppers
some analysts speculated koppers soon would join the negative publicity campaign against shearson
i would expect the first thing you'll see...will be some newspaper advertising that'll peel the hide off shearson,'' said donald a. pattison of cyrus j. lawrence inc. of new york
koppers alleged in a federal lawsuit filed march 11 that shearson violated disclosure requirements of securities laws and that it offered to sell koppers its services defending the company against hostile takeovers after laying plans with beazer to raid the company
a federal judge, pressing for quick payments of damage claims stemming from the dalkon shield birth control device, has approved the merger of a.h. robins co. and american home products corp
u.s. district judge robert r. merhige jr. signed an order wednesday to allow the merger between robins, which sold the dalkon shield in the early 1970s, and new york-based american home
attorneys for robins, its shareholders and the 195,000 women who have filed injury claims stemming from use of the device, endorsed the merger of the two drug makers, which includes creation of a $2.475 billion dalkon shield trust fund to compensate victims
before approving the deal merhige had to be satisfied that some claims would be paid before final approval of robins' bankruptcy reorganization plan. robins has been under chapter 11 protection from creditors since august 1985
the judge approved the jan. 19 merger agreement only after robins offered to provide $100 million to cover administrative start-up costs for the trust fund and to begin sending payments to some of the victims
merhige said he was concerned about a provision in the merger agreement that allowed american home to pull out of the deal if appeals of the final reorganization plan remained pending a year after the plan was confirmed by the court
the judge suggested american home put up $100 million to cover the start-up costs, and said he would not approve the merger agreement without it
later in the day, robins offered to provide the $100 million and the judge agreed to the merger deal. roscoe e. puckett jr., a robins spokesman, said the first payments will involve smaller amounts for women who claimed lesser use and injuries from the dalkon shield
any payments still are at least several months away. court approval of the merger is only one step in the reorganization of robins, a richmond-based pharmaceutical manufacturer
the company's final reorganization plan also requires approval by robins' stockholders and creditors, including the dalkon shield claimants
the merger with american home involves an exchange of $700 million of american home common stock and full payment to robins' trade creditors, in addition to the provision of the dalkon shield trust fund
merhige said he would conduct a hearing later to review a filing by the rorer group inc., which had sought to acquire robins, for a $25 million breakup fee stemming from a previous merger agreement between robins and fort washington, pa.-based rorer
after merhige set the $2.475 billion figure for dalkon shield claims late last year, robins had three corporate suitors. robins rejected the rorer deal and a similar proposal from france's sanofi sa in favor of american home, which offered a substantially quicker settlement of dalkon shield claims
texaco inc. says it will turn over information sought by several small shareholders who have objected to the company's bankruptcy reorganization plan
the company's largest shareholder, financier carl icahn, also has objected to provisions of the plan that would release officers of texaco, getty oil co. and various getty trusts from any liability in texaco's acquisition of getty oil
a texas jury decided in 1985 that texaco had wrongly interfered with pennzoil co.'s agreement to merge with getty and awarded pennzoil $10.53 billion in damages
texaco filed for protection from creditors under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code a year ago to avoid having to post a potentially ruinous bond to appeal the decision
as part of its plan for emerging from chapter 11, texaco would pay pennzoil $3 billion cash to settle their case
the documents sought by the small shareholders covered discussions on why the reorganization plan would release the texaco, getty and trust officials from liability
the 16 shareholders had filed suit against those parties to seek reimbursement of the settlement costs from them, and the reorganization plan would cause those suits to be dismissed
daniel krasner, a lawyer for one of the shareholders, said the attorneys for the shareholders would study the documents and decide by monday whether to continue opposing the plan
texaco shareholders are voting on the reorganization proposal and a bankruptcy court hearing is scheduled for next week to hear the results of the vote as well as arguments on whether the judge should confirm the plan
in papers filed with bankruptcy judge howard schwartzberg, icahn, who controls about 14.8 percent of texaco's shares, said he would vote for the reorganization proposal but urged the judge to drop the liability release
the releases are a purely gratuitous act and an unconscionable act of self-dealing by texaco's directors,'' he said
continued uncertainty in the financial markets has not greatly undermined u.s. business executives' expectations for second quarter sales and profits, according to a survey published today by dun &amp; bradstreet corp
the business research company polled 1,500 executives nationwide between feb. 9 and feb. 23 for its latest quarterly business expectations survey
based on the survey, dun &amp; bradstreet's sales optimism index for the second quarter remained strong at 69, down only slightly from 70 in the first three months of the year
the executives' outlook for higher profits in the coming quarter improved modestly, with the profit expectations index rising to 64 from 63 in the first quarter
expectations for higher sales and profits are still at the highest levels since 1984, when the current business expansion was at its peak,'' said joseph w. duncan, corporate economist and chief statistician for dun &amp; bradstreet. ``business people remain confident in the future, despite lingering uncertainty in the financial markets.''
expectations for higher prices remained stable at an index of 41, unchanged from the first quarter
results by industry sector differed widely. among executives from manufacturing companies, the price expectation index fell to 38 from 40 in the first quarter, while the index for retailing companies moved up to 42 from 36
expectations for increased business inventories were higher, with the index rising to 28 from 23, with most of the gain anticipated in the manufacturing sector. the employment expectations index fell to 23 from 26, mainly because of anticipated declines in retailing and wholesaling, while the index for new orders rose to 69 from 67
bankruptcies, bank failures and a criminal investigation of texas' savings and loan industry continue to bash the state's financial image as the nation's biggest and the best, and analysts say the worst isn't over
banking analyst herb jones of the investment firm eppler, guerin &amp; turner says texans used to brag that everything in the state was bigger, better, the best
we can't say that now. we look at the northeast and see their growth is far superior to ours. that was never supposed to happen,'' jones said wednesday
as the state's largest bank-holding company seeks federal rescue, the nation's perception of texas has become more negative, analysts say
dallas-based first republicbank corp., with $33.2 billion in deposits and 134 banking facilities statewide, acknowledged tuesday it was seeking federal help because of a deteriorating loan portfolio and difficulty in raising deposits
gerald w. fronterhouse, chairman and chief executive officer, said a loss of $1 billion in deposits since the beginning of february contributed to the bank's decision
there are signs the state's battered economy is rebounding and that the energy industry is revitalizing, but analysts say the banking industry still lags, coping with mistakes made one to three years ago and the continuing troubles in real estate
real estate is still a real thorn here,'' jones said. ``i expect some further weakness in the real estate sector.''
also hurting the state's image are the bankruptcy court petitions of such texas notables as former gov. john connally, who was u.s. treasury secretary under president nixon; connally's lieutenant governor, ben barnes; oil heir cullen davis of fort worth; famed heart surgeon denton cooley; some businesses of the billionaire hunt brothers; former dallas cowboys owner clint murchison; and the western co. of north america, owned by texas rangers owner eddie chiles
the number of texas bank failures, meanwhile, continues soaring, nearly doubling from 26 in 1986 to 50 in 1987, and stands at 15 so far this year
we do have some other banks that are in trouble. i have no reason to think we've hit the bottom of the problem. there could still be some more (banks) to be heard from,'' jones said
staggering losses continue at other banks _ with the state's seven largest bank-holding companies losing a combined $2.6 billion last year. by contrast, all texas banks lost $883.2 million in 1986
regulators also say more than one-third of the state's 281 savings and loan institutions are insolvent. the fbi and the u.s. justice department are in the midst of a criminal investigation of some of the state's thrifts, called the largest white-collar probe in the southwest's history
tuesday, houston-based first city bancorporation of texas inc. extended its deadline for debt holders to redeem their securities at a discount under a rescue plan representing the second-largest bank bailout in u.s. history
jones said he believes a major financial institution will come into texas and take over first republicbank, if the federal deposit insurance corp. makes it an attractive deal
it's a very desirable institution, at a price,'' jones said. ``a lot of worms are in there still. will the fdic pick them up? that's the question. i think they will. they're going to have to.''
first republicbank's plea for federal aid is a ``bittersweet story,'' said alan coleman, director of the southwestern graduate school of banking at southern methodist university
the good news is that new capital will be brought into the state, along with new faces and new investors. but the bad news, he said, is that ``it's very tough on the people struggling with the problems here.''
firestone tire &amp; rubber co. has gained a court victory in its attempt to thwart a takeover by italian tiremaker pirelli, with a federal judge's refusal to block ohio's anti-takeover law as unconstitutional
u.s. district judge alice m. batchelder ruled wednesday that the ohio control share acquisition act does not violate federal law by discriminating against interstate commerce, or causing inconsistent state regulation
pirelli societe generale sa had sought a preliminary injunction against the law in attempting to press an unsolicited $58 a share, or $1.9 billion, takeover bid for firestone, which has its north american tire headquarters in akron
firestone stock closed at $63.12{ a share wednesday on the new york stock exchange, unchanged from tuesday's close
the ohio statute requires a hostile bidder to wait up to 50 days for shareholders to vote before it may purchase tendered shares. federal law requires that any tender offer remain open for no less than 20 business days
judge batchelder said it was possible for companies to comply with both ohio and federal law
the ohio act... by allowing the shareholders collectively to evaluate the fairness of the tender offer and to vote as a group, ...furthers the policy of investor protection,'' ms. batchelder wrote in a 14-page opinion
the ohio statute does not discriminate against interstate commerce or cause inconsistent state regulation because it has the same effects on bidders from inside and outside of ohio, she stated
pirelli's $1.9 billion offer is contingent on firestone dropping its plans to sell 75 percent of its tire business to bridgestone corp. of japan
firestone officials said pirelli's offer effectively killed earlier plans to sell most of the firestone tire-making business to bridgestone, but it again was talking with bridgestone about other options
the u.s. tire maker said it would advise shareholders by friday on the pirelli offer
henley group inc., a two-year-old holding company, says it plans to split into two public companies and buy back 22 percent of its stock
the stock buy-back announced wednesday would cost about $512 million at current prices
henley jumped $1.75 a share to close at $25.625 a share in over-the-counter trading
henley is an amalgam of 35 construction, environmental, energy, chemcial, manufacturing and finance businesses spun off in april 1986 by allied-signal inc., which itself was formed by a $5 billion merger in 1985
henley has gained a reputation for tightening operations to boost profits in individual units and then taking those units public. the current market value of henley's investments in its subsidiaries that have publicly traded shares and its other long-term investment securities is $2 billion
in recent months henley has been involved in a so-far unsuccessful bid for santa fe southern pacific corp., the chicago-based railroad, land and natural resources giant
under the restructuring, which was approved in principle by the company's board on wednesday, henley's assets would be divided between two public companies:
_wheelabrator group inc., which already is publicly traded, would take over henley's stake in its successful wheelabrator technologies inc. subsidiary and other assets related to the refuse-to-energy business
wheelabrator group would have the flexibility and resources to speed up the expansion of its businesses through mergers, acquisitions and joint ventures
_a newly created entity, to be called henley group inc., would own signal capital corp., signal landmark holdings inc., henley manufacturing corp. and henley's stake in fisher scientific group inc., plus other assets
this program will enable our shareholders to participate directly in henley's $650 million investment in wheelabrator technologies, the nation's leading refuse-to-energy business,'' said michael dingman, henley's chairman and chief executive
shares of the new entity that will be created for henley's other holdings will be distributed to stockholders as a partially taxable special dividend, the company said
henley's board also authorized the repurchase of 20 million of the company's 90 million outstanding shares. the number of outstanding shares peaked at 129 million in november 1986 before the company initiated a series of stock buy-backs
after the buy-back is completed, henley will have repurchased nearly 43 percent of its stock
separately, henley said it decided to waive protection under a recently enacted delaware statute providing that a holder of 15 percent of a company's stock is prohibited from merging with the company or undertaking certain other actions for three years
we do not believe it is in the best interests of shareholders to impose these restrictions,'' dingman said. ``we prefer to give investors a free hand to make those decisions.''
henley's top management owns about 6.5 million of the company's shares. that stake would rise to 9.3 percent with the completion of the stock repurchase
henley spokesman norman ritter said management wasn't considering a bid to take the company private
henley also said it intends to raise $1 billion by issuing notes, then using the proceeds to pay off its current $980 million in bank debt. that will allow the company to arrange $2.5 billion in new bank credit, henley said
sears, roebuck and co. has agreed to buy western auto supply co. in a $402 million deal that some industry watchers call the biggest step sears has taken to increase its specialty retailing operations
sears, the nation's largest general retailer, announced wednesday it would pay $19 a share to acquire 52.3 percent of western auto's 13 million outstanding shares that are held by company management and the investment firm wesray capital corp
if western auto's board of directors approves the merger, sears would acquire the remaining shares at the same price. sears said it reserved the right to cancel the deal if the western auto board of directors fails to give its approval to the tender offer by friday
the stock buyout totals $250 million, and sears also would assume $152 million in debt held by the auto supply company
this is the first really significant step sears has made into specialty retailing,'' said john landschultz, an analyst with mesirow &amp; co. in chicago
sears previously had acquired other specialty operations, including its eye care centers of america, pinstripe petites, its paint and hardware store and sears business systems stores
sears chairman edward a. brennan called the acquisition ``an important part of sears' previously announced plan to expand its presence in specialty retailing.''
brennan said western auto is ``an ideal complement to sears merchandise group, which for decades has been one of the nation's leading retailers of automotive parts and services.''
western auto share jumped $6 to $18.50 a share in national over-the-counter stock trading. sears rose 12{ cents to $37.87{ on the new york stock exchange
western auto will continue to operate under its name and management, sears said
the kansas city-based company sells auto supplies, tires, appliances and lawn and garden equipment through 278 retail stores it owns and through 1,570 independently owned western auto outlets, which buy the products wholesale
sears said john t. lundegard, western auto's chairman and chief executive officer, would remain as head of the auto supply unit and would report to alfred g. goldstein, president of sears' specialty merchandising
last year, western auto had a profit of $10.5 million on sales of $930.8 million
sears earned $1.65 billion and had revenue of $48.4 billion last year, including sales of about $2 billion in automotive parts and services
tokyo's main stock market barometer climbed today to a level higher than just before the october crash, while the dollar fell slightly in lackluster trading, traders said
the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues closed at 25,872.29, up 167.86 points, or 0.65 percent. on oct. 19, the index closed at 25,746.56, before plunging by 3,836.48 points the following day
individual investors played a big role in the strong market activity,'' said an exchange dealer at a major commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``it is the first time the index has gone beyond the level recorded just prior to the oct. 20 crash.''
he said last minute transactions by many local businesses in preparation for the fiscal year beginning april 1 also contributed to the market's bullish performance
today was the third consecutive trading day that the index climbed. the nikkei posted a 228.76-point, or 0.90 percent, gain wednesday
investors are bullish for high prices lying ahead, and the market will have to find some negative factors about the japanese economy before investors are going to back off,'' said masahiro umemori, a stock analyst with nomura securities, japan's largest brokerage firm
meanwhile, on the tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 127.43 yen, down 0.06 yen from wednesday's close of 127.49 yen
the currency traded in a narrow range between 127.40 yen and 127.71 yen as market participants waited for the release later today of u.s. trade figures for january
the dollar has been pressured lower in the past by u.s. trade reports showing a growing imbalance of imports over exports. but as recent reports have shown improvements in the trade gap, the u.s. currency has stabilized
basically, the foreign exchange market is real quiet,'' said a trader from a major investment firm, speaking on condition of anonymity
there was no ``real action,'' he added
the united states posted a $12.1 billion deficit in december
share prices were lower at midday thursday, but well above their worst levels, helped by a cut in bank base lending rates
trading was subdued, however, amid nervousness ahead of the release of u.s. trade data for january
the financial times-stock exchange 100-share index was down 6.2 points, or 0.3 percent, at 1,819.5 at midday
