the canadian dollar traded above 80 u.s. cents today for the first time in four years
buoyed by wednesday's report of an increase in canada's foreign trade surplus, the canadian currency was quoted as high as 80.08 u.s. cents in mid-morning trading on foreign exchange markets
the canadian dollar last traded above 80 u.s. cents on feb. 24, 1984. it is now more than 10 cents above its all-time low of 69.13 u.s. cents recorded in february 1986
the currency, which ended 1987 at 76.93 u.s. cents, has risen steadily this year
the trend is good news for canadians who buy goods imported from the united states and who travel south of the border. but it is bad news for canadian manufacturers, who send 80 percent of their exports to the united states. general news wires</note>
allowing private companies to go into the mail delivery business could improve service, but such a drastic change must be phased in gradually, the president's commission on privatization says
over time, the government monopoly on delivering letters should be ended, with immediate steps to allow private firms to deliver advertising and to operate in rural areas, the commission recommends
the mail recommendations are part of a detailed report on privatizing various government operations, scheduled to be released friday at the white house
other aspects of the study include developing a system of private air traffic control towers; issuing vouchers for low-income housing instead of building public housing units; selling the government's $250 billion loan portfolio; and issuing vouchers for public school education
in general, the study reports, the benefits of switching to a competitive mail delivery system would outweigh the problems, although the changeover could be confusing and costly
the overall costs of postal service should be reduced through competition, the commission concluded, and efficiency could be improved. the report noted that the growth of competition in parcel delivery has provided consumer with more alternatives and price competition
officials of the u.s. postal service said thursday they could not comment on the report until they have had a chance to study it
however, major unions representing postal workers already have fired a volley at the study based on preliminary reports of what it would contain
if mail delivery is opened to competition, private companies will skim off the money-making city delivery routes and leave the more expensive rural deliveries to the postal service, the national association of letter carriers contended. the american postal workers union also has opposed privatization plans
such a change would destroy the nation's system of universal service, the letter carrier's union charged, ``rural and inner-city residents would not be served by private firms and-or would receive reduced service at exorbitant postage rates.''
former postmaster general preston r. tisch last fall termed the idea of privatization a ``dubious'' solution, contending that the changeover would be ``chaotic and impractical.''
the conservative heritage foundation, however, has lent its support to at least limited privatization, calling for rule changes to allow private firms to deliver third-class advertising mail and for increased contracting out of postal services
the recommendations of the privatization commission are more sweeping, however, if tempered with the caution that the changeover could be confusing, as was the switch from a telephone monopoly to a system of competing systems
changing to a private system could cause problems for many of the postal services' 800,000 workers, and tax money could be required to assist in finding new jobs and in retraining, the study indicates
in addition, the change could result in varying postage rates according to which company a mailer used, perhaps including differing rates depending on distance traveled
questions also arise about liability for lost mail and the process of notifying a variety of companies about changes of address, the study noted
even so, it contends, the long-run benefits should outweigh the problems associated with a change
the recommendation comes at a trying time for the postal service, caught in a public relations bind between congressional budget cutting which has forced it to reduce window hours and collections at the same time rates are being raised
here is a rundown of the basic postal service recommendations of the commission:
_open mail delivery to competition, but on a gradual basis with compensation for postal workers and managers for loss of benefits and earnings
_consider turning the postal service itself into a private business, perhaps by selling stock in the agency to its employees
_immediately end restrictions on private firms delivering third-class advertising, widely known as ``junk'' mail
_immediately open up rural delivery to competition
_end restrictions on private firms placing mail in letter boxes at people's homes
_ease restrictions on delivery of express mail
_actively pursue all possibilities for contracting out services
the u.s. dollar rose against all major foreign currencies except the canadian dollar in european trading thursday following the release of better-than-expected u.s. trade figures. gold prices fell
the u.s. commerce department reported that the merchandise trade deficit widened slightly to $12.4 billion in january from $12.2 billion in december. many traders had expected a trade deficit in the range of $12.8 billion
the market was very nervous immediately after the release (of the trade figures) because the dollar didn't immediately shoot up,'' said a foreign currency dealer in frankfurt, west germany
but gradually the dollar started moving up and that built up some momentum.''
in tokyo, before the trade figures were announced, the dollar dipped to a closing 127.43 yen from 127.49 yen at wednesday's close. in later london trading, it was quoted at 128.15 yen
in london, the dollar gained more than one cent against the british pound. one pound cost $1.8385 in london late thursday, down from $1.8505 late wednesday
the pound began falling thursday morning after major banks cut their base lending rates to 8.5 percent from 9 percent
other late dollar rates in europe, compared with late wednesday's rates, included: 1.6775 west german marks, up from 1.6690; 1.3940 swiss francs, up from 1.3810; 5.7175 french francs, up from 5.6782; 1.8885 dutch guilders, up from 1.8750; 1,244.37 italian lire, up from 1,238.45; and 1.2493 canadian dollars, down from 1.2518
gold prices eased in sluggish european trading as the dollar's rise made gold less attractive for investors
gold fell in london to a late bid of $443 a troy ounce, compared with late wednesday's $446.20. in zurich, it closed at a bid $445, slightly lower than $445.25 late wednesday
earlier, gold closed in hong kong at a bid of $448.75, up from $447.79
silver bullion prices dipped on the london market, where silver was trading at a late bid of $6.34 a troy ounce, compared with wednesday's $6.36 an ounce
the canadian dollar, buoyed by higher interest rates north of the border, rose to 80 u.s. cents thursday for the first time in four years
analysts said the possibility that central american instability might drive prices higher for oil and other commodities was one reason the canadian currency's overnight rise from 79.9 u.s. cents to 80.08 cents
because of canada's dependence on oil, grain, mineral and lumber exports, the canadian dollar is viewed on international exchanges as a semi-commodity based currency
it had been testing the psychologically important 80-cent mark for the past two weeks
the fundamentals support the canadian dollar right now,'' said money market specialist june riley of the royal bank of canada
the fact that we have not had strong intervention by the bank of canada suggests that as long as the canadian dollar is moving in an orderly fashion, it could go higher.''
she also attributed some of the overnight strengthening to speculators, riding the canadian currency's recent upswing
the higher canadian dollar is bad news for american tourists, who got $1.40 for their u.s. dollars two years ago and now get $1.20 at hotels and stores. but for thousands of canadians making their annual late-winter pilgrimage to florida or arizona, the new exchange rate is a windfall
the two dollars were last at par in 1976, and the canadian currency dipped to an all-time low of 69.13 u.s. cents in february 1986. it was last worth 80 cents on feb. 24, 1984
it has risen 15 percent since then, with a 4-cent surge this year after governor john crow of the bank of canada made it clear that high interest rates will prevail until inflation is virtually eradicated. canada's annual inflation rate is now 4.1 percent
prime minister brian mulroney's conservative government has been more equivocal on the issue, under pressure from exporters whose goods cost more as the dollar appreciates. nearly 80 percent of canadian exports go to the united states
finance minister michael wilson said last week that interest rates may dip as soon as inflation falls below 4 percent
but exporters' concerns were undermined this week when the government reported better-than-expected merchandise trade figures for january. canada's surplus of 633 million dollars, or $506 million u.s., was up from december's surplus of 207 million dollars, or $165 million
key canadian interest rates, such as for eurodollar deposits, are 1.5 percent higher than u.s. dollar rates
other factors behind the canadian currency's rise include the anticipated strengthening of oil and commodity prices in the wake of u.s. troop deployment in honduras and the closing of the trans-panama oil pipeline, riley said
a strike by electrical workers cut off power to the trans-panama oil pipeline wednesday, halting the flow of alaska north slope crude oil to markets on the u.s. gulf coast, state officials said
electrical service was restored early thursday, but then was interrupted again, prompting the panamanian government to announce it was taking over all public utilities
the pipeline carries 650,000 barrels a day of alaska oil, roughly 10 percent of u.s. domestic production. a barrel is equivalent to 42 gallons
bp america inc. and its subsidiary sohio oil own two-thirds to three-quarters of the oil flowing through the pipeline. the rest is owned by exxon co. usa
the flow was halted at 2 p.m. est wednesday when electrical workers joined a widespread strike against gen. manuel antonio noriega, said tim reynolds, a bp america spokesman in washington, d.c. the strike cut off power to a pump station at the foot of a mountain, he said
bp america has a one-day supply of oil already on the gulf of mexico side of panama, and does not expect to initiate contingency plans yet, reynolds said
nonetheless we are taking steps to set up a ship-to-ship transfer operation so if necessary we can put at least some oil through the panama canal,'' he said
bp america is not sure how much oil it could move through the canal. the amount would depend on the availability of small tankers and canal congestion, reynolds said
state officials, the alaska congressional delegation and oil companies also are studying alternatives including taking the oil around africa's cape horn or getting a waiver to the federal ban on exports of alaska oil
state officials have been worried about a panama pipeline shutdown because it could slow sales of alaska crude, which account for the bulk of state revenues
west coast oil markets are glutted with alaska oil, and the federal export ban prevents its sale overseas
chuck logsdon, chief oil revenue analyst for the state, said the gulf coast markets have been handling more than 600,000 barrels of the total daily alaska production of 1.8 million to 1.9 million barrels. trend</head>
an increase in mortgage foreclosure and delinquency rates in texas is further evidence of regional economic problems, the mortgage bankers association said
the nationwide foreclosure and delinquency rates are improving, but mba spokesman tom marder said the figures, released wednesday, show that economic problems remain, particularly in the oil and farm states
the trend nationally for two years has been toward lower delinquency and foreclosure rates,'' marder said. ``obviously, some of the regional problems still exist.''
the association's figures show that at the end of the last quarter, 1.56 percent of the mortgages surveyed in texas were in foreclosure, up from 1.53 percent for the same period last year
this gives texas the ninth-highest foreclosure rate in the nation
another 8.72 percent were at least 30 days delinquent as of december, a substantial increase from the 7.92 percent delinquent as of the year before
foreclosures nationwide represented 1.06 percent of the total home loans, and 5.37 percent of the loans were delinquent
the association speculated three months ago that problems in the oil patch appeared to be drying up after an improvement in the third quarter. in that quarter, the survey showed 1.19 percent of the loans in texas were in foreclosure and another 7.64 percent were delinquent
the mba reported that although some regions have had disappointing foreclosure and delinquency levels, ``the solutions to these regional problems are of a long-term nature ... there is reason to expect delinquencies to resume their previous downward trend in due course.''
alaska and wyoming ranked first and second on the list of foreclosure and delinquency rates, while rhode island was last
alaska, which also has been severely affected by the plunge in oil prices, had 5.92 percent mortgages in foreclosure, up from 3.55 percent for the same period of last year. alaska's delinquencies also increased, to 11.85 percent in the past quarter, up from 10.18 percent
next on the list was wyoming, with 5.39 percent in foreclosure last quarter, a decline from 5.84 percent in the same period of last year. wyoming also saw a slight improvement in its delinquent loans, to 6.26 percent, a decline from the 7.90 registered last year in the same quarter
rhode island had the lowest foreclosure rate of all states at 0.09 percent
stocks rose in active trading today, buoyed by corporate takeover maneuvering and favorable investor response to the government's report of a lower-than-expected january trade deficit
the dow jones average of 30 industrials advanced 11.28 points to 2,075.60 by 2 p.m. est
among broader market barometers, the nyse's composite index of all listed common stocks rose 0.80 to 152.08. the american stock exchange's market value index rose 0.83 to 298.34
advancing issues outnumbered losers by slightly more than a 3-to-2 margin on the new york stock exchange, with 902 up, 556 down and 466 unchanged. volume on the big board totaled 150.48 million shares with two hours of trading left
although the trade deficit reported by the commerce department widened slightly in january to $12.4 billion from $12.2 billion in december, market economists had expected an even greater gap of about $13 billion
the news therefore provided an optimistic tone to stock trading and substantiated other evidence that the economy is growing despite fears of a slowdown raised by the october crash
i think the trade number was just what everybody liked,'' said philip c. puccio, manager of institutional trading at dillon, read &amp; co. in new york. ``it brought a sigh of relief.''
nevertheless, puccio and other trading strategists said investors still were reluctant to commit large amounts of cash to the stock market, at least until the conclusion of ``triple witching hour'' on friday
that quarterly event is so-named because of the near-simultaneous expiration of contracts to buy or sell stock-index futures, stock options and futures. it has contributed to wild price swings in the past
takeover related buying played a role in lifting stocks today. rumors of impending acquisition attempts on pillsbury, philips petroleum and u.s. shoe sent those stocks sharply higher in active trading. pillsbury rose 3[ to 45[; phillips rose 1| to 17~ and u.s. shoe rose 2] to 24~
american standard rose 1[ to 76| after investment firm kelso &amp; co. agreed to buy the company for $78 a share, topping a hostile $73 a share offer from black &amp; decker corp. black &amp; decker rose 1 to 19{
digital fell 4] to 113\, apparently in response to merrill lynch's reduced earnings estimates for the computer company
west germany officially gave its support to the proposed establishment of a western european central bank that would be independent of common market governments
finance minister gerhard stoltenberg said thursday that the 12-nation common market should free all movements of capital within its borders and strengthen the european monetary system in its efforts to achieve closer economic cooperation and integration
free capital movement without controls and limitations is the most important monetary policy reform for the near future,'' stoltenberg said
in a memorandum prepared for his fellow cabinet ministers and other western european governments, stoltenberg reaffirmed west germany's commitment to closer economic integration among the member nations of the european economic community
he also said that, at the end of the process, there should be a european central bank
stoltenberg's statement came less than three weeks after west german foreign minister hans-dietrich genscher proposed setting up a european committee of experts to outline a course of action for further european economic integration
the document adds further momentum to a discussion that started late last year when french economics minister edouard balladur proposed establishing a european central bank
stoltenberg said in his memorandum that a european central bank should be committed to price stability and should be independent of both common market authorities and member governments
the central bank issue is expected to be discussed at the eec summit in hanover, west germany, on june 27 and 28
sen. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, warned cable television operators thursday that congress will consider reregulating the industry if rates continue to rise and programming is withheld from competitors
some of us feel we were had'' by the congressional decision that freed most cable operators of municipal rate control in january 1987 and let them set their own prices, metzenbaum said
this congress is ready to re-examine that whole issue,'' said metzenbaum at a hearing of the senate judiciary's subcommittee on antitrust, monopolies and business rights, which he chairs
metzenbaum, the only senator present during much of the hearing, said congress is concerned that cable tv operators, an $11 billion a year industry that serves 51 percent of american households, enjoy a monopoly that can freeze out competing tv distribution systems and raise prices
james p. mooney, president of the national cable television association, disputed metzenbaum's charge that cable prices have ``zoomed upwards'' by up to 400 percent in some areas since deregulation
mooney said an ncta study shows that the average cable subscriber's monthly bill rose 6.7 percent in the first six months after deregulation. while basic service prices rose about 10.6 percent, rates for premium or pay channels, like home box office, dropped 2.5 percent, according to the study
mooney said that while some people saw large increases in their rates as cable companies realigned their services, most people paid only a small increase and also received more channels than they did before deregulation
metzenbaum also said he was concerned about complaints by cable competitors that distribute tv programming via microwave and satellite that they are being strangled by the cable industry's control over programming
cable operators have a stake in many of the major satellite programmers, like hbo, showtime, turner broadcasting and mtv, he said
george kocian, spokesman for the home satellite television association, which represents owners and dealers of home satellite dishes, told the committee the cable industry has tried to prevent the growth of the home dish market by controlling access to and the price of programming
about 2 million households receive tv directly from backyard dishes. most programming is now scrambled, so a dish owner must purchase a decoder costing about $400 to unscramble the signals
kocian said the association does not oppose scrambling, but he said dish owners should not have to pay the same prices as cable subscribers since they have to incur more of the cost of service, like buying a decoder and maintaining their dish antenna
consumers are willing to pay a fair price,'' he said. ``but we are not being treated fairly or equally.''
joseph collins, president of hbo, the nation's largest pay tv company, said backyard dish owners can subscribe to hbo's scrambled signal directly from hbo or from a cable operator. dish subscribers pay about two-thirds the price that cable subscribers do, he said
there is no denial of access,'' he said
however, he said the company has had problems with microwave-based tv delivery systems that distribute hbo programming unscrambled. in such cases, nonsubscribers with an appropriate antenna can intercept these transmissions and watch hbo for free, he said
opec president rilwanu lukman said thursday he will announce new measures to bring stability to dropping oil prices on march 22
lukman's two-paragraph statement did not say what the measures would involve. the statement said the measures would be announced at a 10:00 a.m. (4 a.m. est) press conference and should bring stability to the volatile oil market
on tuesday, lukman accused the western press of trying to destabilize the oil market to bring down prices. he said opec would not be stampeded into taking emergency measures to stop the fall of oil prices
he said the cartel would stand firm on its decision to produce 15.6 million barrels of oil a day. a barrel is the equivalent of 42 gallons
ministry sources, who declined to be identified, said lukman would call an emergency opec meeting soon after the march 22 press conference if consultations between members promised meaningful discussion at the meeting
the sources said price stability would be the main topic of discussion if the meeting were held. a report by a private audit team on the level of oil production among cartel members would also be an issue
grain and soybean futures prices posted strong gains thursday on the chicago board of trade
soybeans were up more than 14 cents a bushel and wheat gained as much as a nickel
a large speculator bought sizeable amounts of beans and soybean products to offset earlier sales, said dale gustafson, an analyst with drexel, burnham lambert inc
that ignited it,'' he said. ``it prompted a lot of short covering by commission houses.''
corn and wheat futures were helped by the rally in beans, said gustafson
wheat also did well because there are indications the chinese are chartering some vessels, so maybe there's some new buying coming in,'' he said
on the close, wheat was 3{ cents to 5 cents higher with the contract for delivery in march at $2.97{ a bushel; corn was 1\ cents to 2 cents higher with march at $1.99 a bushel; oats were 2} cents to 4\ cents higher wit march at $1.94 a bushel; and soybeans were 14{ cents to 16\ cents higher with march at $6.26 a bushel
the securities and exchange commission dealt r.h. macy &amp; co. inc.'s bid for federated department stores inc. a setback today by recommending to a federal judge that campeau corp's. revised tender offer for federated be regarded as an amendment to a previous offer rather than a new bid
if the judge agrees, the campeau bid could expire as scheduled, more than two weeks before macy's competing offer. macy fears that federated shareholders will feel pressured to tender their shares to campeau because of the earlier deadline
in a ``friend of the court'' brief, the sec told u.s. district judge leonard sand the revised bid announced by campeau march 2 was not a new offer, and as such did not have to remain open for 20 business days past its publication
the revised offer changed the number of shares campeau was seeking and the price to be paid for those shares
macy has asked sand to declare the latest campeau bid a new offer, which would keep it open past its scheduled expiration
campeau announced today it was extending its offer beyond friday to midnight march 22. however, sand ruled earlier this week that both companies' offers must remain open for three business days after his decision on the macy challenge and on a campeau suit that seeks to invalidate federated's shareholders rights plan
sand had sought the sec opinion on the macy argument. it was not known when he would make his ruling
macy had no comment on the sec's opinion, said maureen milano, a spokeswoman for the retailer
a campeau spokeswoman, joele frank, said ``we're pleased'' about the sec's opinion, but ``it's really up to the judge.''
macy, whose bid expires on april 4, wants a later expiration for the campeau offer because it would put the competing bids on a more equal footing
campeau claimed its offer cannot go forward while the rights plan, known as a ``poison pill,'' remains in effect. the plan allows current federated shareholders to buy more of the company's stock at a steep discount, making a takeover prohibitively expensive
macy is offering $77.35 a share in cash for 70.43 million federated shares, for a total of $6.3 billion. macy will exchange shares in the merged company and issue convertible debt securities for the remainder of federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares
campeau is offering $75 in cash per share for 70.5 million federated shares, or a total of $6.18 billion. the remaining of federated stock would be acquired later for $44 cash per share in a subsequent merger, giving the deal an aggregate value of $68 per share
the stock market rose today, buoyed by corporate takeover maneuvering and favorable investor response to the government's report of a lower-than-expected january trade deficit
the dow jones average of 30 industrials was up 5.81 points to 2,070.13 by 3 p.m. est
among broader market barometers, the nyse's composite index of all listed common stocks rose 0.48 to 151.76. the american stock exchange's market value index rose 1.04 to 298.55
advancing issues outnumbered losers by slightly more than a 3-to-2 margin on the new york stock exchange, with 857 up, 614 down and 480 unchanged. volume on the big board totaled 169.45 million shares with one hour of trading left
although the trade deficit reported by the commerce department widened slightly in january to $12.4 billion from $12.2 billion in december, market economists had expected an even greater gap of about $13 billion
the news therefore provided an optimistic tone to stock trading and substantiated other evidence that the economy is growing despite fears of a slowdown raised by the october crash
i think the trade number was just what everybody liked,'' said philip c. puccio, manager of institutional trading at dillon, read &amp; co. in new york. ``it brought a sigh of relief.''
nevertheless, puccio and other trading strategists said investors still were reluctant to commit large amounts of cash to the stock market, at least until the conclusion of ``triple witching hour'' on friday
that quarterly event is so-named because of the near-simultaneous expiration of contracts to buy or sell stock-index futures, stock options and futures. it has contributed to wild price swings in the past
takeover related buying played a role in lifting stocks today. rumors of impending acquisition attempts on pillsbury, philips petroleum and u.s. shoe sent those stocks sharply higher in active trading. pillsbury rose 3 to 45; phillips rose 1 to 17\ and u.s. shoe rose 2[ to 24|
