managers at fairfax publications (u.s.) ltd. said thursday they are negotiating to buy ms. and sassy magazines from the company's australian parent
john fairfax ltd. of sydney, which acquired ms. in september and launched sassy five months later, officially put the magazines on the block wednesday. it was not known who else might be bidding for the properties
sandra yates, president of fairfax u.s., said she and vice president anne summers began discussing a management-led buyout with executives in australia last december. yates said a bid is now on the table, although she declined to reveal any figures
yates labeled as ``optimistic'' rumors that the australian company paid as much as $15 million for ms., which was founded by gloria steinem and pat carbine 16 years ago
in an interview last month, yates acknowledged that start-up costs for sassy, a monthly magazine aimed at teen-age american girls, totaled $10 million
the decision to sell the magazines is part of a wider sale of assets to help finance the privatization of john fairfax ltd
twenty-six-year-old warwick fairfax, who took his father's company private last december, ``had to borrow significant funds to buy out shareholders and has a large debt and needs to liquidate assets,'' yates explained
mr. fairfax has announced other belt-tightening measures at company holdings in both australia and london
ms. circulation is holding steady at about 484,000 copies a month, yates said. sassy was expected to have an initial circulation of 250,000 and a goal of 1 million within five years. because only two issues of sassy have been published, it is too early to assess its circulation
yates said both the acquisition of the badly undercapitalized ms. and the launching of sassy by fairfax were her idea. ``so obviously i've always been very firmly convinced they could work.''
still, both magazines will require ``a substantial amount of investment over the next couple of years _ many millions of dollars before they come into profit because one is a turnaround and the other is a start-up,'' yates said
she said she did not think finding investors would be a problem
manufacturing and retailing conglomerate wickes cos. inc. on thursday posted a turnaround in fourth-quarter earnings and a 116 percent jump in profits for its fiscal year
however, earnings for the year ended jan. 30 were boosted primarily by $126.7 million in gains on assets sales and extraordinary items
for the fourth quarter, the company netted $8.3 million, or 15 cents per share, compared to the year-earlier period when it had a loss of $2.5 million
revenues for the period were up 9.6 percent to $832.5 million from $759.8 million, reflecting wickes' acquisition of collins &amp; aikman corp., the new york-based textile concern, in december 1986 for $1.16 billion
for the full year, the wickes earned $180.5 million, or $3.68 per share, compared to the previous year when it earned $83.7 million, or $1.65 per share. the per-share figures for fiscal 1987 were restated to reflect a one-for-five reverse stock split that took effect last august
revenues for the past year were up 61.9 percent to $3.48 billion from $2.15 billion
the company's income from continuing operations, which does not include taxes or gains from assets sales and extraordinary items, rose to $14.6 million from $3.1 million for the quarter, and slipped to $69.1 million from $69.6 million for the year
the stock market closed higher today, helped by takeover-related buying and a better-than-expected report on the nation's trade deficit
but wall street strategists said the volume of trading did not reflect a surge of investor confidence and probably was caused by fears about the market's unpredictable behavior on ``triple witching hour'' friday
that quarterly event, so-named because of the near-simultaneous expirations of contracts to buy or sell stock-index futures, options and futures on individual stocks, has injected wildness into the market in the past
i suspect traders are waiting for the triple witching hour to get out of the way,'' said philip c. puccio, manager of institutional trading at dillon, read &amp; co. in new york
japan overtook the united states last year in economic output per person, according to a report thursday that highlighted that nation's relentless rise as an economic superpower
the report by japan's economic planning agency was the latest in a string of reports on the island nation's growing wealth. for example, the tokyo stock exchange has become the world's largest, and most of the world's largest banks are japanese
the agency said japan's per-capita gross national product _ the output of goods and services for each member of the population _ reached the equivalent of $19,642 in 1987, compared with $18,403 in the united states
japan's ascendance was made possible partly by a strong 4.2 percent increase in its total gross national product. more important, though, was a 17 percent rise in the value of the japanese yen vs. the dollar from one year to the next
when the yen is strong, it makes japan's economic output more valuable in terms of dollars. it also increases japan's financial muscle in the united states and other markets
as an economic power, the united states has already been surpassed,'' ezra vogel, a harvard university expert in east asian affairs, said in reaction to the report
the critical question is who has the leverage, who has the strategy, who has the critical assets that influence the course of world economic development,'' vogel said
the key people who are able to make new loans are the japanese. people begin to look to the rules of the game as the lender defines it,'' he said
unfortunately, it's continuing to happen,'' he added. ``japan is continuing to collect more chips and the united states is continuing to lose chips.''
the report drew a different reaction from japanese observers, who contended it gives an unrealistic picture because it is based on what they regard as an overvaluation of the japanese yen vs. the dollar
it's kind of magic _ numerical magic. it has no sense in real life,'' said yoshihisa kitai, the economist in the new york office of the long-term credit bank of japan
japan has indeed grown wealthier, but the japanese people still feel poor when they compare their buying power with that of americans, kitai said. land costs are high because of overprotection of farmland, and an inefficient distribution system keeps retail prices high, he said
in 1986, when calculations were based on $1 trading at 168.51 yen, the u.s. gross national product per capita was $17,464 and japan's was $16,330. in 1987, the calculations were based on $1 for 144.62 yen. the dollar currently is trading at about 127 yen
it is difficult to tell what nation has the highest gross national product per capita because of drastic fluctuations from year to year caused by exchange-rate shifts and the rise and fall of oil prices
the united arab emirates was the world's leader in 1985 at $19,120 per capita, followed by the sultanate of brunei at $17,580, the united states at $16,400 and switzerland at $16,380, according to world bank atlas 1987. japan ranked well back at $11,330, the atlas said
although more recent numbers are not available, it is known that the oil-producing nations have fallen in rank because of lower oil prices, while western europe and japan have risen because of stronger currencies
japan had about 122 million people as of the middle of last year, half of the united states' 244 million. but its economic output is more than half that of the united states
japan's inflation-adjusted gnp growth of 4.2 percent in the calendar year 1987 was up from 2.4 percent the previous year, helped by gains in housing and industrial equipment investment
the economic planning agency said japan's gnp grew by an inflation-adjusted 1.7 percent in the october-december quarter from the july-september quarter
the agency said the government's target of 3.7 percent growth for fiscal 1987, which ends march 31, was in reach
the original target was 3.5 percent, but it was revised upward in december based on signs of an encouraging recovery in the manufacturing sector. manufacturing earlier had been slumping because of the yen's rise, which makes japanese products more expensive and less competitive abroad
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 21.72 points to 2,086.04. much of the gain came in the last hour of trading
gaining issues outpaced losers by about 9-to-5 on the new york stock exchange, with 969 up, 544 down and 465 unchanged
big board volume totaled 211.92 million shares, against 153.59 million in the previous session
the nyse's composite index rose 1.40 to 152.68. 
at the american stock exchange, the market value index rose 1.48 to 298.99
h.j. heinz co. said wednesday it acquired the lone producer of toilet and laundry soap in the african nation of botswana
kgalagadi soap industries of gaborone, botswana, which heinz got from overseas development enterprises ltd., operates a 33,000-square-foot facility that makes soap in various forms, including cakes, bars, pieces and pellets
we are happy to begin operations in botswana, a nation with an expanding economy and with an interest in promoting free enterprise,'' said heinz chairman anthony o'reilly
heinz withheld terms of the deal
heinz and the government in neighboring zimbabwe operate olivine industries ltd. a private producer in harare of edible oils, margarines and soaps
may department stores co. said wednesday its earnings rose 8 percent in the fourth quarter and 16.5 percent for 1987 as a whole
may, the nation's seventh-largest retailer, reported earnings of $230 million, or $1.52 a share, in the quarter ended jan. 31, compared with earnings of $213 million, or $1.38 a share, during the same period a year earlier
sales for the latest quarter totaled $3.34 billion, up from $3.1 billion during the final quarter of fiscal 1986
for all of 1987, earnings totaled $444 million, or $2.90 a share, up from $381 million, or $2.44 a share, in fiscal 1986
sales totaled $10.31 billion for the year, up from $9.5 billion in the previous year
may operates 2,960 department, discount and specialty stores. its divisions include lord &amp; taylor and may department stores, venture and caldor discount stores and volume shoe stores
may president thomas a. hays said the company plans to open seven department stores, seven discount stores and about 240 specialty stores in 1988
a food and medical supply irradiation company pleaded guilty wednesday to covering up safety violations, and authorities revealed that its founder _ a leading spokesman for the preservation process _ was negotiating a plea arrangement with prosecutors
radiation technology inc. admitted that a false memorandum saying it had stopped bypassing safety measures at its rockaway plant was prepared and given to nuclear regulatory commission investigators
both the company and federal authorities have said no employees or members of the public were injured because of the violations
the morris plains company, represented by its president, allan booth, also admitted telling the nrc that a radiation safety monitor was removed for only one night when it was actually removed for several days while the plant was irradiating products
radiation technology, which also has plants in west memphis, ark., haw river, n.c., and salem, uses radioactive cobalt-60 to sterilize medical supplies and foodstuffs, mainly spices
on tuesday, prosecutors said thomas powell, who worked as operations manager at the rockaway plant from 1980 to 1985, pleaded guilty to related charges
powell admitted conspiring with others to have employees bypass devices called conveyor door safety interlocks required under its license. the safety locks automatically lower the highly radioactive cobalt-60 materials into a safety pool if they sense the presence of people. powell faces five years in prison, said assistant u.s. attorney jacqueline wolff
the company, which faces a $1 million penalty, admitted that company officials prepared and backdated a memo dated sept. 21, 1984, falsely saying that its employees had been ordered to stop bypassing the interlock system
during a hearing, u.s. district judge maryanne trump barry asked if there was a problem with plea negotiations with the company's founder and former chairman, martin welt
ms. wolff responded that welt had signed a plea agreement admitting to related charges but had decided not to enter the plea
later, ms. wolff said welt's attorneys and her office had been negotiating over a plea and that she did not know the reason why welt did not enter it
welt has spoken frequently in the national media about the value of food irradiation, and even traveled to china last year to promote the process
welt was forced to sever his links to radiation technology in mid-1986 along with powell after the nrc briefly suspended the company's license for the interlock safety violations
ms. wolff said the safety systems were bypassed ``to keep the business going
the interlocks were not operating properly. the thing to do is shut it down,'' she said
in a prepared statement, the company said:
by this guilty plea, rti has acknowledged its legal responsibility for the actions of an officer who submitted false information to the nrc relating to known deficiences in equipment designed to insure operator safety at rti's rockaway facility.''
the company referred all further comment, including who the official was, to its public relations firm, solakian associates
mary solakian said she was not familiar enough with wednesday's hearing to comment, and said her husband was out of the office and could not be reached
in exchange for the company's guilty plea, the government agreed not to further prosecute the firm on the matter and take no position on sentencing unless the judge asks, said ms. wolff
the two broadest measures of the nation's money supply rose in the week ended march 7, the federal reserve board reported thursday
the fed said the measure known as m2 rose to a seasonally adjusted $2,954.5 billion in the latest week from $2,947.4 billion te previous week
an even broader measure, m3, increased to a seasonally adjusted $3,725.4 billion from $3,721.6 billion
the narrowest measure of the money supply, m1, rose to a seasonally adjusted $755.6 billion from a revised $755 billion
m1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts and non-bank travelers checks. m2 is m1 plus accounts like savings deposits and money-market mutual funds. m3 is m2 plus less-liquid accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations of $100,000
in judging its monetary policy, the fed has indicated it is monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the difference between short- and long-term interest rates. it also has shifted its attention from m1 to the two broader money supply measures
the fed said in early 1988 that it would like annual growth for m2 and m3 to be between 4 percent and 8 percent, which is slightly lower than the 1987 target of 5.5 percent to 8.5 percent. the fed has not set a specific target range for m1 since early 1987
in other reports:
_the federal reserve bank of new york reported commercial and industrial loans at major new york city banks fell $1.24 billion in the week ended march 9, compared with a gain of $1.3 billion a week earlier
_the federal reserve said bank borrowings from the federal reserve system at the discount window averaged $153 million a day in the week ended wednesday, compared with $378 million in the previous week
_the federal reserve bank of st. louis reported that the monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at federal reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation, was $272.1 billion in the two-week period ended wednesday, down from $272.4 billion two weeks earlier
bond prices advanced thursday in active trading, lifted by a report on the nation's trade deficit for january that was better than expected
the treasury's closely watched 30-year bond rose about } point, or $7.50 for every $1,000 in face amount. its yield, which moves inversely to its price, dropped to 8.53 percent from 8.60 percent late wednesday
in a long-awaited report, the commerce department said the merchandise trade deficit widened slightly in january to $12.4 billion after two months of sharp improvements. the news cheered the credit markets despite the wider deficit, since most analysts had expected a trade shortfall of around $13 billion
the numbers were pretty juicy,'' said maria ramirez, a managing director of drexel burnham lambert inc
bond prices have been pushed and pulled in recent months by data on the nation's trade performance, mimicking the impact of the figures on the value of the dollar. a positive trade showing tends to bolster the u.s. currency and increase the value of dollar-denominated investments such as bonds
analysts said the market was unaffected by another government report thursday that u.s. factories, mines and utilities operated at 82.4 percent of capacity in february, the third consecutive month the operating rate has been at that level
in the secondary market for treasury bonds, prices of short-term government issues rose 5-32 point to \ point, intermediate maturities advanced 7-16 point to 17-32 point, and 20-year issues gained 11-16 point, according to figures provided by telerate inc., a financial information service
the movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the price of a bond with a $1,000 face value
the merrill lynch daily treasury index, which measures price movements on all outstanding treasury issues with maturities of a year or longer, rose 0.38 to 112.93. the shearson lehman daily treasury bond index, which makes a similar measurement, jumped 5.20 to 1,182.20
moody's investment grade corporate bond index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, edged up 0.76 to 284.27
in the municipal bond market, the bond buyer index of 40 actively traded general obligation and revenue bonds rose 5-32 point to 88 27-32 as of 3 p.m. est. the average yield declined to 8.07 percent from 8.09 percent late wednesday
yields on three-month treasury bills, meanwhile, declined 4 basis points to 5.56 percent. a basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. six-month bills fell 7 basis points to 5.72 percent and one-year bills dropped 8 basis points to 6.18 percent
the federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was quoted late in the day at 6 7-16 percent, up from 6] percent late wednesday
back interest payments on brazilian loans could add $250 million to citicorp's 1988 earnings, chairman and chief executive officer john s. reed said wednesday
citicorp, the nation's largest bank holding company with assets of $203.6 billion, is the leader of negotiations between banks and the brazilian government aimed at restructuring that country's debt
i believe brazil is likely to reach an agreement with the banks, but it is difficult to be assured of it,'' reed told a news conference before a luncheon address to the economic club of detroit
whatever the success of the debt-restructuring talks, brazil's resumption of interest payments will be a boost, reed said
and he said, ``we are quite positive about our own situation.''
they have paid the interest for the fourth quarter of last year. they are paying now the interest due for the first quarter of this year but no one has booked it yet,'' he said. ``we are short $200 million after tax, $333 million before tax, from brazil. so we have the potential of booking in this year one-quarter billion dollars.''
brazil, which owes more than $112 billion abroad and has not repaid any principal since 1983, stopped paying interest on bank debts in february 1987
citicorp was the first bank to respond, in may 1987, by boosting loan-loss reserves, increasing them during the year by about $3 billion
that and other steps ``confused'' citicorp's earnings picture for 1987, reed said. citicorp reported a loss of $1.13 billion for 1987, compared with net income of $1.05 billion in 1986
in 1988, he said, ``we expect to return to a normal year.''
reed said predictions of slower consumer-spending growth this year may have been excessively conservative, as indicated by healthy auto sales and home mortgage activity thus far
mortgage applications to citicorp, which accounts for 6 percent of the nation's single-family home loans, have been higher than expected in the past 30 days, he said
chrysler corp. would like to begin early contract negotiations with the united auto workers on april 18 _ that is, if chrysler's top bargainer isn't serving on a jury
anthony st. john, the company's lead negotiator, said wednesday that chrysler has settled on the tentative date for the start of talks on a contract covering 59,500 active and 8,000 laid-off workers and wants a settlement deadline for sometime in june
uaw spokesman bob barbee said the date won't be confirmed until uaw vice president marc stepp is sure it will fit into a schedule crammed with negotiations with other companies including general dynamics
in general, barbee said, ``it sounds reasonable.''
but st. john, chrysler's vice president for human resources, also has a conflict: he's been called to jury duty in oakland county circuit court for april 18-19
i'm trying to get out of jury duty,'' he said. ``this is my third summons. i asked to postpone one to attend a board meeting.''
as a lawyer _ he began his labor relations career arguing cases for the national labor relations board _ st. john said he is automatically excluded from jury duty in most states, but not in michigan
next week, the uaw's elected 10-member bargaining committee meets in tampa, fla., with stepp and other union officials to prepare demands. its 140-member national chrysler council meets april 5-7 in missouri to approve them
chrysler's three-year contract expires sept. 14. talks normally begin in mid-july, but chrysler asked for the early start after the uaw forced it to reverse a plan to sell its 28,000-worker acustar inc. parts subsidiary
in cooperative union-management programs that reach from the executive suite to the plant floor, the two sides have begun working together to find ways to improve chrysler's production quality and efficiency
they are considered crucial to the survival of any auto company battling for its share of an intensely competitive market. but ``negotiations tend to put everything into a kind of holding pattern,'' st. john said
chrysler will work within the job-protecting pattern contracts established for the industry last fall at ford motor co. and general motors corp., but will try to mold the pattern to chrysler's needs, he said. up 7th graf, while high...</note>
the nation's factories, mines and utilities operated at 82.4 percent of capacity in february, the third consecutive month the operating rate has been at that level, the federal reserve said thursday
even though the february rate was the same as december and january, those two months were revised up slightly in the newest report, a fact that private economists said was encouraging
slowly, but surely, capacity utilization is marching higher, showing that the industrial sector remains strong,'' said allen sinai, chief economist of the boston co
before the revision, the operating rate in december and january had been put at 82.2 percent
the report said that the february operating rate was held back by further cutbacks in production at auto plants and a big drop in coal production
before the year began, analysts expressed fears that the economy could weaken significantly due to widespread cutbacks in production as businesses tried to work off a huge supply of unsold goods which had been built up in the last part of 1987
while high inventories have led to cuts in auto production, many other industries, such as textiles, chemicals, and paper, have continued to have high operating rates
analysts have recently been boosting their forecasts for growth in the first quarter of 1988 based on a belief that the weakness from production cutbacks was overstated
manufacturing, which was in a virtual recession in 1985 and 1986 because of the country's large trade deficit, began to rebound last year as the weaker dollar made american products competitive once again on overseas markets
continued strength in manufacturing this year is expected to be the principal force keeping the country out of a recession
the 82.4 percent industrial operating rate is the highest overall operating rate since march 1980. the operating rate plunged to 69.5 percent during the depths of the 1981-82 recession
in february, the operating rate at manufacturing plants remained unchanged at 82.4 percent of capacity, reflecting an operating rate of 80.1 percent at factories making durable goods and a production rate of 85.9 percent of capacity at plants making nondurable goods
paper, a non-durable good, had the highest operating rate of any industry at 95.8 percent of capacity, with textile plants close behind at 91.9 percent and chemical plants at 86.5 percent
auto plants operated at 77 percent of capacity in february, down from 77.4 percent in january and a full 5 percentage points below the operating rate in october. sales have rebounded in recent weeks and analysts believe that auto operating rates should start to move higher
the mining industry operated at 80.6 percent of capacity in february, down from 81.1 percent in january. the decline was attributed to a drop in production at coal mines
u.s. utilities operated at 82.2 percent of capacity last month, up from 81.7 percent in january
the overall operating rate of 82.4 percent was more than two percentage points higher than the 79.7 percent operating rate in february 1987
south korea is considering making an infusion of money to the international monetary fund's lending operations, the finance ministry said thursday
ministry officials said the proposed funds would be for the imf's structural adjustment facility, which extends loans to help finance economic development in the third world
officials said the government had not decided how much korea should provide, but that the sum might be close to the $90 million cited in local news reports
ministry officials also said the government was studying additional capital subscriptions to the imf, the world bank and the asian development bank in response to requests from the three organizations. but they said the size of the capital contributions remained to be negotiated
